  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Patient welfare: the surgeon's unwavering compass.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, which accurately identifies one of the three foundational principles of the ACS Code of Professional Conduct. This code, based on the Charter of Medical Professionalism, guides ethical surgical practice by prioritizing patient welfare above all else.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe ACS Code of Professional Conduct, adopted in 2002, is built upon three core principles. The first principle, as stated in option A, emphasizes the physician's unwavering dedication to the patient’s welfare, ensuring that financial, societal, or administrative pressures do not compromise care. The second principle is respect for patient autonomy, requiring honesty and comprehensive information for informed decision-making. The third principle is the promotion of justice within the healthcare system, advocating for equitable access and eliminating discrimination. These principles collectively form the ethical bedrock for surgeons.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Reasonable reimbursement for expert witness testimony is a professional ethical consideration but not one of the three core principles of the ACS Code of Professional Conduct.\nOption C (Incorrect): While accepting patients regardless of ability to pay aligns with ethical practice and the broader principle of justice, it is not explicitly listed as one of the three foundational principles of the ACS Code of Professional Conduct.\nOption D (Incorrect): Referring patients due to conflicts of interest is a crucial ethical practice for maintaining professional integrity, but it is a specific application of professional responsibility rather than one of the three overarching principles of the ACS Code of Professional Conduct.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Principle | Description |\n|---|---|\n| Dedication to Patient Welfare | Patient's well-being supersedes financial, societal, or administrative forces. |\n| Respect for Patient Autonomy | Honesty and full disclosure to enable informed patient decisions. |\n| Promotion of Justice | Advocating for equitable healthcare access and eliminating discrimination. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ACS Code: Patient Welfare, Autonomy, Justice.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable; this question pertains to medical ethics and professional conduct, not imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Code of Professional Conduct (2002). This code endorsed the Charter of Medical Professionalism, establishing three core principles for surgical practice.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dedication to the patient’s welfare, independent of administrative forces | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Reasonable reimbursement for testifying as an expert witness | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Accepting patients, regardless of ability to pay | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Referring patients to other doctors when conflicts do not allow the surgeon | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The ACS endorsed the Charter of Medical Professionalism as its Code of Professional Conduct in 2002.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
