  "question": "Cortisol is elevated in response to severe injury. How long can this response persist in a patient with a significant burn?",
  "options": {
    "A": "2 days",
    "B": "1 week",
    "C": "1 month",
    "D": "3 months"
  },
  "answer": "C) Cortisol is a glucocorticoid steroid hormone released by the adrenal cortex in response to ACTH. Cortisol release is increased during times of stress and may be chronically elevated in certain disease processes. For example, burn-injured patients may exhibit elevated levels for 4 weeks. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 18.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Burn stress: Cortisol's month-long marathon, not a sprint.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 1 month. Cortisol, a key stress hormone, remains significantly elevated for an extended period following severe burn injury, reflecting the body's profound and prolonged catabolic and inflammatory response.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSevere burn injury triggers a profound neuroendocrine stress response, primarily mediated by the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. This leads to sustained elevation of cortisol, a glucocorticoid, which mobilizes energy stores, suppresses inflammation (initially), and maintains cardiovascular stability. However, chronic elevation contributes to muscle wasting, immunosuppression, and impaired wound healing. The duration of this hypercortisolemia, up to 4 weeks (1 month), underscores the prolonged metabolic derangement and catabolic state in burn patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 2 days is too short for the sustained stress response seen in significant burns.\nOption B (Incorrect): 1 week is insufficient to cover the prolonged catabolic state and inflammatory response following severe burn injury.\nOption D (Incorrect): 3 months is generally too long for the primary phase of elevated cortisol, although some metabolic derangements can persist. The peak elevation typically subsides by 4 weeks.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Stimulus | Duration of Elevation (Severe Injury) | Primary Effect |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cortisol | ACTH (stress) | Up to 4 weeks | Glucose mobilization, anti-inflammatory (initially), catabolism |\n| Catecholamines (Epi/Norepi) | Sympathetic activation | Days to weeks | Tachycardia, vasoconstriction, increased metabolic rate |\n| Glucagon | Stress, low insulin | Days to weeks | Glucose production, catabolism |\n| Growth Hormone | Stress, injury | Days to weeks | Anabolic (initially), counter-regulatory |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Severe burns cause prolonged cortisol elevation, driving catabolism for up to a month.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile direct imaging of cortisol levels isn't standard, patients with prolonged hypercortisolism might show signs like muscle wasting, impaired wound healing, or increased susceptibility to infection, which could be observed clinically or indirectly on imaging (e.g., muscle atrophy on CT).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Burn Association (ABA) Practice Guidelines for Burn Care (e.g., 2018). These guidelines emphasize metabolic support and management of the hypermetabolic response, which includes understanding the duration of hormonal changes like cortisol elevation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2 days | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 1 week | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 1 month | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 3 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Cortisol is a glucocorticoid steroid hormone released by the adrenal cortex in response to ACTH. Cor** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
