  "question": "Which of the following is found in patients with adrenal insufficiency?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Hyperglycemia",
    "B": "Hyperkalemia",
    "C": "Hypercalcemia",
    "D": "Hypernatremia"
  },
  "answer": "D) Laboratory findings in adrenal insufficiency include hypoglycemia from decreased gluconeogenesis, hyponatremia from impaired renal tubular sodium resorption, and hyperkalemia from diminished kaliuresis. Calcium levels are not typically affected by adrenal insufficiency. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 19.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let adrenal insufficiency catch you off guard; check those electrolytes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hyperkalemia. Adrenal insufficiency, particularly primary adrenal insufficiency, leads to decreased mineralocorticoid (aldosterone) production, which impairs renal potassium excretion, resulting in hyperkalemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdrenal insufficiency is characterized by deficient production of adrenal hormones, primarily cortisol and aldosterone. Aldosterone deficiency leads to impaired sodium reabsorption and potassium excretion in the renal tubules, causing hyponatremia and hyperkalemia. Cortisol deficiency impairs gluconeogenesis, leading to hypoglycemia. These electrolyte and metabolic derangements are critical diagnostic markers for this condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hyperglycemia. Adrenal insufficiency typically causes hypoglycemia due to decreased cortisol-mediated gluconeogenesis and increased insulin sensitivity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hypercalcemia. Calcium levels are generally not directly affected by adrenal insufficiency.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hypernatremia. Adrenal insufficiency causes hyponatremia due to impaired renal tubular sodium resorption secondary to aldosterone deficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lab Finding | Adrenal Insufficiency Effect | Reason |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sodium | Hyponatremia | Impaired renal tubular sodium resorption (aldosterone deficiency) |\n| Potassium | Hyperkalemia | Diminished renal potassium excretion (aldosterone deficiency) |\n| Glucose | Hypoglycemia | Decreased gluconeogenesis (cortisol deficiency) |\n| Calcium | Unaffected | Not directly regulated by adrenal hormones |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adrenal insufficiency: low Na, high K, low glucose.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, bilateral adrenal enlargement may be seen in autoimmune adrenalitis (early) or infiltrative diseases (e.g., tuberculosis, metastases). Atrophy may be seen in chronic autoimmune disease. Intraoperatively, if an adrenalectomy is performed, the remaining adrenal tissue's function must be carefully monitored to prevent iatrogenic insufficiency.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Primary Adrenal Insufficiency (2016) recommends measuring morning cortisol, ACTH, and plasma renin activity/aldosterone for diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hyperglycemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hyperkalemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypercalcemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypernatremia | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Laboratory findings in adrenal insufficiency include hypoglycemia from decreased gluconeogenesis, hy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
