  "question": "If 1 liter of 0.9% NaCl solution is given intravenously, how much will be distributed to the interstitial space?",
  "options": {
    "A": "100 cc",
    "B": "250 cc",
    "C": "400 cc",
    "D": "750 cc"
  },
  "answer": "D) Sodium is confined to the extracellular fluid (ECF) compartment, and because of its osmotic and electrical properties, it remains associated with water. Therefore, sodium-containing fluids are distributed throughout the ECF and add to the volume of both the intravascular and interstitial spaces. Although the administration of sodium-containing fluids expands the intravascular volume, it also expands the interstitial space by approximately three times as much as the plasma. One liter of normal saline will be distributed 3:1 to the interstitial space. Therefore, 750 ml will be distributed to the interstitial space and 250 ml will remain in the intravascular volume. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 53.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Normal saline: 75% interstitial, 25% intravascular. Remember the 3:1 rule!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, 750 cc. This question assesses understanding of fluid distribution principles, specifically how isotonic saline (0.9% NaCl) distributes within the extracellular fluid (ECF) compartment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNormal saline is an isotonic solution, meaning its osmolality is similar to plasma. Sodium, the primary osmotically active solute in normal saline, is largely confined to the extracellular fluid (ECF) compartment. Due to its osmotic properties, water follows sodium. The ECF is composed of two main sub-compartments: the intravascular space (plasma) and the interstitial space. When 1 liter of 0.9% NaCl is administered, it distributes throughout the entire ECF. The physiological distribution ratio for isotonic saline between the interstitial and intravascular spaces is approximately 3:1. Therefore, 75% of the administered volume goes to the interstitial space, and 25% remains in the intravascular space.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (100 cc) (Incorrect): This volume is significantly less than what would be distributed to the interstitial space, not reflecting the 3:1 ECF distribution.\nOption B (250 cc) (Incorrect): This volume represents the approximate amount that would remain in the intravascular space (25% of 1 liter), not the interstitial space.\nOption C (400 cc) (Incorrect): This volume is too low for the interstitial distribution and does not align with the physiological 3:1 ECF distribution ratio.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fluid Type | Primary Distribution | Interstitial % | Intravascular % |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 0.9% NaCl (Isotonic) | Extracellular Fluid (ECF) | ~75% | ~25% |\n| D5W (Hypotonic after metabolism) | Total Body Water (TBW) | ~66% | ~8% |\n| Albumin (Colloid) | Intravascular Fluid | ~0% | ~100% |\n| Lactated Ringer's (Isotonic) | Extracellular Fluid (ECF) | ~75% | ~25% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal saline expands interstitial space 3x more than intravascular.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., CT, X-ray), excessive interstitial fluid administration can manifest as pulmonary edema (interstitial or alveolar patterns) or peripheral edema (soft tissue swelling). Intraoperatively, this can be observed as tissue boggy-ness or increased serous fluid in surgical fields.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Perioperative Fluid Management (2020): Recommends individualized fluid therapy, often starting with balanced crystalloids, and emphasizes avoiding excessive positive fluid balance to prevent interstitial edema.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 100 cc | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 250 cc | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 400 cc | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 750 cc | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Sodium is confined to the extracellular fluid (ECF) compartment, and because of its osmotic and elec** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
