  "question": "The approximate IVrate for maintenance fluids for a 50-kg patient would be",
  "options": {
    "A": "75 ml/hr",
    "B": "90 ml/hr",
    "C": "105 ml/hr",
    "D": "120 ml/hr"
  },
  "answer": "B) Once the daily total is established, dividing by 24 will give an approximate hourly rate. Alternatively, dividing by 25 (instead of 24) gives a rapid approximate rate. In other words, the hourly IVrate will be 4 ml/kg/hour for the 1st 10 kg 2 ml/kg/hour for the 2nd 10 kg 1 ml/kg/hour for each kg >20 kg In this example, 4 × 10 = 40 (for the 1st 10 kg), 2 × 10 = 20 (for the 2nd 10 kg), and 1 × 30 = 30 (for the remaining kg). 40 + 20 + 30 = 90 ml/hr. (The number if one divides by 24 instead of 25 is 87.5 ml/hr.) (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 63.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hydration math: 4-2-1 keeps patients running right.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 90 ml/hr, which is derived from the standard \"4-2-1 rule\" for calculating maintenance fluid requirements. This formula accurately estimates the hourly intravenous fluid rate needed to maintain hydration and electrolyte balance in a 50-kg patient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Holliday-Segar formula, commonly known as the \"4-2-1 rule,\" is a fundamental principle for calculating maintenance fluid requirements. It accounts for basal metabolic water loss and insensible losses, providing 4 ml/kg/hr for the first 10 kg, 2 ml/kg/hr for the next 10 kg, and 1 ml/kg/hr for every kilogram thereafter. For a 50-kg patient, this translates to (4 ml/kg * 10 kg) + (2 ml/kg * 10 kg) + (1 ml/kg * 30 kg) = 40 + 20 + 30 = 90 ml/hr, ensuring physiological fluid balance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 75 ml/hr is significantly lower than the calculated maintenance rate, risking under-hydration and potential electrolyte disturbances for a 50-kg patient.\nOption C (Incorrect): 105 ml/hr is higher than the physiological maintenance requirement, increasing the risk of fluid overload, dilutional hyponatremia, and pulmonary edema.\nOption D (Incorrect): 120 ml/hr is substantially above the appropriate maintenance rate, posing a significant risk of fluid overload complications, especially in patients with compromised cardiac or renal function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Weight Range | Hourly Rate (ml/kg/hr) | Calculation for 50 kg Patient |\n|---|---|---|\n| First 10 kg | 4 | 4 ml/kg/hr * 10 kg = 40 ml/hr |\n| Next 10 kg | 2 | 2 ml/kg/hr * 10 kg = 20 ml/hr |\n| > 20 kg | 1 | 1 ml/kg/hr * 30 kg = 30 ml/hr |\n| Total for 50 kg | N/A | 40 + 20 + 30 = 90 ml/hr |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the 4-2-1 rule: 4 for 1st 10, 2 for 2nd 10, 1 for rest.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile direct imaging is not typically used for maintenance fluid calculation, clinical assessment of hydration status is crucial. Look for signs like skin turgor, mucous membrane moisture, urine output, and vital signs (heart rate, blood pressure). A chest X-ray might reveal pulmonary edema in cases of fluid overload.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition (ASPEN) guidelines (e.g., 2014) provide recommendations for intravenous fluid therapy, including maintenance fluid calculations based on patient weight and clinical status.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 75 ml/hr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 90 ml/hr | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 105 ml/hr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 120 ml/hr | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Once the daily total is established, dividing by 24 will give an approximate hourly rate. Alternativ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
