  "id": 120061,
  "question": "Which of the following is required for platelet adherence to exposed areas of an injured vessel?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Prothrombin",
    "B": "von Willebrand factor",
    "C": "Glycoprotein IX",
    "D": "Prostaglandin GI2"
  },
  "answer": "B) Platelets do not normally adhere to each other or to the vessel wall but can form a plug that aids in cessation of bleeding when vascular disruption occurs. Injury to the intimal layer in the vascular wall exposes subendothelial collagen to which platelets adhere. This process requires von Willebrand’s factor (vWF), a protein in the subendothelium that is lacking in patients with von Willebrand’s disease. The vWF binds to glycoprotein I/IX/V on the platelet membrane. After adhesion, platelets initiate a release reaction that recruits other platelets from the circulating blood to seal the disrupted vessel. Up to this point, this process is known as primary hemostasis. Prothrombin initiates the common phase of the coagulation cascade, which occurs after primary hemostasis. Prostaglandin GI is a vasodilator and inhibits platelet aggregation. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 68.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No vWF, no stick; bleeding won't quit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, von Willebrand factor. This protein is absolutely required for the initial adherence of platelets to the exposed subendothelial collagen of an injured vessel, which is the critical first step in primary hemostasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPlatelets normally circulate freely, but upon vascular injury, the disruption of the endothelial layer exposes subendothelial collagen. von Willebrand factor (vWF), a large multimeric glycoprotein found in the subendothelium and plasma, acts as a crucial molecular bridge. It binds simultaneously to the exposed collagen and to the glycoprotein Ib/IX/V complex on the platelet surface. This binding mediates the initial platelet adhesion, forming the foundation for the subsequent platelet plug and initiating the process of primary hemostasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Prothrombin is a precursor to thrombin and is central to the coagulation cascade (secondary hemostasis), which occurs after primary platelet adherence. It is not directly involved in initial platelet adherence.\nOption C (Incorrect): Glycoprotein IX is part of the GPIb/IX/V complex on the platelet membrane, which serves as the receptor for vWF. While essential for the platelet to bind, vWF itself is the factor required for adherence to the vessel wall, acting as the ligand.\nOption D (Incorrect): Prostaglandin GI2 (prostacyclin) is produced by endothelial cells and acts as a potent vasodilator and inhibitor of platelet aggregation. Its role is to prevent platelet adherence and promote blood flow, not to facilitate adherence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Role in Hemostasis | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| von Willebrand Factor (vWF) | Mediates platelet adhesion to subendothelial collagen | Deficiency causes von Willebrand Disease (most common inherited bleeding disorder) |\n| Prothrombin | Precursor to thrombin, central to coagulation cascade | Deficiency impairs fibrin clot formation, increasing bleeding risk |\n| Glycoprotein Ib/IX/V | Platelet receptor for vWF | Defect causes Bernard-Soulier Syndrome (platelet adhesion defect) |\n| Prostaglandin GI2 (PGI2) | Inhibits platelet aggregation and causes vasodilation | Produced by healthy endothelium to prevent thrombosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: vWF is the sticky bridge for platelets to injured vessels.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, an injured vessel will show active bleeding. In patients with von Willebrand disease, the initial platelet plug formation may be delayed or ineffective, leading to prolonged oozing from surgical sites or diffuse mucosal bleeding, requiring specific hemostatic agents like desmopressin or vWF concentrate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2021 Guidelines for the Management of von Willebrand Disease. These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, treatment, and management strategies, including surgical prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prothrombin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | von Willebrand factor | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Glycoprotein IX | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prostaglandin GI2 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Platelets do not normally adhere to each other or to the vessel wall but can form a plug that aids i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
