  "question": "Which of the following drugs irreversibly inhibits platelet COX (cyclo-oxygenase)?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Ibuprofen",
    "B": "Clopidogrel",
    "C": "Aspirin",
    "D": "Celebrex"
  },
  "answer": "C) Arachidonic acid released from the platelet membranes is converted by COX to prostaglandin G2(PGG2) and then to prostaglandin H2(PGH2), which, in turn, is converted to TXA2. TXA2 has potent vasoconstriction and platelet aggregation effects. Arachidonic acid may also be shuttled to adjacent endothelial cells and converted to prostacyclin (PGI2), which is a vasodilator and acts to inhibit platelet aggregation. Platelet COX is irreversibly inhibited by aspirin and reversibly blocked by NSAIDs but is not affected by COX-2 inhibitors. Ibuprofen is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) and reversibly affects platelet COX. Both aspirin and clopidogrel irreversibly inhibit platelet function, clopidogrel through selective irreversible inhibition of ADP-induced platelet aggregation and aspirin through irreversible acetylation of platelet prostaglandin synthase. Celebrex is a COX-2 inhibitor and therefore does not affect platelet COX. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 68.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Aspirin: The irreversible antiplatelet, a platelet's last stand.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAspirin is the correct answer because it irreversibly inhibits platelet cyclo-oxygenase (COX-1), preventing the synthesis of thromboxane A2 (TXA2) and thus inhibiting platelet aggregation. This mechanism is distinct from other antiplatelet agents and NSAIDs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAspirin achieves its antiplatelet effect by acetylating a serine residue in the active site of platelet COX-1. This irreversible inhibition means that the platelet cannot synthesize new COX-1, and its antiplatelet effect lasts for the lifetime of the platelet (7-10 days). This sustained inhibition of TXA2 production is crucial for its role in preventing arterial thrombosis, myocardial infarction, and stroke.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Ibuprofen) (Incorrect): Ibuprofen is a non-selective NSAID that reversibly inhibits COX enzymes, meaning its antiplatelet effect is temporary and ceases once the drug is metabolized.\nOption B (Clopidogrel) (Incorrect): Clopidogrel is an antiplatelet drug, but it acts by irreversibly blocking the P2Y12 ADP receptor on platelets, not by inhibiting COX.\nOption D (Celebrex) (Incorrect): Celebrex (celecoxib) is a selective COX-2 inhibitor. Platelet aggregation is primarily mediated by COX-1, so COX-2 inhibitors have minimal to no effect on platelet function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drug Class | Example | Mechanism of Action | Effect on Platelets | Reversibility |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Irreversible COX-1 Inhibitor | Aspirin | Irreversible acetylation of COX-1 | Inhibits TXA2 synthesis | Irreversible |\n| Non-selective NSAID | Ibuprofen | Reversible inhibition of COX-1 & COX-2 | Reversibly inhibits TXA2 synthesis | Reversible |\n| P2Y12 Inhibitor | Clopidogrel | Irreversible blockade of P2Y12 ADP receptor | Inhibits ADP-induced aggregation | Irreversible |\n| Selective COX-2 Inhibitor | Celebrex | Selective inhibition of COX-2 | Minimal/No effect on platelet aggregation | Reversible |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Aspirin's antiplatelet effect is permanent for the platelet's lifespan.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, patients on aspirin may have increased bleeding risk, requiring careful hemostasis. Preoperative cessation of aspirin is often considered, balancing thrombotic risk vs. bleeding risk.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Cardiology/American Heart Association (ACC/AHA) 2017 Perioperative Management of Patients With Cardiovascular Disease Undergoing Noncardiac Surgery. It recommends individualized assessment for continuing or discontinuing aspirin based on thrombotic and bleeding risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ibuprofen | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Clopidogrel | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Aspirin | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Celebrex | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Arachidonic acid released from the platelet membranes is converted by COX to prostaglandin G2(PGG2) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
