  "answer": "C) A third major mechanism of inhibition of thrombin formation is the protein C system. On its formation, thrombin binds to thrombomodulin and activates protein C to activated protein C (APC), which then forms a complex with its cofactor, protein S, on a phospholipid surface. The APC–protein S complex cleaves factors Va and VIIIa so they are no longer able to participate in the formation of tissue factor–VIIa or prothrombinase complexes. Of interest is an inherited form of factor V that carries a genetic mutation, called factor V Leiden, that is resistant to cleavage by APC and thus remains active (procoagulant). Patients with factor V Leiden are predisposed to venous thromboembolic events. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 70.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Factor V Leiden: Can't turn off the clot switch!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because Factor V Leiden is a genetic mutation that renders Factor Va resistant to inactivation by activated protein C (APC), thereby prolonging its procoagulant activity and predisposing to thrombosis. This resistance to inactivation is the core mechanism behind the thrombotic tendency.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe normal coagulation cascade involves the protein C system as a crucial anticoagulant pathway. Thrombin, upon binding to thrombomodulin, activates protein C to activated protein C (APC). APC, in complex with protein S, cleaves and inactivates factors Va and VIIIa, effectively downregulating thrombin formation. In Factor V Leiden, a specific point mutation (Arg506Gln) in factor V prevents this critical cleavage by APC, allowing factor Va to remain active for a longer duration. This sustained activity of factor Va significantly enhances the prothrombinase complex, leading to increased thrombin generation and a hypercoagulable state.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Factor V Leiden does not lead to inadequate production of factor V; the issue is with its inactivation.\nOption B (Incorrect): The mutation does not cause overproduction of factor V; rather, it impairs its breakdown.\nOption D (Incorrect): Factor V needs to be activated to factor Va to participate in coagulation. The problem in Factor V Leiden is the *inability to inactivate* the active form (Va), not an inability to activate it.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Thrombophilia | Mechanism | Clinical Manifestation |\n|---|---|---|\n| Factor V Leiden | Resistance to inactivation by Activated Protein C (APC) | Venous thromboembolism (VTE), DVT, PE |\n| Protein C Deficiency | Reduced levels or function of Protein C | VTE, warfarin-induced skin necrosis |\n| Protein S Deficiency | Reduced levels or function of Protein S | VTE |\n| Antithrombin Deficiency | Reduced levels or function of Antithrombin | VTE, heparin resistance |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Factor V Leiden means Factor Va stays active, leading to clots.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, you might see a non-compressible vein with intraluminal thrombus in a patient presenting with DVT. For pulmonary embolism, CT pulmonary angiography (CTPA) would show filling defects in the pulmonary arteries.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2020 guidelines for management of venous thromboembolism: These guidelines recommend against routine thrombophilia testing for all VTE patients, but suggest considering it in specific scenarios, such as unprovoked VTE in young patients or those with a strong family history, to guide duration of anticoagulation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Leads to inadequate production of factor V | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Leads to overproduction of factor V | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Leads to an inability to inactivate factor V | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Leads to an inability to activate factor V | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) A third major mechanism of inhibition of thrombin formation is the protein C system. On its formatio** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
