  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 C for C: Hemophilia C is Factor XI deficiency, not X-linked!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies Factor XI as the deficient factor in Hemophilia C. This condition, also known as Rosenthal syndrome, is distinct from Hemophilia A and B, which involve Factor VIII and IX, respectively.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemophilia C, or Factor XI deficiency, is an autosomal recessive inherited bleeding disorder, notably more prevalent in the Ashkenazi Jewish population. Unlike Hemophilia A and B, spontaneous bleeding is rare; however, patients are at risk for significant bleeding following surgery, trauma, or invasive procedures. Management often involves fresh-frozen plasma (FFP) to replace Factor XI, with recombinant Factor VIIa or desmopressin acetate as alternative treatments, especially for severe cases or surgical prophylaxis. Understanding the specific factor deficiency is crucial for appropriate diagnosis and management of bleeding disorders.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Factor VIII deficiency causes Hemophilia A, the most common type of hemophilia.\nOption B (Incorrect): Factor IX deficiency causes Hemophilia B, also known as Christmas disease.\nOption C (Incorrect): Factor X deficiency is a rare bleeding disorder, but it is not referred to as Hemophilia C.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hemophilia Type | Deficient Factor | Inheritance Pattern |\n|------------------|------------------|---------------------|\n| Hemophilia A     | Factor VIII      | X-linked recessive  |\n| Hemophilia B     | Factor IX        | X-linked recessive  |\n| Hemophilia C     | Factor XI        | Autosomal recessive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hemophilia C = Factor XI deficiency, autosomal recessive, Ashkenazi Jewish.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a patient with undiagnosed or poorly managed Hemophilia C might exhibit diffuse oozing from surgical sites, prolonged bleeding despite meticulous hemostasis, or the rapid formation of hematomas in the surgical field.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Federation of Hemophilia (WFH) Guidelines for the Management of Hemophilia (2020): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis and management of all hemophilias, including Factor XI deficiency, covering treatment strategies like FFP, rFVIIa, and desmopressin for bleeding episodes and surgical prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Factor VIII | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Factor IX | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Factor X | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Factor XI | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Factor XI deficiency, an autosomal recessive inherited condition sometimes referred to as hemophilia** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
