  "answer": "A) One unit of platelet concentrate contains approximately 5.5 × 1010 platelets and would be expected to increase the circulating platelet count by approximately 10,000/μLin the average 70-kg person. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 74.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 1 unit, 10K rise: Simple math for platelet life.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 10,000. This is a fundamental concept in transfusion medicine, indicating the expected physiological response to a single unit of platelet concentrate in an average adult. Understanding this baseline is crucial for managing thrombocytopenia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPlatelet transfusions are a critical intervention for patients with thrombocytopenia or platelet dysfunction, particularly in surgical settings to prevent or control bleeding. A standard unit of platelet concentrate contains approximately 5.5 x 10^10 platelets. In a 70-kg patient, with an estimated blood volume, this quantity is expected to raise the circulating platelet count by roughly 10,000/μL. This calculation is based on the distribution of transfused platelets within the patient's blood volume and is a key metric for assessing transfusion efficacy and guiding further management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 20,000 is an overestimation for the expected increase from a single unit of random donor platelets. This rise is more typical for a pooled unit or an apheresis unit. \nOption C (Incorrect): 30,000 is significantly higher than the expected increase from one unit of random donor platelets. This level of increase is usually seen with multiple units or an apheresis product. \nOption D (Incorrect): 40,000 is a substantial overestimation for the effect of a single unit of platelets, indicating a misunderstanding of standard transfusion responses.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Platelet Product | Typical Platelet Content | Expected Increase (70kg adult) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Random Donor Platelet (RDP) Unit | ~5.5 x 10^10 platelets | ~10,000/μL |\n| Pooled Platelets (5-6 RDP units) | ~3.0 x 10^11 platelets | ~30,000 - 60,000/μL |\n| Single Donor Apheresis Platelets | ~3.0 x 10^11 platelets | ~30,000 - 60,000/μL |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: One unit of platelets typically raises count by 10,000/μL.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, severe thrombocytopenia (e.g., platelet count <50,000/μL for major surgery) would manifest as diffuse microvascular bleeding, persistent oozing from surgical planes, or petechial hemorrhages in the surgical field, despite adequate surgical hemostasis. Transfusion of platelets would be indicated to improve hemostasis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAABB Clinical Practice Guidelines: Platelet Transfusion for Patients with Hypoproliferative Thrombocytopenia (2018). This guideline recommends prophylactic platelet transfusions to maintain a platelet count of at least 10,000/μL in patients with hypoproliferative thrombocytopenia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 10,000 | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 20,000 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 30,000 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 40,000 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) One unit of platelet concentrate contains approximately 5.5 × 1010 platelets and would be expected t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
