  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Colon surgery: clean-contaminated, but don't underestimate the dirty truth of its SSI risk.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C, 10-25%, is the correct answer. This range accurately reflects the expected surgical site infection (SSI) risk for an elective low anterior colon resection, which is classified as a clean-contaminated procedure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nElective low anterior colon resection involves opening the alimentary tract, specifically the colon, which is rich in indigenous bacterial flora. This classifies it as a clean-contaminated wound (Class II). While historically, clean-contaminated wounds had lower reported SSI rates, recent studies have shown that colorectal surgeries, even elective ones, consistently demonstrate higher SSI rates, often ranging from 9% to 25%. Factors contributing to this include the bacterial load, potential for spillage, and the complexity of the procedure, especially when entering the rectal space. A significant proportion of these infections may manifest post-discharge, underscoring the need for vigilant follow-up.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1-5% is typically associated with clean surgical procedures (Class I), such as hernia repair or breast biopsy, where the alimentary, respiratory, or genitourinary tracts are not entered.\nOption B (Incorrect): 2-10% is still too low for a clean-contaminated procedure like colon resection, which inherently carries a higher bacterial load and risk compared to truly clean cases.\nOption D (Incorrect): >25% would be indicative of a contaminated (Class III) or dirty/infected (Class IV) wound, such as a perforated viscus or an existing abscess, which is not the case for an elective low anterior colon resection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Wound Classification | Description | Typical SSI Rate |\n|--------------------|-------------|------------------|\n| Clean (Class I) | No inflammation, no entry into tracts | 1-5% |\n| Clean-Contaminated (Class II) | Controlled entry into tracts (e.g., GI, GU, Resp) | 5-15% (Colorectal often 9-25%) |\n| Contaminated (Class III) | Acute inflammation, gross spillage, major break in technique | 15-30% |\n| Dirty/Infected (Class IV) | Pre-existing infection, perforated viscus | >30% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Colorectal surgery is clean-contaminated, but its SSI rate is often higher than other Class II cases.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, look for meticulous bowel preparation, minimal spillage, and secure anastomoses. Postoperatively, imaging (CT with contrast) for SSI might reveal anastomotic leaks, intra-abdominal abscesses, or cellulitis at the incision site.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guideline for the Prevention of Surgical Site Infection (2017). Recommends appropriate antimicrobial prophylaxis, optimal glycemic control, and normothermia to reduce SSI risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1-5% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 2-10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 10-25% | ✅ Correct |\n| D | >25% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The expected infection rate in colorectal surgery (clean/contaminated) is 9.4 to 25%. Clean/contamin** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
