  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't underestimate the drip; it can lead to a flood.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 750 mL. This is derived from the understanding that each rib fracture can contribute approximately 100 to 200 mL of blood loss, and for 6 fractures, the cumulative loss falls within this range.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTrauma patients often present with multiple injuries, and while individual injuries might seem minor, their cumulative effect can lead to significant hemodynamic instability. For rib fractures, the blood loss stems from damage to intercostal vessels and surrounding muscle and soft tissue. With 6 rib fractures, the expected blood loss would be between 600 mL (6 x 100 mL) and 1200 mL (6 x 200 mL), making 750 mL a reasonable estimate within this range.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 240 mL is significantly underestimated for 6 rib fractures, as even the lower end of the range (100 mL/rib) would yield 600 mL.\nOption B (Incorrect): 480 mL is also a substantial underestimation, not aligning with the accepted range of blood loss per rib fracture.\nOption D (Incorrect): 1500 mL is an overestimation for 6 isolated rib fractures and is more consistent with blood loss from a femur or pelvic fracture.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Estimated Blood Loss |\n|---|---|\n| Rib Fracture (each) | 100 - 200 mL |\n| Tibial Fracture | 300 - 500 mL |\n| Femur Fracture | 800 - 1000 mL |\n| Pelvic Fracture | >1000 mL |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sum of small bleeds can equal a big problem.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a chest X-ray or CT scan, rib fractures appear as cortical disruptions. Look for associated hemothorax or pneumothorax, which can significantly increase blood loss. Intraoperatively, bleeding from intercostal arteries or veins can be identified and controlled.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons Committee on Trauma (ACS COT) Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) 11th Edition. ATLS emphasizes the importance of recognizing occult blood loss and managing hemorrhagic shock in trauma patients, often due to cumulative injuries.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 240 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 480 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 750 ml | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 1500 ml | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) For each rib fracture there is approximately 100 to 200 mLof blood loss; for tibial fractures, 300 t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
