  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't sweat the small stuff; most adrenal incidentalomas are just benign adenomas.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cortical adenoma. This is because nonfunctional cortical adenomas are overwhelmingly the most frequent type of adrenal mass discovered incidentally on imaging, accounting for a large majority of adrenal incidentalomas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCortical adenomas are benign tumors arising from the adrenal cortex. They are often non-functional, meaning they do not produce excess hormones, which explains why they are frequently discovered incidentally during imaging for unrelated conditions. Their high prevalence (36-94% of incidentalomas) makes them the leading diagnosis in patients without a history of cancer, highlighting their significance in the differential diagnosis of adrenal masses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Adrenal cysts are benign but significantly less common than cortical adenomas as incidental findings.\nOption B (Incorrect): Adrenal hemorrhage is a less common cause of an incidental adrenal mass and often presents with acute symptoms or specific predisposing factors, rather than being a silent incidentaloma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Myelolipomas are benign, fat-containing adrenal tumors, but they are much less common than cortical adenomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Incidentaloma Type | Characteristics | Prevalence |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cortical Adenoma | Benign, often non-functional, low attenuation on CT | 36-94% |\n| Myelolipoma | Benign, contains macroscopic fat, usually non-functional | ~5-10% |\n| Adrenal Cyst | Benign, fluid-filled, well-defined, thin wall | <5% |\n| Pheochromocytoma | Functional (catecholamine-secreting), high attenuation, \"washout\" | ~5% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Most adrenal incidentalomas are benign non-functional cortical adenomas.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a typical cortical adenoma appears as a well-circumscribed, homogeneous mass with low attenuation (<10 Hounsfield Units) on unenhanced imaging due to its high lipid content, and demonstrates rapid contrast washout.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Clinical Endocrinologists (AACE) and American Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Medical Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Incidentalomas (2017). These guidelines provide a comprehensive approach to the diagnostic workup and management of adrenal incidentalomas, emphasizing biochemical evaluation and imaging characteristics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adrenal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Adrenal hemorrhage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cortical adenoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Myelolipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The differential diagnosis of adrenal incidentalomas is shown in Table 38-9. Nonfunctional cortical ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
