  "question": "The most sensitive test to diagnose a pheochromocytoma is",
  "options": {
    "A": "Plasma vanillylmandellic acid (VMA)",
    "B": "Urinary vanillylmandellic acid (VMA)",
    "C": "Plasma metanephrines",
    "D": "Urinary metanephrines"
  },
  "answer": "C) Recent studies have shown that plasma metanephrines are the most reliable tests to identify pheochromocytomas, with sensitivity approaching 100%. Urinary metanephrines are 98% sensitive and also are highly specific for pheochromocytomas, whereas VMA measurements are slightly less sensitive and specific. False-positive VMA tests may result from ingestion of caffeine, raw fruits, or medications (α-methyldopa). Fractionated urinary catecholamines (norepinephrine, epinephrine, and dopamine) also are very sensitive but less specific for pheochromocytomas. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1399.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, check plasma metanephrines out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Plasma metanephrines. Recent studies have established plasma metanephrines as the most reliable and sensitive test for diagnosing pheochromocytoma, with sensitivity approaching 100%.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPheochromocytomas continuously metabolize catecholamines (epinephrine and norepinephrine) within the tumor cells into metanephrines (metanephrine and normetanephrine) via catechol-O-methyltransferase (COMT). These metanephrines are then released into the circulation. Because this metabolism occurs *within* the tumor, plasma metanephrine levels reflect the sustained, unregulated production of these metabolites, providing a more consistent and sensitive indicator of tumor presence compared to episodic catecholamine release or urinary excretion of metabolites.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Plasma vanillylmandellic acid (VMA)): Incorrect. Plasma VMA is not a standard or highly sensitive test for pheochromocytoma. VMA is a downstream metabolite and its plasma measurement is not as reliable as metanephrines.\nOption B (Urinary vanillylmandellic acid (VMA)): Incorrect. Urinary VMA measurements are less sensitive and specific than metanephrines and are prone to false positives from dietary factors (e.g., caffeine, raw fruits) and certain medications (e.g., α-methyldopa).\nOption D (Urinary metanephrines): Incorrect. While highly sensitive (98%) and specific, urinary metanephrines are slightly less sensitive than plasma metanephrines (approaching 100%). They also require a 24-hour collection, which can be prone to errors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Sensitivity | Specificity | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Plasma Free Metanephrines | ~100% | High | Most sensitive, reflects continuous tumor metabolism |\n| Urinary Fractionated Metanephrines | 98% | High | Excellent, but slightly less sensitive than plasma; requires 24-hr collection |\n| Urinary VMA | Lower | Lower | Prone to false positives (diet, meds); less reliable |\n| Fractionated Urinary Catecholamines | Very sensitive | Less specific | Can be elevated in stress, other conditions; less specific than metanephrines |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Plasma metanephrines: the gold standard for pheo screening.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, pheochromocytomas typically appear as well-circumscribed, highly vascular adrenal masses. They often show high signal intensity on T2-weighted MRI and avid contrast enhancement on CT. Intraoperatively, they are usually reddish-brown, encapsulated, and highly vascular, requiring careful dissection to avoid hypertensive crises.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma (2014, updated 2022). Recommends initial biochemical testing with measurement of plasma free metanephrines or urinary fractionated metanephrines, with plasma free metanephrines preferred in high-probability patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Plasma vanillylmandellic acid (VMA) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Urinary vanillylmandellic acid (VMA) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Plasma metanephrines | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Urinary metanephrines | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Recent studies have shown that plasma metanephrines are the most reliable tests to identify pheochro** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
