  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, stick a needle in it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA) because it is the most accurate and cost-effective initial diagnostic test for stratifying the risk of malignancy in a solitary thyroid nodule. It directly assesses the cellular pathology, guiding subsequent management decisions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFine Needle Aspiration (FNA) is a minimally invasive procedure that obtains cells directly from the thyroid nodule for cytological examination. Its high sensitivity and specificity allow for accurate differentiation between benign and malignant lesions, thereby preventing unnecessary surgeries for benign nodules and facilitating timely intervention for cancerous ones. This direct cellular assessment is superior to imaging or functional studies for initial malignancy risk stratification.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Radioactive iodine scan is primarily used to assess the functional status of a nodule (hot vs. cold) and is typically performed after malignancy risk has been assessed, especially for hyperfunctioning nodules. It does not directly diagnose malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): CT or MRI are advanced imaging modalities used for staging known malignancies, assessing local invasion, or evaluating substernal extension, not for the initial diagnosis of malignancy in a solitary thyroid nodule. Ultrasound is the preferred initial imaging.\nOption D (Incorrect): Core needle biopsy is more invasive than FNA and is generally reserved for cases where FNA is non-diagnostic or when specific architectural information is required, such as in lymphoma or anaplastic carcinoma. FNA is the standard first-line biopsy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Diagnostic Test | Primary Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ultrasound** | Initial imaging, guide FNA | Non-invasive, real-time, risk stratification features | Operator dependent, not diagnostic alone |\n| **Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA)** | **First-line diagnosis of malignancy** | High accuracy, minimally invasive, cost-effective | Non-diagnostic rate, requires experienced cytopathologist |\n| **Radioactive Iodine Scan** | Assess functional status (hot/cold) | Differentiates hyperfunctioning from non-functioning | Exposure to radiation, not for initial malignancy diagnosis |\n| **CT/MRI** | Staging, local invasion, substernal extension | Detailed anatomical information | Radiation (CT), cost, not for initial malignancy diagnosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: FNA is the gold standard for initial thyroid nodule malignancy risk assessment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, suspicious thyroid nodules often appear hypoechoic, have irregular margins, microcalcifications, or a taller-than-wide shape. Intraoperatively, a malignant nodule may feel firm, fixed, or show capsular invasion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015: Recommend ultrasound-guided FNA as the primary diagnostic tool for thyroid nodules meeting specific size and suspicious sonographic criteria.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radioactive iodine scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT or MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fine needle aspiration | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Core needle biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) FNAB has become the single most important test in the evaluation of thyroid masses and can be perfor** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
