  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Growing a human is hungry work!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 110 kcal/kg/day. This caloric intake is essential to meet the high metabolic demands of a newborn infant, supporting rapid growth, development, and basic physiological functions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNewborn infants have a significantly higher metabolic rate per unit of body weight compared to older children and adults. This elevated caloric requirement, approximately 110-120 kcal/kg/day, is necessary to fuel rapid cellular proliferation, organ maturation, and the deposition of new tissue. Additionally, a substantial portion of these calories is utilized for thermoregulation, maintaining body temperature in an environment where heat loss can be significant. Adequate caloric intake ensures optimal brain development, immune function, and overall physiological homeostasis during this critical period of rapid growth.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (90 kcal/kg/day) (Incorrect): While close, 90 kcal/kg/day is generally insufficient for optimal growth in a healthy term newborn and may lead to suboptimal weight gain. \nOption C (70 kcal/kg/day) (Incorrect): This caloric intake is significantly below the requirements for a growing newborn and would likely result in failure to thrive and impaired development. \nOption D (55 kcal/kg/day) (Incorrect): This is severely deficient and would lead to severe malnutrition, growth retardation, and significant health complications in a newborn infant.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Population | Caloric Needs (kcal/kg/day) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Term Newborn (for growth) | 110-120 | Supports rapid growth and development |\n| Preterm Infant | 120-150 | Higher needs due to lower reserves, rapid catch-up growth |\n| Adult (basal) | 25-30 | Maintenance, not growth |\n| Surgical Neonate (stressed) | 120-150+ | Increased metabolic demand due to stress, healing |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Newborns need high calories for rapid growth and development.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, signs of inadequate caloric intake in a newborn may include poor weight gain, reduced subcutaneous fat, and delayed bone maturation on X-rays. Intraoperatively, a malnourished infant may exhibit poor tissue integrity and delayed wound healing.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) guidelines for infant nutrition generally recommend 100-120 kcal/kg/day for term infants to support adequate growth and development.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 110 kcal/kg/day | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 90 kcal/kg/day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 70 kcal/kg/day | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 55 kcal/kg/day | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The protein and caloric requirements for the surgical neonate are shown in Table 39-1. (See Schwartz** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
