  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Breast milk: 20 kcal/oz, nature's perfect start!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 20 kcal, which accurately reflects the average caloric density of mature human breast milk. This value is a fundamental concept in pediatric nutrition and critical for assessing infant feeding and growth.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBreast milk is a dynamic biological fluid, with its caloric density primarily derived from fats (lipids), followed by carbohydrates (lactose), and then proteins. While the exact composition can vary based on maternal diet, stage of lactation, and even time of day, the average caloric content is consistently around 0.67 kcal/mL. This translates to approximately 20 kcal per ounce (30 mL), a value optimized for rapid infant growth and development.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 30 kcal is significantly higher than the average caloric density of mature breast milk and would indicate a hypercaloric state if sustained.\nOption C (Incorrect): 42 kcal is an extreme overestimation of breast milk's caloric content, not representative of normal human lactation.\nOption D (Incorrect): 50 kcal is grossly inaccurate and would represent an extremely concentrated or fortified feeding, not natural breast milk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feeding Type | Caloric Density (kcal/oz) | Primary Use |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mature Breast Milk | ~20 | Standard infant nutrition |\n| Standard Infant Formula | ~20 | Alternative to breast milk |\n| Preterm Infant Formula | 22-24 | Enhanced nutrition for premature infants |\n| Fortified Breast Milk | 22-24+ | For preterm or growth-restricted infants |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember 20 kcal/oz for standard breast milk; it's the baseline for infant nutrition.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly imaging, monitoring infant growth curves (weight, length, head circumference) on a growth chart is the primary \"visual\" assessment for adequate caloric intake. Failure to thrive would be a key finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) 2012 Policy Statement on Breastfeeding and the Use of Human Milk. It recommends exclusive breastfeeding for about 6 months, followed by continued breastfeeding with complementary foods for 1 year or longer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 20 kcal | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 30 kcal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 42 kcal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 50 kcal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) There are approximately 0.67 kcal/cc in one mLof breast milk. Therefore, there are about 20 kcals in** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
