  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't miss the midline mover; it's a thyroglossal duct cyst!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 2-4 years of age. Thyroglossal duct cysts are most commonly diagnosed in this age range because the disappearance of baby fat makes neck irregularities, such as the cyst, more readily apparent.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThyroglossal duct cysts are congenital anomalies arising from the incomplete obliteration of the thyroglossal duct, which is the embryological remnant of the thyroid gland's descent from the foramen cecum to its final position. While present from birth, they often remain asymptomatic until later childhood. The characteristic presentation in 2-4 year olds is a midline neck mass, typically at or below the hyoid bone, which uniquely moves superiorly with swallowing or protrusion of the tongue, aiding in its clinical diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While congenital, thyroglossal duct cysts are rarely diagnosed at birth as they are often asymptomatic and not prominent enough to be noticed amidst neonatal neck fat.\nOption B (Incorrect): Diagnosis at 6-9 months is less common than 2-4 years. At this younger age, the neck still retains significant baby fat, which can obscure smaller cysts or make them less noticeable.\nOption D (Incorrect): While some may present later, the peak incidence for diagnosis is earlier, between 2-4 years. By 5-8 years, if present, it would likely have been diagnosed already, or it might be a less common, later presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Branchial Cleft Cyst (2nd) | Cystic Hygroma (Lymphatic Malformation) | Dermoid Cyst |\n| :---------------------- | :--------------------------- | :--------------------------- | :-------------------------------------- | :--------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Midline, often near hyoid | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM | Lateral neck, supraclavicular | Midline, often subcutaneous |\n| **Movement** | With swallowing/tongue prot. | No | No | No |\n| **Age of Diagnosis** | 2-4 years (most common) | Childhood/Adolescence | Birth/Infancy | Childhood |\n| **Embryological Origin**| Thyroglossal duct remnant | Pharyngeal arch remnant | Lymphatic system malformation | Ectodermal/mesodermal inclusion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Midline neck mass moving with tongue protrusion = Thyroglossal duct cyst.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a well-defined, anechoic or hypoechoic midline cyst is typically seen, often with a tract extending towards the foramen cecum. Intraoperatively, the Sistrunk procedure involves excising the cyst, the central portion of the hyoid bone, and the tract up to the foramen cecum to prevent recurrence.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology—Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of the Neck Mass in Children (2019) recommends imaging (ultrasound) for suspected thyroglossal duct cysts and surgical excision (Sistrunk procedure) as definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Birth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 6-9 months of age | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2-4 years of age | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 5-8 years of age | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Thyroglossal duct cysts are most commonly appreciated in the 2- to 4-year-old child when the baby fa** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
