  "id": 120178,
  "question": "A 5-week-old infant presents to the emergency room with bilious vomiting, lethargy, and poor urine output. Following resuscitation, based on the filmin Fig. 39-2, the next intervention should be",
  "options": {
    "A": "NG decompression and observation",
    "B": "Upper GI series",
    "C": "Contrast enema",
    "D": "Laparotomy"
  },
  "answer": "D) Midgut volvulus can occur at any age, although it is seen most often in the first few weeks of life. Bilious vomiting is usually the first sign of volvulus, and all infants with bilious vomiting must be evaluated rapidly to ensure that they do not have intestinal malrotation with volvulus. This diagnosis should be suspected in a child with irritability and bilious emesis. If the condition is left untreated, vascular compromise of the midgut initially causes bloody stools but eventually results in circulatory collapse. Additional clues to the presence of advanced ischemia of the intestine include erythema and edema of the abdominal wall, which progresses to shock and death. It must be re-emphasized that the index of suspicion for this condition must be high, because abdominal signs are minimal in the early stages. Abdominal films show a paucity of gas throughout the intestine with a few scattered air-fluid levels (Fig. 39-2). When these findings are present, the patient should undergo immediate fluid resuscitation to ensure adequate perfusion and urine output, followed by prompt exploratory laparotomy. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1428.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bilious vomit in a baby? Don't delay, operate today!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Laparotomy. In a 5-week-old infant presenting with bilious vomiting, lethargy, and poor urine output, midgut volvulus must be suspected. Following initial resuscitation, immediate surgical exploration is the definitive and life-saving intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBilious vomiting in an infant is a surgical emergency until proven otherwise, especially when accompanied by signs of systemic compromise like lethargy and poor urine output, which suggest shock. Midgut volvulus, a twisting of the bowel around the superior mesenteric artery, can rapidly lead to bowel ischemia, necrosis, and death if not promptly addressed. The urgency stems from the potential for irreversible damage to a large segment of the small intestine, making immediate surgical detorsion and fixation (Ladd procedure) critical to preserve bowel viability and prevent catastrophic outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): NG decompression and observation is dangerously insufficient for suspected midgut volvulus with signs of compromise, as it delays definitive surgical intervention and can lead to irreversible bowel ischemia and death. \nOption B (Incorrect): While an Upper GI series can diagnose malrotation with volvulus (corkscrew sign), performing it in a critically ill infant with bilious vomiting and signs of shock causes dangerous delays in emergent surgical management. \nOption C (Incorrect): A contrast enema is primarily used for distal obstructions (e.g., meconium ileus, Hirschsprung's) and is not the primary diagnostic or therapeutic step for suspected midgut volvulus, especially in a compromised patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Feature | Midgut Volvulus | Pyloric Stenosis | Intussusception |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Age | Neonate/Infant (often <1 month) | 3-6 weeks | 6 months - 3 years |\n| Vomiting | Bilious, rapid onset | Non-bilious, projectile | Non-bilious initially, may become bilious late |\n| Abdominal Exam | Soft, non-distended early; distended, tender late | Olive-shaped mass (epigastric) | Sausage-shaped mass (RUQ), currant jelly stools |\n| Urgency | **Surgical Emergency** | Surgical (elective) | Medical (enema reduction) or Surgical |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilious vomiting in an infant = surgical emergency until proven otherwise. Act fast!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAbdominal films may show a paucity of gas with scattered air-fluid levels. Intraoperatively, a 'whirlpool sign' of twisted mesentery and ischemic, dusky bowel will be evident, requiring immediate detorsion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Pediatric Surgical Association (APSA) guidelines (e.g., 2019 consensus statement on neonatal surgical emergencies) strongly recommend immediate surgical exploration for any infant with bilious emesis and suspected midgut volvulus after initial resuscitation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | NG decompression and observation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Upper GI series | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Contrast enema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Laparotomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Midgut volvulus can occur at any age, although it is seen most often in the first few weeks of life.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
