  "question": "Intestinal duplications are most commonly located in the",
  "options": {
    "A": "Duodenum",
    "B": "Jejunum",
    "C": "Ileum",
    "D": "Colon"
  },
  "answer": "C) Intestinal duplications are mucosa-lined structures that are in continuity with the GI tract. Although they can occur at any level in the GI tract, duplications are found most commonly in the ileum within the leaves of the mesentery. Duplications may be long and tubular, but usually are cystic masses. In all cases, they share a common wall with the intestine. Symptoms associated with enteric duplication cysts include recurrent abdominal pain, emesis from intestinal obstruction, and hematochezia. Such bleeding typically results from ulceration in the duplication or in the adjacent intestine if the duplication contains ectopic gastric mucosa. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1435.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, the ileum's where duplications hang out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the ileum as the most common location for intestinal duplications. These are congenital anomalies that can occur anywhere along the GI tract but have a clear predilection for the distal small bowel.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntestinal duplications are congenital anomalies characterized by mucosa-lined structures that share a common muscular wall with the adjacent intestine and are often in continuity with the GI tract lumen. While they can be tubular, they are most often cystic masses found within the leaves of the mesentery. The presence of ectopic gastric mucosa within the duplication is a critical feature, as it can lead to ulceration, bleeding (hematochezia), and perforation, often presenting with recurrent abdominal pain or intestinal obstruction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Duodenum) (Incorrect): While duplications can occur in the duodenum, they are far less common than in the ileum. Duodenal duplications may present with obstructive symptoms or pancreatitis due to their location near the ampulla.\nOption B (Jejunum) (Incorrect): Jejunum is a possible site for duplications, but the ileum remains the most frequently affected segment of the small intestine.\nOption D (Colon) (Incorrect): Colonic duplications are rare compared to small bowel duplications, particularly those in the ileum. They can present with constipation or an abdominal mass.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Description | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Most Common Site** | Ileum | Guides diagnostic suspicion and surgical planning |\n| **Pathology** | Mucosa-lined, common muscular wall with intestine | Differentiates from mesenteric cysts; risk of ectopic mucosa |\n| **Morphology** | Usually cystic, can be tubular | Cystic forms more common, often within mesentery |\n| **Symptoms** | Abdominal pain, emesis, hematochezia | Often due to obstruction, ulceration from ectopic gastric mucosa |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think ileum first for intestinal duplications; ectopic gastric mucosa is key.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (ultrasound, CT), intestinal duplications typically appear as well-defined, fluid-filled cystic masses adjacent to the bowel wall, often demonstrating a 'double-wall' sign. Intraoperatively, they are found sharing a common muscular wall with the native intestine, often within the mesentery, and may be difficult to separate without resecting a segment of the adjacent bowel.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThere isn't one overarching society guideline specifically for intestinal duplications. Management is typically guided by general pediatric surgical principles and institutional protocols, often referencing standard surgical textbooks like 'Schwartz's Principles of Surgery'.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Duodenum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Jejunum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ileum | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Intestinal duplications are mucosa-lined structures that are in continuity with the GI tract. Althou** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
