  "id": 120186,
  "question": "The expected survival for a patient with Stage IVWilms’ tumor is approximately",
  "options": {
    "A": "5%",
    "B": "33%",
    "C": "50%",
    "D": "80%"
  },
  "answer": "D) Wilms’ tumor is the most common primary malignant tumor of the kidney in children. Approximately 500 new cases are seen annually in the United States, and most are diagnosed in children between 1 and 5 years of age with the peak incidence at age 3. Advances in the care of patients with Wilms’ tumor have resulted in an overall cure rate of roughly 90%, even in the presence of metastatic spread. Essentially, patients who have disease confined to one kidney that is completely excised surgically receive a short course of chemotherapy, and for this group a 97% 4-year survival is expected, with tumor relapse rare after that time. Patients who have more advanced disease or tumors with unfavorable histologic features receive more intensive chemotherapy and radiation therapy. Even in patients with stage IV disease, cure rates of 80% are achieved. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1449.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Wilms' tumor: Stage IV isn't a death sentence; it's a challenge we conquer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The correct answer is D, 80%. This high survival rate for Stage IV Wilms' tumor reflects significant advancements in multimodal treatment strategies, including surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy, which have transformed the prognosis for this pediatric malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWilms' tumor, despite being a malignant pediatric renal tumor, boasts remarkable cure rates due to a highly effective multidisciplinary approach. Surgical resection is often the primary treatment, followed by tailored chemotherapy regimens, and in some cases, radiation therapy. Even with metastatic disease (Stage IV), aggressive treatment protocols have pushed survival rates to approximately 80%, a testament to the efficacy of modern pediatric oncology protocols that combine precise staging, neoadjuvant/adjuvant chemotherapy, and meticulous surgical technique.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 5% is drastically too low and reflects outdated survival statistics from decades ago, prior to the advent of modern multimodal therapy.\nOption B (Incorrect): 33% is also significantly too low and does not accurately represent the current high cure rates achieved for Wilms' tumor, even in advanced stages.\nOption C (Incorrect): 50% is an underestimation of the current survival rates for Stage IV Wilms' tumor, which have improved substantially beyond this figure due to optimized treatment protocols.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Wilms' Tumor Stage | Approximate 4-Year Survival |\n|---|---|\n| Overall | 90% |\n| Stage I (confined to kidney) | 97% |\n| Stage IV (metastatic) | 80% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stage IV Wilms' tumor has an 80% survival, a pediatric oncology success story.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (CT/MRI) typically shows a large, well-circumscribed, heterogeneous renal mass, often with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage, and sometimes calcifications. Intraoperatively, careful dissection is crucial to avoid tumor spillage, and thorough lymph node sampling is performed for accurate staging. Metastases, if present, are most commonly found in the lungs.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) guidelines (e.g., AREN0532, AREN03B2) provide comprehensive recommendations for the staging and treatment of Wilms' tumor, including specific protocols for Stage IV disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 5% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 33% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 80% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Wilms’ tumor is the most common primary malignant tumor of the kidney in children. Approximately 500** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
