  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Prune-belly: lax belly, bad kidneys, no balls.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT because respiratory insufficiency, while a potential complication, is not one of the defining primary features of Prune-belly syndrome. The question asks what is NOT *typically* associated as a primary characteristic.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrune-belly syndrome, also known as Eagle-Barrett syndrome, is classically defined by a triad: congenital absence or severe hypoplasia of the abdominal wall musculature, cryptorchidism (bilateral undescended testes), and urinary tract abnormalities (e.g., hydronephrosis, hydroureter, megacystis). Respiratory insufficiency can occur due to pulmonary hypoplasia from oligohydramnios (secondary to renal dysfunction) or impaired cough/ventilation from the lax abdominal wall, but it is a secondary complication rather than a primary diagnostic criterion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Lax abdominal wall) (Incorrect): This is one of the three cardinal features of Prune-belly syndrome, directly contributing to the characteristic \"prune\" appearance.\nOption C (Dilated ureters) (Incorrect): This is a key component of the urinary tract abnormalities, which is another cardinal feature of the syndrome.\nOption D (Bilateral undescended testes) (Incorrect): This is the third cardinal feature of Prune-belly syndrome, present in nearly all affected males.\nOption B (Respiratory insufficiency) (Correct): While respiratory issues can be a significant complication due to pulmonary hypoplasia or impaired abdominal mechanics, it is not considered one of the primary, defining features of the syndrome itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Prune-Belly Syndrome (Primary Defining Trait) | Prune-Belly Syndrome (Secondary Complication) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Abdominal Wall | Lax, wrinkled, \"prune\" appearance | Impaired cough, ventilation |\n| Genitourinary | Bilateral undescended testes, dilated ureters, hydronephrosis, megacystis | Renal failure, recurrent UTIs |\n| Pulmonary | - | Pulmonary hypoplasia (due to oligohydramnios), respiratory insufficiency |\n| Etiology | Unknown, likely mesodermal defect | - |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prune-belly syndrome is defined by the triad: lax abdomen, cryptorchidism, and urinary tract anomalies.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn prenatal ultrasound, one might see oligohydramnios, a large bladder, dilated ureters, and undescended testes. Postnatally, imaging (ultrasound, VCUG) will confirm the dilated urinary tract, and surgical exploration will reveal the absent/hypoplastic abdominal muscles and undescended testes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guidelines on Cryptorchidism (2023) recommends surgical management for undescended testes, a key component of Prune-belly syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lax abdominal wall | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Respiratory insufficiency | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Dilated ureters | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Bilateral undescended testes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Prune-belly syndrome is a disorder that is characterized by a constellation of symptoms including ex** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
