  "id": 120198,
  "question": "What is the approximate success rate for air enema reduction of intussusceptions in children?",
  "options": {
    "A": "10%",
    "B": "25%",
    "C": "50%",
    "D": "75%"
  },
  "answer": "D) In the patient [with an intussusceptions who is] in stable condition, the air enema is both diagnostic and often curative. It constitutes the preferred method of diagnosis and nonoperative treatment of intussusception. Air is introduced with a manometer and the pressure that is administered is carefully monitored. Under most instances, this should not exceed 120 mmHg. Successful reduction is marked by free reflux of air into multiple loops of small bowel and symptomatic improvement as the infant suddenly becomes pain free. Unless both of these indications are observed, it cannot be assumed that the intussusception is reduced. If reduction is unsuccessful and the infant’s condition remains stable, the infant should be brought back to the radiology suite for a repeat attempt at reduction after a few hours. This strategy has improved the success rate of nonoperative reduction in many centers. In addition, hydrostatic reduction with bariummay be useful if pneumatic reduction is unsuccessful. The overall success rate of radiographic reduction varies based on the experience of the center but is typically between 60 and 90%. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1433.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Push air, not fear: 75% success, less surgery, more smiles.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D, 75%, is the correct answer. The provided text indicates that the overall success rate of radiographic reduction for intussusception typically ranges between 60% and 90%, making 75% the most appropriate choice among the given options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAir enema reduction is the preferred nonoperative treatment for intussusception in stable children, serving both diagnostic and therapeutic purposes. The procedure involves carefully introducing air with a manometer, ensuring pressure does not exceed 120 mmHg. Successful reduction is confirmed by free reflux of air into multiple small bowel loops and immediate symptomatic improvement, such as the child becoming pain-free. If initial reduction is unsuccessful, repeat attempts after a few hours or hydrostatic reduction can significantly improve the overall success rate, which typically falls within the 60-90% range.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 10% is far too low; the success rate for air enema reduction is significantly higher, typically between 60-90%.\nOption B (Incorrect): 25% is also substantially lower than the established success rates for air enema reduction.\nOption C (Incorrect): 50% is below the typical range of 60-90% for successful air enema reduction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Air Enema Reduction | Hydrostatic Reduction (Barium) | Surgical Reduction |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Success Rate** | 60-90% | Similar to air enema | Nearly 100% (for reduction) |\n| **Mechanism** | Pneumatic pressure | Fluid pressure | Manual manipulation |\n| **Pressure Limit** | <120 mmHg | <100-120 mmHg | N/A |\n| **Indications** | Stable patient, no peritonitis/perforation | Stable patient, failed air enema | Unstable patient, signs of perforation, failed non-operative |\n| **Advantages** | Diagnostic & therapeutic, no radiation from contrast | Diagnostic & therapeutic | Definitive, allows for resection of non-viable bowel |\n| **Disadvantages** | Risk of perforation, radiation exposure | Risk of perforation, radiation exposure | Invasive, general anesthesia, longer recovery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Air enema for intussusception is often curative, aiming for 75% success.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an air enema, successful reduction is visualized as free reflux of air into multiple loops of small bowel. If reduction fails, the 'coiled spring' sign or a persistent filling defect may be seen. Intraoperatively, a 'telescoped' bowel segment would be observed, requiring manual reduction or resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline (2010): Management of Intussusception. Recommends pneumatic or hydrostatic enema as the initial treatment for stable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 25% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 75% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) In the patient [with an intussusceptions who is] in stable condition, the air enema is both diagnost** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
