  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Connective tissue genes are not cancer genes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question correctly identifies FBN1 as the gene NOT associated with hereditary cancer. FBN1 is primarily linked to Marfan syndrome, a connective tissue disorder, rather than an increased predisposition to malignancy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFBN1 encodes fibrillin-1, a crucial component of extracellular microfibrils that provide structural support to connective tissues. Mutations in FBN1 lead to Marfan syndrome, characterized by skeletal, ocular, and cardiovascular abnormalities, but not typically an elevated cancer risk. In contrast, genes like CDH1, HER2, and RET are well-established oncogenes or tumor suppressor genes whose germline mutations or overexpression are directly implicated in specific hereditary cancer syndromes, driving tumor initiation and progression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): CDH1 is a tumor suppressor gene associated with hereditary diffuse gastric cancer (HDGC) and lobular breast cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): HER2 (ERBB2) is an oncogene whose amplification/overexpression is a significant driver in breast and gastric cancers, and while germline mutations are rare, its role in cancer development is critical and can be seen in hereditary contexts.\nOption D (Incorrect): RET is a proto-oncogene associated with Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2A, MEN2B) and familial medullary thyroid carcinoma (FMTC).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gene | Associated Condition(s) | Type of Gene/Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| FBN1 | Marfan Syndrome | Connective Tissue Protein |\n| CDH1 | Hereditary Diffuse Gastric Cancer, Lobular Breast Cancer | Tumor Suppressor |\n| HER2 (ERBB2) | Breast Cancer, Gastric Cancer | Oncogene |\n| RET | MEN2A, MEN2B, Familial Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma | Proto-oncogene |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Marfan's (FBN1) is connective tissue, not cancer predisposition.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor Marfan syndrome, imaging (echocardiogram, CT/MRI) often reveals aortic root dilation, dissection, or mitral valve prolapse. Intraoperatively, surgeons may encounter friable tissues or require specialized techniques for aortic repair. For hereditary cancer syndromes, imaging might show early-onset, multifocal, or bilateral tumors (e.g., medullary thyroid cancer in MEN2, diffuse gastric cancer in HDGC).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment: Breast, Ovarian, and Pancreatic (v1.2024) recommends genetic counseling and testing for individuals meeting specific criteria for hereditary cancer syndromes, including those involving CDH1 and HER2-related cancers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | FBN1 | ✅ Correct |\n| B | CDH1 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | HER2 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | RET | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) FBN1 is the gene associated with Marfan’s syndrome and in not associated with malignancy. CDH1, HER2** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
