  "question": "APC (adenomatosis polyposis coli tumor-suppressor gene) is abnormal in what percentage of sporadic (nonsyndromic) colon cancer?",
  "options": {
    "A": "5%",
    "B": "15%",
    "C": "50%",
    "D": "80%"
  },
  "answer": "D) The product of the adenomatous polyposis coli tumor-suppressor gene (APC) is widely expressed in many tissues and plays an important role in cell-cell interactions, cell adhesion, regulation of β-catenin, and maintenance of cytoskeletal microtubules. Alterations in APC lead to dysregulation of several physiologic processes that govern colonic epithelial cell homeostasis, including cell-cycle progression, migration, differentiation, and apoptosis. Mutations in the APC gene have been identified in FAP and in 80% of sporadic colorectal cancers. Furthermore, APC mutations are the earliest known genetic alterations in colorectal cancer progression, which emphasizes its importance in cancer initiation. The germline mutations in APC may arise from point mutations, insertions, or deletions that lead to a premature stop codon and a truncated, functionally inactive protein. The risk of developing specific manifestations of FAP is correlated with the position of the FAP mutations, a phenomenon referred to as genotype-phenotype correlation. For example, desmoids usually are associated with mutations between codons 1403 and 1578. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 248.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 APC: The 80% rule for sporadic colon cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 80%, indicating that mutations in the APC gene are a highly prevalent and early event in the development of most sporadic (nonsyndromic) colorectal cancers. This highlights APC's critical role as a tumor suppressor in colonic epithelial cell homeostasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe APC gene product is vital for cell-cell interactions, cell adhesion, regulation of β-catenin, and maintenance of cytoskeletal microtubules. Alterations in APC lead to dysregulation of key physiological processes including cell-cycle progression, migration, differentiation, and apoptosis. Its mutation is considered the earliest known genetic alteration in colorectal cancer progression, underscoring its foundational importance in cancer initiation, even in cases without a hereditary syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (5%) (Incorrect): This percentage is far too low and does not reflect the significant role of APC mutations in sporadic colorectal cancer.\nOption B (15%) (Incorrect): This percentage significantly underestimates the prevalence of APC mutations, which are a dominant genetic driver in sporadic colorectal cancer.\nOption C (50%) (Incorrect): While a substantial percentage, 50% still falls short of the established prevalence of APC mutations, which are found in a higher proportion of sporadic colorectal cancers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | Sporadic Colorectal Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| APC Mutation | Germline mutation, 100% | Somatic mutation, ~80% |\n| Inheritance | Autosomal Dominant | Acquired |\n| Polyps | Hundreds to thousands, early onset | Fewer, develop over time |\n| Significance | Initiating event for both | Initiating event for both |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: APC mutation is the most common genetic alteration in sporadic colon cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn colonoscopy, one might observe adenomatous polyps or a frank mass, which, upon biopsy, could reveal dysplastic changes or adenocarcinoma driven by APC mutations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). These guidelines emphasize the molecular pathology of colorectal cancer, including the role of APC mutations, in guiding treatment and surveillance strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 5% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 15% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 80% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The product of the adenomatous polyposis coli tumor-suppressor gene (APC) is widely expressed in man** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
