  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, remember the \"5-10 rule\" for hereditary breast cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, indicating that 5-10% of breast cancers are hereditary. This percentage is a well-established epidemiological fact crucial for understanding breast cancer risk assessment and screening strategies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHereditary breast cancer, though a minority, is significant due to its strong genetic predisposition, primarily involving germline mutations in genes like BRCA1 and BRCA2. These mutations confer a substantially increased lifetime risk of breast and ovarian cancers, often presenting at an earlier age (e.g., <40 years old). Recognition of family history, particularly first- or second-degree relatives with premenopausal breast or ovarian cancer, is key to identifying individuals who may benefit from genetic counseling and testing. Founder mutations, as seen in the Ashkenazi Jewish population, further emphasize the importance of ethnic background in risk assessment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1% is significantly too low; the established range for hereditary breast cancer is higher.\nOption C (Incorrect): 30% is too high; this percentage might be closer to the proportion of breast cancers with some familial clustering, but not strictly hereditary (germline mutation).\nOption D (Incorrect): 50% is vastly too high; the vast majority of breast cancers are sporadic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Sporadic Breast Cancer | Hereditary Breast Cancer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | ~90-95% | ~5-10% |\n| Cause | Acquired somatic mutations, environmental factors | Germline mutations (e.g., BRCA1/2) |\n| Age of Onset | Typically older | Often younger (<50 years) |\n| Family History | Usually negative or weak | Strong, often multiple affected relatives |\n| Bilaterality | Less common | More common |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 5-10% for hereditary breast cancer, especially with early onset or strong family history.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, hereditary breast cancers, particularly BRCA-associated, may present as multifocal or multicentric disease, and there's a higher incidence of bilateral breast cancer. Intraoperatively, surgeons might encounter more aggressive tumor biology or consider prophylactic mastectomy in high-risk patients.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment: Breast, Ovarian, and Pancreatic (Version 1.2024). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for genetic testing criteria, risk assessment, and management strategies for individuals at high risk for hereditary breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 5-10% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 30% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) It is estimated that 5 to 10% of breast cancers are hereditary. Of women with early-onset breast can** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
