  "answer": "B) Besides breast and ovarian cancer, BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations may be associated with increased risks for several other cancers. BRCA1 mutations confer a fourfold increased risk for colon cancer and threefold increased risk for prostate cancer. BRCA2 mutations confer a fivefold increased risk for prostate cancer, sevenfold in men younger than 65 years. Furthermore, BRCA2 mutations confer a fivefold increased risk for gallbladder and bile duct cancers, fourfold increased risk for pancreatic cancer, and threefold increased risk for gastric cancer and malignant melanoma. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 248.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BRCA2: Not just breasts and ovaries, but a whole cancer party!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Lung cancer, because BRCA2 mutations are not significantly associated with an increased risk of lung cancer. In contrast, BRCA2 mutations are well-established risk factors for gastric, ovarian, and prostate cancers, among others.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBRCA2 is a tumor suppressor gene critical for DNA repair, particularly homologous recombination. Mutations in BRCA2 impair this repair mechanism, leading to genomic instability and an increased risk of developing various cancers. While most famously linked to breast and ovarian cancers, BRCA2 also significantly elevates the risk for prostate, pancreatic, gastric, and melanoma, highlighting its broad role in cancer predisposition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): BRCA2 mutations confer a threefold increased risk for gastric cancer, making this association correct.\nOption C (Incorrect): BRCA2 mutations are strongly associated with ovarian cancer, a primary cancer type linked to these mutations.\nOption D (Incorrect): BRCA2 mutations confer a fivefold increased risk for prostate cancer, especially in younger men, making this association correct.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cancer Type | BRCA1 Association | BRCA2 Association |\n|---|---|---|\n| Breast Cancer | High risk | High risk |\n| Ovarian Cancer | High risk | High risk |\n| Prostate Cancer | Threefold increased risk | Fivefold increased risk |\n| Pancreatic Cancer | Increased risk | Fourfold increased risk |\n| Gastric Cancer | Not specified | Threefold increased risk |\n| Colon Cancer | Fourfold increased risk | Not specified |\n| Melanoma | Not specified | Increased risk |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BRCA2 is more than just breast/ovarian; think prostate, pancreas, stomach, melanoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor BRCA2 carriers, imaging might reveal early-stage prostate cancer on MRI, pancreatic cysts or masses on CT/MRI, or gastric lesions on endoscopy, necessitating heightened surveillance. Intraoperatively, these patients may present with multifocal disease or more aggressive tumor biology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment: Breast, Ovarian, and Pancreatic (Version 1.2024) recommend genetic testing for individuals meeting specific criteria and outline surveillance strategies for associated cancers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastric cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lung cancer | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Ovarian cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prostate cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Besides breast and ovarian cancer, BRCA1 and BRCA2 mutations may be associated with increased risks ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
