  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer: No routine screen, just a mean disease.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Pancreatic cancer. Routine screening for pancreatic cancer is not recommended for average-risk patients due to its low prevalence, lack of effective screening tools, and high potential for false positives and unnecessary interventions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEffective cancer screening relies on identifying common cancers with a detectable pre-malignant or early-stage disease, for which effective and safe screening tests exist. Breast, colorectal, and cervical cancers meet these criteria with mammography, colonoscopy/FIT, and Pap smears/HPV testing, respectively. Pancreatic cancer, however, is often aggressive, presents late, and lacks a reliable, cost-effective, and non-invasive screening method for the general population.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Mammography is a widely recommended routine screening for breast cancer in average-risk women, typically starting at age 40 or 50 depending on guidelines.\nOption B (Incorrect): Colorectal cancer screening, via colonoscopy or stool-based tests, is routinely recommended for average-risk individuals, typically starting at age 45.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cervical cancer screening with Pap tests and/or HPV testing is a standard routine recommendation for average-risk women, typically starting at age 21.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cancer Type | Screening Method (Average-Risk) | Recommendation |\n|-------------|---------------------------------|----------------|\n| Breast      | Mammography                     | Routine        |\n| Colorectal  | Colonoscopy, FIT/FOBT           | Routine        |\n| Cervical    | Pap test, HPV testing           | Routine        |\n| Pancreatic  | None                            | Not Routine    |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Screen for common, treatable cancers with good tests, not rare, aggressive ones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, pancreatic cancer often appears as a hypodense mass with irregular borders, potentially causing pancreatic duct dilation or vascular encasement. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, often ill-defined mass within the pancreatic parenchyma, which may be locally invasive.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nUSPSTF (2021) and ACS (2023) recommend routine screening for breast, colorectal, and cervical cancers but explicitly state there is insufficient evidence to recommend routine screening for pancreatic cancer in asymptomatic, average-risk adults.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Breast cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Colorectal cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cervical cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pancreatic cancer | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 254, and Table 10-7.)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
