  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your markers, but trust your biopsy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the incorrect tumor marker-disease association. Option D, \"AFP and breast cancer,\" is the incorrect pairing, making it the correct answer to the question. Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is primarily associated with hepatocellular carcinoma and germ cell tumors, not breast cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTumor markers are biochemical substances produced by cancer cells or by the body in response to cancer. While rarely diagnostic on their own, they are valuable tools for screening, prognosis, monitoring treatment response, and detecting recurrence. PSA (Prostate-Specific Antigen) is a well-established marker for prostate cancer. CEA (Carcinoembryonic Antigen) is primarily used for monitoring colorectal cancer recurrence. CA19-9 (Carbohydrate Antigen 19-9) is the most widely used marker for pancreatic adenocarcinoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): PSA and prostate cancer is a correct association. PSA is crucial for prostate cancer screening, diagnosis, and monitoring.\nOption B (Incorrect): CEA and colon cancer is a correct association. CEA is a key marker for surveillance of colorectal cancer recurrence post-resection.\nOption C (Incorrect): CA19-9 and pancreatic cancer is a correct association. CA19-9 is used in the diagnosis, prognosis, and monitoring of pancreatic adenocarcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Marker | Primary Associated Cancer(s) | Clinical Utility |\n|---|---|---|\n| PSA | Prostate Cancer | Screening, diagnosis, recurrence monitoring |\n| CEA | Colorectal Cancer | Recurrence monitoring, prognosis |\n| CA19-9 | Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma | Diagnosis, prognosis, treatment response |\n| AFP | Hepatocellular Carcinoma, Germ Cell Tumors | Screening (HCC in high-risk), diagnosis, monitoring |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tumor markers aid, but rarely diagnose; context is key.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor breast cancer, imaging (mammography, ultrasound, MRI) typically reveals a mass or architectural distortion. Intraoperatively, a suspicious lesion is often biopsied or excised for definitive diagnosis, as no specific tumor marker guides surgical intervention directly for breast cancer.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (2023) recommend AFP for surveillance of hepatocellular carcinoma in high-risk patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | PSA and prostate cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CEA and colon cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CA19-9 and pancreatic cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | AFP and breast cancer | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 255, and Table 10-8.)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
