  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HER2: Hit it with Trastuzumab, not just hope!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Trastuzumab. This question tests your knowledge of molecularly targeted therapies and their specific gene/receptor targets, a critical area in modern surgical oncology. Trastuzumab is a well-known monoclonal antibody specifically designed to target the HER2 receptor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHER2 (Human Epidermal growth factor Receptor 2) is a transmembrane tyrosine kinase receptor that, when overexpressed, drives uncontrolled cell proliferation and survival in certain cancers. Trastuzumab binds to the extracellular domain of the HER2 receptor, preventing ligand binding and receptor dimerization, thereby inhibiting downstream signaling pathways. This action also recruits immune effector cells to mediate antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity (ADCC), leading to the destruction of HER2-positive cancer cells. Its specificity makes it highly effective in HER2-positive breast and gastric cancers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cetuximab is a monoclonal antibody that targets the Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor (EGFR), not HER2. It is used in colorectal and head and neck cancers.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sunitinib is a multi-targeted receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitor that primarily targets VEGFR, PDGFR, and KIT, among others. It is used in renal cell carcinoma and GIST.\nOption D (Incorrect): Temsirolimus is an mTOR inhibitor, which acts downstream in cell growth and proliferation pathways, but does not directly target the HER2 receptor. It is used in renal cell carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drug | Target | Indication Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| Trastuzumab | HER2 receptor | HER2+ Breast Cancer, HER2+ Gastric Cancer |\n| Cetuximab | EGFR receptor | Colorectal Cancer, Head & Neck Cancer |\n| Sunitinib | VEGFR, PDGFR, KIT | Renal Cell Carcinoma, GIST |\n| Temsirolimus | mTOR | Renal Cell Carcinoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HER2: Think Trastuzumab. EGFR: Think Cetuximab.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, HER2-positive tumors may show increased metabolic activity on PET scans. Intraoperatively, HER2 status is determined by immunohistochemistry (IHC) and/or FISH on biopsy or resected tissue, guiding neoadjuvant or adjuvant therapy decisions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend HER2 testing for all newly diagnosed invasive breast cancers and provide detailed algorithms for Trastuzumab-based regimens in HER2-positive disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cetuximab | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sunitinib | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Trastuzumab | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Temsirolimus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) (See Schwartz 9th ed., p. 263, and Table 10-10.)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
