  "question": "Rejection that starts on postoperative day 2 is most likely",
  "options": {
    "A": "Hyperacute rejection",
    "B": "Accelerated acute rejection",
    "C": "Acute rejection",
    "D": "Chronic rejection"
  },
  "answer": "B) [Hyperacute] rejection, which usually occurs within minutes after the transplanted organ is reperfused, is due to the presence of preformed antibodies in the recipient, antibodies that are specific to the donor. These antibodies may be directed against the donor’s HLAantigens or they may be anti-ABO blood group antibodies. [Accelerated acute] rejection, seen within the first few days posttransplant, involves both cellular and antibody-mediated injury. It is more common when a recipient has been sensitized by previous exposure to antigens present in the donor, resulting in an immunologic memory response. Acute rejection usually is seen within days to a few months posttransplant. It is predominantly a cell-mediated process, with lymphocytes being the main cells involved. [Chronic] rejection occurs months to years posttransplant. Now that short-term graft survival rates have improved so markedly, chronic rejection is an increasingly common problem. Histologically, the process is characterized by atrophy, fibrosis, and arteriosclerosis. Both immune and nonimmune mechanisms are likely involved. Clinically, graft function slowly deteriorates over months to years posttransplant. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 274.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Early rejection? Think accelerated, not just acute.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B, Accelerated acute rejection, is the correct answer. Rejection occurring on postoperative day 2 aligns perfectly with the definition of accelerated acute rejection, which is seen within the first few days post-transplant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAccelerated acute rejection is characterized by its early onset, typically within the first few days following transplantation. This rapid response is due to prior sensitization of the recipient to donor antigens, leading to an immunologic memory response. The mechanism involves both cellular and antibody-mediated injury, distinguishing it from hyperacute (preformed antibodies) and typical acute rejection (predominantly cell-mediated). Understanding the timing and underlying immunological mechanisms of different rejection types is crucial for prompt diagnosis and management in transplant surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Hyperacute rejection): Incorrect. Hyperacute rejection occurs within minutes of reperfusion, not on postoperative day 2. It is mediated by preformed antibodies.\nOption C (Acute rejection): Incorrect. While acute rejection can occur within days, its typical window is days to a few months post-transplant, and it is predominantly cell-mediated. Accelerated acute is a more specific and earlier form.\nOption D (Chronic rejection): Incorrect. Chronic rejection occurs months to years post-transplant, characterized by slow graft deterioration, atrophy, fibrosis, and arteriosclerosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Rejection Type | Timing | Primary Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hyperacute | Minutes post-reperfusion | Preformed antibodies |\n| Accelerated Acute | First few days post-transplant | Cellular and antibody-mediated (prior sensitization) |\n| Acute | Days to a few months post-transplant | Predominantly cell-mediated |\n| Chronic | Months to years post-transplant | Immune and non-immune mechanisms (fibrosis, arteriosclerosis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rejection timing is key: minutes (hyperacute), days (accelerated acute), weeks/months (acute), years (chronic).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., ultrasound with Doppler), accelerated acute rejection might manifest as early graft dysfunction with signs like increased resistive indices, edema, or decreased perfusion. Intraoperatively, the graft might appear dusky or fail to perfuse adequately if it were hyperacute, but for accelerated acute, it's more about early functional decline and biopsy findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Transplantation (AST) Guidelines (various years): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, prevention, and treatment of all types of organ transplant rejection, including specific protocols for early post-transplant complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hyperacute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Accelerated acute rejection | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Acute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Chronic rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) [Hyperacute] rejection, which usually occurs within minutes after the transplanted organ is reperfus** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
