  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ileum's the deal for living donor bowel, don't be a fool!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Mid to distal ileum. Living-donor intestinal transplants most commonly utilize about 200 cm of the donor's ileum, specifically the mid to distal portion, due to its suitable length and vascular supply via the ileocolic vessels.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe mid to distal ileum is the preferred segment for living donor small bowel transplantation for several key reasons. It offers a sufficient length (approximately 200 cm) for adequate nutrient absorption post-transplant, while preserving enough bowel for the donor to maintain normal digestive function. Crucially, its vascular supply, the ileocolic vessels, provides a robust and anatomically consistent pedicle that is amenable to microvascular anastomosis. This segment also has a lower density of Peyer's patches compared to the proximal ileum, which may theoretically reduce the immunogenicity of the graft, although this is less of a primary driver than length and vascularity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Proximal jejunum) (Incorrect): The proximal jejunum is critical for early digestion and absorption of many nutrients. Removing a significant portion would severely compromise the donor's digestive capacity. Its vascular supply can also be more complex to isolate for a transplant.\nOption B (Mid to distal jejunum) (Incorrect): Similar to the proximal jejunum, the jejunum is vital for nutrient absorption. While longer than the proximal jejunum, removing a substantial segment would still pose significant risks to donor nutrition. The vascular pedicle might also be less ideal than the ileocolic vessels.\nOption C (Proximal ileum) (Incorrect): While the ileum is the correct general region, the proximal ileum is often less preferred than the mid to distal segment. The mid to distal ileum typically offers a longer segment with a more consistent and easily dissectible ileocolic vascular pedicle, which is crucial for successful transplantation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Bowel Segment | Primary Function | Suitability for Living Donor Transplant | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Proximal Jejunum | Primary digestion & absorption (carbs, proteins, fats) | Poor | Critical for donor's nutrition; complex vascular supply; high immunogenicity |\n| Mid/Distal Jejunum | Continued absorption | Poor | Significant impact on donor's nutrition; less ideal vascular pedicle |\n| Proximal Ileum | Vitamin B12, bile salt absorption; immune function | Less preferred | Shorter length; less consistent ileocolic pedicle than mid/distal |\n| Mid/Distal Ileum | Vitamin B12, bile salt absorption; immune function | Preferred | Sufficient length (200cm); robust ileocolic vascular pedicle; preserves donor function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Living donor small bowel transplant uses mid-distal ileum with ileocolic vessels.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the ileocolic artery and vein are meticulously dissected, typically originating from the superior mesenteric artery and draining into the superior mesenteric vein. The length of the harvested ileum (around 200 cm) is carefully measured from the ileocecal valve proximally. On angiography, the robust nature of the ileocolic pedicle supplying the mid-distal ileum would be evident.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Transplant Surgeons (ASTS) 2020 Guidelines for Intestinal Transplantation: These guidelines emphasize careful donor selection and surgical technique, often referencing the use of the ileum for living donor grafts due to its vascular anatomy and functional capacity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Proximal jejunum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mid to distal jejunum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Proximal ileum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mid to distal ileum | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Living-donor intestinal transplants usually involve removal of about 200 cm of the donor’s ileum, wi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
