  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lungs don't wait; transplant fast or face the wrath.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 6 hours. Hearts and lungs are highly sensitive to ischemic injury and tolerate preservation poorly compared to other solid organs, necessitating shorter cold ischemia times for optimal graft function and reduced risk of primary graft dysfunction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLungs, with their delicate parenchymal structure and constant exposure to the environment, are particularly vulnerable to ischemic and reperfusion injury. Prolonged ischemia leads to endothelial dysfunction, increased capillary permeability, and inflammatory responses, culminating in primary graft dysfunction. The high metabolic demand of lung tissue, even in hypothermic conditions, contributes to this rapid deterioration, making prompt transplantation crucial to minimize cellular damage and ensure graft viability.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (12 hours) (Incorrect): While acceptable for some organs, 12 hours is significantly beyond the ideal limit for lung preservation and would substantially increase the risk of primary graft dysfunction.\nOption C (24 hours) (Incorrect): 24 hours is typically the upper limit for pancreas transplantation, where prolonged ischemia can lead to pancreatitis and duodenal leaks, but it is far too long for lung grafts.\nOption D (36 hours) (Incorrect): 36 hours is the approximate upper limit for kidney transplantation before delayed graft function significantly increases, highlighting how poorly lungs tolerate such extended ischemia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organ | Ideal/Max Ischemia Time | Complications of Prolonged Ischemia |\n|---|---|---|\n| Heart/Lung | < 6 hours | Primary graft dysfunction, reperfusion injury |\n| Liver | < 16 hours | Primary non-function, biliary complications |\n| Pancreas | < 24 hours | Pancreatitis, duodenal leaks |\n| Kidney | < 36-40 hours | Delayed graft function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hearts and lungs are ischemia-intolerant; prioritize rapid transplantation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn chest X-ray or CT, an ischemic lung graft might show diffuse alveolar infiltrates, ground-glass opacities, or consolidation, indicative of primary graft dysfunction (PGD) or reperfusion injury. Intraoperatively, an ischemic lung may appear edematous, boggy, and fail to inflate or oxygenate adequately.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation (ISHLT) Guidelines for the Selection and Management of Lung Transplant Candidates and Recipients (2021). These guidelines emphasize minimizing cold ischemia time to reduce the incidence and severity of primary graft dysfunction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 6 hours | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 12 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 24 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 36 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) With kidneys, cold ischemic times should be kept below 36 to 40 hours; after that, delayed graft fun** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
