  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The patient dies, not the kidney.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Recipient death. This is currently the leading cause of graft loss following renal transplantation, often occurring with a still-functioning graft, primarily due to cardiovascular complications in the recipient.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWith significant advancements in immunosuppressive therapies, the incidence of acute rejection as a primary cause of graft loss has dramatically decreased. Consequently, kidney transplant recipients are living longer, but they often carry a heavy burden of comorbidities, particularly cardiovascular disease, which is exacerbated by chronic kidney disease and immunosuppression. Therefore, the most common reason a transplanted kidney is no longer in a living recipient is the death of the recipient from these systemic issues, rather than the intrinsic failure of the graft itself.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Acute rejection, while a serious complication, is no longer the leading cause of overall graft loss due to improved immunosuppressive regimens. It is more common in the early post-transplant period.\nOption C (Incorrect): Chronic nephropathy (or chronic allograft dysfunction) is the second most common cause of graft loss, characterized by a slow, progressive decline in graft function, but it is not the leading cause.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pyelonephritis is a potential infectious complication of renal transplantation but is not the leading cause of graft loss.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Graft Loss | Description | Relative Incidence |\n| :------------------ | :---------- | :----------------- |\n| Recipient Death     | Often due to cardiovascular disease, with a functioning graft. | Leading cause |\n| Chronic Allograft Nephropathy | Slow, progressive deterioration of graft function. | Second leading cause |\n| Acute Rejection     | Immunologic attack on the graft, often early post-transplant. | Decreased significantly with modern immunosuppression |\n| Surgical Complications | Technical issues during or immediately after surgery. | Relatively low (~2%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Recipient death, not graft failure, is the top reason for graft loss.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., echocardiogram, coronary angiography) in a deceased recipient would likely show severe cardiovascular disease (e.g., myocardial infarction, severe heart failure), while the transplanted kidney itself would appear viable and well-perfused on post-mortem imaging or explantation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO (Kidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Care of Kidney Transplant Recipients (2009, updated 2020). Recommends comprehensive cardiovascular risk assessment and management in transplant recipients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Recipient death | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Acute rejection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Chronic nephropathy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pyelonephritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Currently, the most common cause of graft loss is recipient death (usually from cardiovascular cause** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
