  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Milan criteria: Small tumors, big survival.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This question correctly identifies a patient who meets the Milan criteria for liver transplantation for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC), which are crucial for optimal post-transplant survival outcomes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Milan criteria, established in 1996, revolutionized patient selection for liver transplantation in HCC. They define eligibility as a single tumor ≤ 5 cm or 1 to 3 tumors, each ≤ 3 cm, with no evidence of vascular or lymphatic invasion. Adherence to these strict criteria significantly improved 4-year overall survival rates to an impressive 85%, demonstrating the importance of careful patient selection to maximize the benefit of this life-saving procedure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A single tumor of 5.5 cm exceeds the Milan criterion of a single lesion ≤ 5 cm.\nOption B (Incorrect): Two tumors, one measuring 3.5 cm, exceeds the Milan criterion that each of 1-3 tumors must be ≤ 3 cm.\nOption D (Incorrect): Option C correctly meets the Milan criteria, making this choice incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Criteria | Single Tumor | Multiple Tumors |\n|---|---|---|\n| Milan | ≤ 5 cm | 1-3 tumors, each ≤ 3 cm |\n| UCSF | ≤ 6.5 cm | 2-3 tumors, largest ≤ 4.5 cm, total diameter ≤ 8 cm |\n| Extended | Varies, often includes larger/more tumors with careful selection | Varies |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Milan criteria: 5-3-3 rule (single ≤5cm OR 1-3 tumors, each ≤3cm).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn contrast-enhanced CT or MRI, HCC typically appears as an arterial-enhancing lesion with rapid washout in the portal venous or delayed phases. Intraoperatively, HCC lesions may appear as discrete nodules, often paler or darker than surrounding cirrhotic liver.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) 2018 guidelines for HCC management endorse the Milan criteria as a primary selection tool for liver transplantation, alongside other expanded criteria.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A single tumor in the left lobe 5.5 cmin diameter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Two tumors, both in the right lobe, 3.5 cmand 2.5 cmin diameter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Three tumors, in the right and left lobes, 2.5 cm, 2.8 cm, and 1.0 cmin dia | ✅ Correct |\n| D | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Long-term patient survival in early series of OLT for HCC only reached 30 to 40%. It was not until p** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
