  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Red bumps on shins? Think IBD, not just a bruise!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, as erythema nodosum characteristically presents with lesions predominantly on the lower legs. This is a key distinguishing feature of this extraintestinal manifestation of inflammatory bowel disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nErythema nodosum is a common extraintestinal manifestation of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD), affecting 5-15% of patients and often correlating with disease activity. It is characterized by raised, red, tender nodules that typically appear on the shins and lower legs. It is important to differentiate it from pyoderma gangrenosum, another IBD-associated skin condition, which starts as an erythematous plaque or papule, often on the pretibial region, but progresses to painful, necrotic ulcers and can occasionally occur near a stoma. Unlike pyoderma gangrenosum, erythema nodosum is more frequently seen in women.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Erythema nodosum is seen more commonly in women, not men, with women being affected three to four times more frequently.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pyoderma gangrenosum, not erythema nodosum, is the condition that may occur near a stoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Since options A and B are incorrect, 'All of the above' is also incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Erythema Nodosum | Pyoderma Gangrenosum |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Association with IBD** | 5-15% of IBD patients | Uncommon but serious |\n| **Gender Predilection** | Women (3-4x more) | No strong gender predilection |\n| **Lesion Description** | Raised, red, tender nodules | Erythematous plaque/papule progressing to painful, necrotic ulcer |\n| **Primary Location** | Lower legs (shins) | Pretibial region of leg |\n| **Stoma Association** | No | Occasionally near a stoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Erythema nodosum = red nodules on shins; Pyoderma gangrenosum = painful ulcers, can be near stoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, erythema nodosum presents as tender, erythematous, warm nodules, typically 1-5 cm in diameter, located bilaterally on the anterior aspects of the lower legs. These lesions do not ulcerate.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guidelines: Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019) and Crohn's Disease in Adults (2018) recommend screening for and managing extraintestinal manifestations, including dermatologic conditions like erythema nodosum, as part of comprehensive IBD care.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is seen more commonly in men | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | May occur near a stoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Usually occurs on the lower legs | ✅ Correct |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Erythema nodosum is seen in 5 to 15% of patients with inflammatory bowel disease and usually coincid** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
