  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When lymphoma hits the colon, the cecum's the first stop!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Cecum. Lymphoma of the colon is a rare entity, but when it does occur, the cecum is the most frequently involved site, often due to its rich lymphoid tissue and proximity to the terminal ileum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe cecum is anatomically rich in lymphoid tissue, particularly the Peyer's patches found in the adjacent terminal ileum, which makes it a common site for primary gastrointestinal lymphomas or for spread from the ileum. This predilection for lymphoid-rich areas explains why the cecum, and the GI tract in general, can be affected by lymphoma. While overall GI lymphoma is rare, accounting for about 10% of all lymphomas, the cecum stands out as the most common colorectal location.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The transverse colon is not the most common site for colorectal lymphoma; the cecum holds this distinction. \nOption C (Incorrect): The sigmoid colon, while a common site for other colorectal pathologies like diverticulitis and adenocarcinoma, is not the most common location for lymphoma. \nOption D (Incorrect): The rectum is less commonly involved with lymphoma compared to the cecum, though it can be affected.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cecal Lymphoma | Colorectal Adenocarcinoma | Gastric Lymphoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Most Common Site** | Cecum (for colorectal lymphoma) | Sigmoid colon/Rectum | Stomach (overall GI lymphoma) |\n| **Typical Presentation** | Bleeding, obstruction, mass | Bleeding, change in bowel habits, obstruction | Dyspepsia, pain, weight loss |\n| **Histology** | Non-Hodgkin lymphoma (often MALT or diffuse large B-cell) | Adenocarcinoma | Non-Hodgkin lymphoma (often MALT or diffuse large B-cell) |\n| **Treatment** | Resection for localized disease, +/- adjuvant chemo/radiation | Resection, +/- adjuvant chemo/radiation | Chemo/radiation, +/- surgery |\n| **Distinguishing Feature** | Can mimic adenocarcinoma clinically | Most common colorectal malignancy | Most common primary GI lymphoma |\n| **Risk Factors** | Immunosuppression, H. pylori (for gastric) | Age, genetics, IBD | H. pylori (MALT lymphoma) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cecum is the GI lymphoma hotspot in the colon, often spreading from the ileum.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or endoscopy, cecal lymphoma can present as a bulky, infiltrative mass, ulceration, or stricture, often indistinguishable from adenocarcinoma. Intraoperatively, it may appear as a firm, irregular mass, sometimes with associated lymphadenopathy, requiring careful differentiation from other cecal pathologies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for B-Cell Lymphomas (2023): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of various B-cell lymphomas, including those affecting the gastrointestinal tract, emphasizing multidisciplinary management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cecum | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Transverse colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sigmoid colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Rectum | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Lymphoma involving the colon and rectum is rare, but accounts for about 10% of all GI lymphomas. The** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
