  "question": "A microscopic focus of cancer is found in a polyp after endoscopic resection. Which of the following is an indication for colectomy in this patient?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Focus of cancer 2 mm from the resection margin",
    "B": "Polyp size >2 cm",
    "C": "Lymphovascular invasion",
    "D": "History of multiple polyps"
  },
  "answer": "C) Occasionally, a polyp that was thought to be benign will be found to harbor invasive carcinoma after polypectomy. Treatment of a malignant polyp is based upon the risk of local recurrence and the risk of lymph node metastasis. The risk of lymph node metastases depends primarily upon the depth of invasion. Invasive carcinoma in the head of a pedunculated polyp with no stalk involvement carries a low risk of metastasis (1%) and may be completely resected endoscopically. However, lymphovascular invasion, poorly differentiated histology, or tumor within 1 mm of the resection margin greatly increases the risk of local recurrence and metastatic spread. Segmental colectomy is then indicated. Invasive carcinoma arising in a sessile polyp extends into the submucosa and is usually best treated with segmental colectomy (Fig. 29-5). (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1048.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When cancer cells hitch a ride, cut out the highway!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Lymphovascular invasion. This finding is a critical indicator of increased metastatic potential, necessitating a more aggressive surgical approach like segmental colectomy to ensure complete oncologic resection and address potential regional lymph node involvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant polyps require careful risk stratification to determine appropriate management. While many can be managed endoscopically, the presence of high-risk features dictates the need for surgical colectomy. Lymphovascular invasion specifically signifies that cancer cells have penetrated into the lymphatic or blood vessels, providing a direct conduit for systemic spread and lymph node metastasis. This dramatically elevates the risk of residual disease or distant spread, making segmental colectomy the definitive treatment to achieve clear margins and perform lymphadenectomy for accurate staging and improved prognosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Focus of cancer 2 mm from the resection margin. A margin of 2 mm is generally considered adequate for endoscopic resection if other high-risk features are absent. The critical threshold for an inadequate margin, necessitating further intervention, is typically less than 1 mm.\nOption B (Incorrect): Polyp size >2 cm. Polyp size alone is not a primary indication for colectomy. The decision for surgical resection is based on the histopathological features of the malignancy within the polyp, such as depth of invasion, differentiation, and presence of lymphovascular invasion, rather than its overall dimensions.\nOption D (Incorrect): History of multiple polyps. A history of multiple polyps indicates a predisposition to polyp formation but does not, by itself, dictate the management of a single malignant polyp found after resection. Management is based on the specific high-risk features of the malignant polyp itself.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Endoscopic Resection (Adequate) | Colectomy (Indicated) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Depth of Invasion | Head of pedunculated polyp, no stalk involvement | Sessile polyp with submucosal invasion |\n| Resection Margin | >1 mm clear margin | <1 mm margin |\n| Histology | Well/moderately differentiated | Poorly differentiated |\n| Lymphovascular Invasion | Absent | Present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lymphovascular invasion in a malignant polyp means colectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy would show the resected polyp site. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would identify the segment of colon containing the polypectomy site and perform a segmental colectomy with regional lymphadenectomy. The resected specimen would then be oriented for pathology to confirm clear margins and assess lymph node status.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend segmental colectomy for malignant polyps with high-risk features such as lymphovascular invasion, poorly differentiated histology, or an involved/positive margin.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Focus of cancer 2 mm from the resection margin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Polyp size >2 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lymphovascular invasion | ✅ Correct |\n| D | History of multiple polyps | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Occasionally, a polyp that was thought to be benign will be found to harbor invasive carcinoma after** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
