  "answer": "B) Adenomatous polyps are common, occurring in up to 25% of the population older than 50 years of age in the United States. By definition, these lesions are dysplastic. The risk of malignant degeneration is related to both the size and type of polyp. Tubular adenomas are associated with malignancy in only 5% of cases, whereas villous adenomas may harbor cancer in up to 40%. Tubulovillous adenomas are at intermediate risk (22%). (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1042.) In contrast to adenomatous polyps, hamartomatous polyps (juvenile polyps) usually are not premalignant. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1042.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's villous, be vigilant; it's often villainous.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Villous adenomas. These polyps carry the highest risk of malignant degeneration among the adenomatous types listed, with up to 40% potentially harboring cancer, significantly higher than tubular or tubulovillous adenomas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdenomatous polyps are dysplastic lesions with varying malignant potential. The risk of progression to adenocarcinoma is directly correlated with polyp size and histological architecture. Villous adenomas are characterized by long, finger-like projections of dysplastic epithelium, which provide a larger surface area for cellular proliferation and accumulation of genetic mutations, thus predisposing them to a higher rate of malignant transformation compared to the more common tubular adenomas with their glandular architecture.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Tubular adenomas have a lower malignant potential, with only about 5% progressing to cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): Tubulovillous adenomas represent an intermediate risk, with approximately 22% harboring malignancy, falling between tubular and villous types.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hamartomatous adenomas (e.g., juvenile polyps) are generally not considered premalignant and have a very low risk of malignant transformation, unlike adenomatous polyps.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Polyp Type | Histology | Malignant Potential |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tubular Adenoma | Glandular, branching tubules | ~5% |\n| Tubulovillous Adenoma | Mixed tubular and villous features | ~22% (Intermediate) |\n| Villous Adenoma | Long, finger-like projections | Up to 40% (Highest) |\n| Hamartomatous Polyp | Disorganized normal tissue | Very low/None (Non-premalignant) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Villous architecture equals villainous potential for cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, villous adenomas often appear as broad-based, sessile, or carpet-like lesions with a velvety or shaggy surface, sometimes friable, and can be quite large, making complete resection challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for Colorectal Cancer Screening and Surveillance (2021). These guidelines provide recommendations for surveillance intervals based on polyp number, size, and histology, emphasizing the increased risk associated with villous features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Tubular adenomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Villous adenomas | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Tubulovillous adenomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hamartomatous adenomas | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Adenomatous polyps are common, occurring in up to 25% of the population older than 50 years of age i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
