  "question": "Which of the following has the lowest recurrence rate after reduction and repair of a rectal prolapse?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Perineal reefing of the rectal mucosa (Delorme procedure)",
    "B": "Abdominal rectopexy (Ripstein procedure)",
    "C": "Perineal rectosigmoidectomy (Altemeier procedure)",
    "D": "Reduction of the perineal hernia and closure of the cul-de-sac (Moschcowitz procedure)"
  },
  "answer": "B) The primary therapy for rectal prolapse is surgery, and more than 100 different procedures have been described to treat this condition. Operations can be categorized as either abdominal or perineal. Abdominal operations have taken three major approaches: (a) reduction of the perineal hernia and closure of the cul-de-sac (Moschcowitz’s operation); (b) fixation of the rectum, either with a prosthetic sling (Ripstein and Wells rectopexy) or by suture rectopexy; or (c) resection of redundant sigmoid colon. In some cases, resection is combined with rectal fixation (resection rectopexy). Abdominal rectopexy with or without resection also is increasingly performed laparoscopically. Perineal approaches have focused on tightening the anus with a variety of prosthetic materials, reefing the rectal mucosa (Delorme procedure), or resecting the prolapsed bowel from the perineum (perineal rectosigmoidectomy or Altemeier procedure) (Fig. 29-6). Because rectal prolapse occurs most commonly in elderly women, the choice of operation depends in part upon the patient’s overall medical condition. Abdominal rectopexy (with or without sigmoid resection) offers the most durable repair, with recurrence occurring in fewer than 10% of patients. Perineal rectosigmoidectomy avoids an abdominal operation and may be preferable in high-risk patients, but is associated with a higher recurrence rate. Reefing the rectal mucosa is effective for patients with limited prolapse. Anal encirclement procedures generally have been abandoned. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1054.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For rectal prolapse, go abdominal for the win!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nAbdominal rectopexy, such as the Ripstein procedure, is the correct answer because it consistently demonstrates the lowest recurrence rates for rectal prolapse repair. This approach offers the most durable repair among the described surgical options by directly addressing the anatomical defect.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbdominal rectopexy achieves its superior durability by directly fixing the rectum, often using a prosthetic sling or sutures, to the sacrum or posterior pelvic wall. This robust fixation prevents the descent of the rectum, addressing the underlying anatomical defect more comprehensively than perineal approaches. Its effectiveness is reflected in recurrence rates typically below 10%, making it the gold standard for definitive repair, especially in patients who can tolerate an abdominal operation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Perineal reefing of the rectal mucosa (Delorme procedure) is a perineal approach effective for limited prolapse but is associated with higher recurrence rates compared to abdominal rectopexy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Perineal rectosigmoidectomy (Altemeier procedure) is a perineal approach often chosen for high-risk patients due to its less invasive nature, but it carries a significantly higher recurrence rate than abdominal rectopexy.\nOption D (Incorrect): Reduction of the perineal hernia and closure of the cul-de-sac (Moschcowitz procedure) is an abdominal approach, but the text explicitly states that \"Abdominal rectopexy (with or without sigmoid resection) offers the most durable repair,\" implying its superiority over other abdominal techniques like Moschcowitz in terms of recurrence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | Approach | Key Mechanism | Recurrence Rate | Patient Suitability |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Abdominal Rectopexy (Ripstein) | Abdominal | Rectal fixation (sling/suture) | Lowest (<10%) | Fit patients, definitive repair |\n| Perineal Rectosigmoidectomy (Altemeier) | Perineal | Resection of prolapsed bowel | Higher | High-risk/elderly patients |\n| Perineal Reefing (Delorme) | Perineal | Mucosal plication | Moderate | Limited/mucosal prolapse |\n| Moschcowitz Procedure | Abdominal | Cul-de-sac closure | Moderate | Less durable than rectopexy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Abdominal rectopexy: Fix it from above for the lowest recurrence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively during an abdominal rectopexy, the surgeon would identify the prolapsed rectum, mobilize it, and then fix it to the sacral promontory or posterior pelvic wall, often using a mesh or sutures, ensuring proper alignment and tension.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Colon and Rectal Surgeons (ASCRS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Treatment of Rectal Prolapse (2017). Recommends abdominal rectopexy as the most durable repair for full-thickness rectal prolapse in medically fit patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Perineal reefing of the rectal mucosa (Delorme procedure) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Abdominal rectopexy (Ripstein procedure) | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Perineal rectosigmoidectomy (Altemeier procedure) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Reduction of the perineal hernia and closure of the cul-de-sac (Moschcowitz | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The primary therapy for rectal prolapse is surgery, and more than 100 different procedures have been** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
