  "answer": "C) The most common perianal lesions in Crohn’s disease are skin tags that are minimally symptomatic. Fissures also are common. Typically, a fissure from Crohn’s disease is particularly deep or broad and perhaps better described as an anal ulcer. They often are multiple and located in a lateral position rather than anterior or posterior midline as seen in an idiopathic fissure in ano. A classic appearing fissure in ano located laterally should raise the suspicion of Crohn’s disease. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1038.)",
