  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Chronic UC: Time is a tumor's best friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 8% because the risk of colon cancer in patients with ulcerative colitis increases with disease duration. After 20 years, the approximate cumulative risk reaches 8%, reflecting the impact of chronic inflammation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nChronic inflammation in ulcerative colitis is a significant risk factor for colorectal cancer, driving a dysplastic process in the colonic mucosa. This risk is cumulative and duration-dependent, escalating from approximately 2% after 10 years to 8% after 20 years, and 18% after 30 years. Unlike sporadic colorectal cancers, UC-associated cancers often arise from flat dysplasia, making them challenging to detect early without meticulous endoscopic surveillance and targeted biopsies. Pancolonic disease further increases this risk, necessitating regular monitoring.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 18% represents the approximate risk of colon cancer after 30 years of ulcerative colitis, not 20 years.\nOption C (Incorrect): 28% is not a recognized approximate risk percentage for colon cancer at 20 years duration of ulcerative colitis.\nOption D (Incorrect): 38% is not a recognized approximate risk percentage for colon cancer at 20 years duration of ulcerative colitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Duration of UC | Approximate Colon Cancer Risk |\n|---|---|\n| 10 years | 2% |\n| 20 years | 8% |\n| 30 years | 18% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: UC cancer risk: 2% at 10, 8% at 20, 18% at 30 years.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, UC-associated dysplasia or cancer may appear as flat, subtle mucosal changes, often requiring targeted biopsies or chromoendoscopy for detection, rather than obvious polyps.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Ulcerative Colitis in Adults (2019). Recommends surveillance colonoscopy with biopsies every 1-3 years for patients with pancolitis or left-sided colitis for 8-10 years or more.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 8% | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 18% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 28% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 38% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Risk of malignancy increases with pancolonic disease and the duration of symptoms is approximately 2** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
