  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be a T1-N0-M0; know your stages, or you'll be in a Stage IV panic!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Stage III, because the tumor's characteristics (T1, N1, M0) directly correspond to this stage in the TNM classification system for colorectal cancer. Submucosal invasion (T1) with two positive lymph nodes (N1) and no distant metastases (M0) unequivocally places it in Stage III.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe TNM staging system is crucial for colorectal cancer, guiding prognosis and treatment. A T1 tumor indicates invasion into the submucosa but not beyond the muscularis propria. N1 signifies involvement of 1-3 regional lymph nodes, which is the case with two positive nodes. M0 means there are no distant metastases. The combination of any N-positive status (N1, N2) with any T-stage (T1-T4) and M0 automatically elevates the tumor to Stage III, as lymph node involvement is a significant prognostic factor.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Stage I colorectal cancer is defined as T1-T2 N0 M0. The presence of positive lymph nodes (N1) immediately excludes Stage I.\nOption B (Incorrect): Stage II colorectal cancer is defined as T3-T4 N0 M0. While it involves deeper invasion than Stage I, it still requires no lymph node involvement (N0). The N1 status makes this option incorrect.\nOption D (Incorrect): Stage IV colorectal cancer is defined by the presence of distant metastases (M1), regardless of T or N status. The question explicitly states \"no metastases\" (M0), thus ruling out Stage IV.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stage | T (Tumor) | N (Nodes) | M (Metastasis) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| I | T1, T2 | N0 | M0 |\n| II | T3, T4 | N0 | M0 |\n| III | Any T | N1, N2 | M0 |\n| IV | Any T | Any N | M1 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lymph node positivity (N+) always pushes colorectal cancer to Stage III or higher.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT scan, a T1 tumor might be difficult to definitively stage for depth of invasion, but enlarged regional lymph nodes (N1) would be visible. Intraoperatively, the primary tumor would be palpable or visible as a mass invading the submucosa, and suspicious regional lymph nodes would be identified and biopsied or resected.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 8th Edition (2017). It provides the definitive TNM classification for colorectal cancer, which is universally used for staging and prognosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Stage I | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stage II | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Stage III | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Stage IV | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) This is a T1, N1, M0 tumor, which makes it stage III. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1047, Tables 29-1 and** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
