  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Breast ducts: 15-20, like spokes on a wheel!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, indicating that 15-20 lactiferous ducts drain into the nipple of the mature female breast. This is because the breast is anatomically organized into 15 to 20 distinct lobes, with each lobe contributing one major lactiferous duct.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe mature female breast is composed of 15 to 20 glandular lobes, each of which is drained by a single major lactiferous duct. These ducts converge towards the nipple, where they typically dilate into an ampulla just beneath the surface before opening individually through constricted orifices on the nipple. This precise anatomical arrangement ensures efficient transport of milk from the glandular tissue to the exterior during lactation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 5-10 is too few; the breast typically has more lobes and thus more draining ducts than this range suggests.\nOption C (Incorrect): 25-30 is too many; this number exceeds the typical anatomical range of breast lobes and their associated ducts.\nOption D (Incorrect): 35-40 is significantly too many, far exceeding the known anatomical structure of the breast's ductal system.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Structure | Approximate Number | Function |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lobes | 15-20 | Major divisions of glandular tissue, each drained by a lactiferous duct |\n| Lobules | Hundreds per lobe | Functional units containing acini (milk-producing glands) |\n| Lactiferous Ducts | 15-20 | Transport milk from lobes to the nipple |\n| Nipple Pores | 15-20 | Openings for lactiferous ducts on the nipple surface |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember, 15-20 lobes = 15-20 ducts opening at the nipple.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn galactography, contrast injected into a single duct can delineate its branching pattern within a lobe. On ultrasound, dilated lactiferous ducts can appear as anechoic tubular structures radiating towards the nipple, especially in lactating women or those with ductal ectasia. During surgery, these ducts are typically not individually visible without specific dissection or injection, but their collective presence forms the nipple's internal structure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Breast Imaging (e.g., 2023). While not directly about duct count, these guidelines underpin the diagnostic imaging used to evaluate breast anatomy and pathology, including ductal abnormalities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 5-10 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 15-20 | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 25-30 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 35-40 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The breast is composed of 15 to 20 lobes, which are each composed of several lobules. Each lobe of t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
