  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just observe Zuska's; drain the pus and give the drugs!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Zuska’s disease, also known as recurrent periductal mastitis, is a condition characterized by recurrent retroareolar infections and abscesses. The correct treatment involves symptomatic management with antibiotics combined with incision and drainage of any formed abscesses.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nZuska’s disease involves chronic inflammation and infection of the retroareolar mammary ducts, often exacerbated by smoking. The primary goal of treatment is to resolve acute infections and drain purulent collections. Antibiotics target the bacterial pathogens, while incision and drainage physically remove the abscess contents, providing immediate relief and promoting healing. More aggressive surgical options like wide débridement or terminal duct resection are often complicated by persistent infection or recurrence, making conservative management the preferred initial strategy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Observation and NSAIDs are insufficient for an active bacterial infection and abscess formation, which require definitive drainage and antimicrobial therapy.\nOption C (Incorrect): While wide resection might seem definitive, it is frequently complicated by postoperative infections and is not the initial treatment of choice due to its morbidity and high recurrence rate.\nOption D (Incorrect): Mastectomy is a radical procedure reserved for conditions like extensive malignancy and is entirely inappropriate for Zuska's disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Features | Primary Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Zuska's Disease (Recurrent Periductal Mastitis) | Recurrent retroareolar infections/abscesses, often associated with smoking | Antibiotics + Incision & Drainage |\n| Lactational Mastitis | Puerperal, S. aureus, diffuse inflammation, may form abscess | Antibiotics; I&D if abscess |\n| Inflammatory Breast Cancer | Rapid onset, peau d'orange, erythema, no discrete mass, often mistaken for infection | Systemic chemotherapy, surgery, radiation |\n| Mammary Duct Ectasia | Non-infectious inflammation of ducts, nipple discharge, periareolar mass | Symptomatic, warm compresses, NSAIDs; excision if persistent/bothersome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Zuska's disease = recurrent retroareolar abscesses, treat with antibiotics and I&D.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a breast abscess appears as a hypoechoic, often complex, fluid collection with posterior acoustic enhancement. Intraoperatively, incision and drainage would reveal purulent material, often thick and malodorous, from a retroareolar cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Breast Abscesses (2014). Recommends aspiration or incision and drainage for breast abscesses, combined with appropriate antibiotics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Observation and nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Antibiotics, incision, and drainage | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Wide resection of the affected area | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Zuska’s disease, also called recurrent periductal mastitis, is a condition of recurrent retroareolar** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
