  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Subclavicular means Level III; don't get lost in the axilla!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, as a clinically positive subclavicular lymph node is anatomically classified as a Level III node. This classification is crucial for surgical planning and accurate oncologic staging, particularly in breast cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anatomical classification of axillary lymph nodes is based on their precise relationship to the pectoralis minor muscle. Level I nodes are located lateral to or below the lower border of the pectoralis minor, encompassing groups like the axillary vein and external mammary nodes. Level II nodes are situated superficial or deep to the pectoralis minor, including central and interpectoral groups. Level III nodes, which specifically include the subclavicular (or infraclavicular) group, are found medial to or above the upper border of the pectoralis minor muscle. This standardized system ensures consistent communication and treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Level I nodes are located lateral to or below the lower border of the pectoralis minor muscle, not in the subclavicular region.\nOption B (Incorrect): Level II nodes are located superficial or deep to the pectoralis minor muscle, not subclavicular.\nOption D (Incorrect): Level IV is not a standard anatomical classification for axillary lymph nodes in this context; the primary classification extends to Level III.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Lymph Node Level | Anatomic Location (relative to Pectoralis Minor) | Included Groups |\n|---|---|---|\n| Level I | Lateral to or below lower border | Axillary vein, external mammary, scapular |\n| Level II | Superficial or deep to | Central, interpectoral |\n| Level III | Medial to or above upper border | Subclavicular (infraclavicular) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pectoralis minor is the key to axillary lymph node levels: I (lateral), II (under), III (medial).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., ultrasound or CT), Level III (subclavicular) nodes would be identified superior and medial to the pectoralis minor muscle, often near the subclavian vein and vessels. Intraoperatively, these nodes are found in the apex of the axilla, requiring careful dissection superior to the pectoralis minor and meticulous attention to the neurovascular bundle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., 2023). These guidelines recommend comprehensive axillary staging, including assessment of Level I, II, and III nodes, to guide adjuvant therapy and prognosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Level I node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Level II node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Level III node | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Level IVnode | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The lymph node groups are assigned levels according to their anatomic relationship to the pectoralis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
