  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 LCIS: A young woman's risk, not a mass to chase.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is correct because lobular carcinoma in situ (LCIS) is predominantly found in younger, premenopausal women. This demographic pattern is a key distinguishing feature of LCIS compared to other breast lesions like ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLCIS is considered a non-obligate precursor lesion and, more importantly, a marker of increased risk for invasive breast cancer in either breast. Its prevalence in younger, premenopausal women underscores the importance of early risk stratification and long-term surveillance in this demographic. Understanding this age distribution helps clinicians differentiate LCIS from other breast pathologies and tailor management strategies, which typically focus on risk reduction and close follow-up rather than immediate aggressive surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): LCIS generally occurs at a younger age than DCIS, not an older age.\nOption C (Incorrect): LCIS is bilateral in a significantly higher percentage (50-70%) of women, not just 10-20%.\nOption D (Incorrect): The risk of developing invasive ductal carcinoma is lower (approximately 25-35%) and occurs much later (an average of 15-20 years), not 75% in 5-10 years.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Lobular Carcinoma In Situ (LCIS) | Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Typical Age | Younger, premenopausal | Older |\n| Bilaterality | 50-70% | Less common (often unilateral) |\n| Risk of Invasive Cancer | 25-35% | Higher (often >50% if untreated) |\n| Time to Invasive Cancer | 15-20 years | Shorter, if untreated |\n| Type of Invasive Cancer | Can be ductal or lobular in either breast | Usually invasive ductal carcinoma in same breast |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: LCIS: Young, premenopausal, bilateral risk, not an obligate precursor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nLCIS is typically an incidental microscopic finding on biopsy, often not visible on mammography or ultrasound as a distinct mass or calcification. It lacks a palpable mass or specific imaging features, making its diagnosis reliant on tissue sampling for other indications.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer Risk Reduction and Early Detection (Version 1.2024). Recommends risk assessment and consideration of risk-reducing strategies (e.g., chemoprevention, surveillance) for women with LCIS.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In general, LCIS occurs at an older age than ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The majority of women with LCIS are premenopausal | ✅ Correct |\n| C | LCIS is bilateral in 10 to 20% of women | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Invasive ductal carcinoma can be expected to occur an average of 5 to 10 ye | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) LCIS tends to occur at a younger age than DCIS and the majority (approximately two thirds) of women ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
