  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 12% is the magic number for lifetime breast cancer risk.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 12%. This represents the average lifetime risk for a newborn U.S. female to develop breast cancer, a key epidemiological statistic in surgical oncology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUnderstanding the average lifetime risk of breast cancer is fundamental for patient counseling and public health initiatives. This 12% figure is a population-level statistic for a female born today in the U.S. It's crucial to note that this risk is dynamic; the longer a woman lives without developing breast cancer, her *remaining* lifetime risk actually decreases. For instance, a 50-year-old woman has an 11% remaining lifetime risk, and a 70-year-old woman has a 7% remaining lifetime risk, reflecting the decreasing probability of developing the disease as one ages without prior diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (7%) (Incorrect): This represents the lifetime risk for a woman who has reached 70 years of age without developing breast cancer, not the average risk from birth.\nOption C (17%) (Incorrect): This percentage is significantly higher than the established average lifetime risk for breast cancer.\nOption D (22%) (Incorrect): This percentage is significantly higher than the established average lifetime risk for breast cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Age Group | Lifetime Breast Cancer Risk |\n|---|---|\n| Newborn U.S. Female | 12% |\n| Woman aged 50 years (remaining risk) | 11% |\n| Woman aged 70 years (remaining risk) | 7% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Average lifetime breast cancer risk is 1 in 8, or 12%.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, breast cancer often appears as a spiculated mass, architectural distortion, or clustered microcalcifications. Intraoperatively, it may present as a firm, irregular, non-mobile mass with desmoplastic reaction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening (2015): Recommends annual mammograms for women starting at age 40 and continuing as long as they are in good health.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 7% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 12% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 17% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 22% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The average lifetime risk of breast cancer for newborn U.S. females is 12%. The longer a woman lives** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
