  "question": "Routine mammography in women over 50 years of age decreases mortality from breast cancer by approximately",
  "options": {
    "A": "10%",
    "B": "25%",
    "C": "33%",
    "D": "45%"
  },
  "answer": "C) Routine use of screening mammography in women ≥50 years of age reduces mortality from breast cancer by 33%. This reduction comes without substantial risks and at an acceptable economic cost. However, the use of screening mammography in women 50 years of age is more controversial for several reasons: (a) breast density is greater and screening mammography is less likely to detect early breast cancer; (b) screening mammography results in more false-positive test findings, which results in unnecessary biopsies; and (c) younger women are less likely to have breast cancer, so fewer young women will benefit from screening. On a population basis, however, the benefits of screening mammography in women between the ages of 40 and 49 years still appear to outweigh the risks. Current recommendations are that women undergo baseline mammography at age 35 and then have annual mammographic screening beginning at age 40. (See Schwartz 9th ed., pp 437-438.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Screen early, live longer: 33% protection is worth it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 33%. Routine mammography in women over 50 years of age significantly reduces breast cancer mortality by approximately one-third, highlighting the critical role of screening in improving patient outcomes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe substantial reduction in mortality (33%) from breast cancer in women over 50 years of age is attributed to the early detection capabilities of mammography. By identifying non-palpable lesions and early-stage cancers, mammography allows for timely intervention, often leading to less aggressive treatments and higher cure rates. This benefit is well-established, with an acceptable balance of risks (e.g., false positives) and economic costs, making it a cornerstone of preventive care in this demographic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A 10% reduction is significantly lower than the established epidemiological benefit of routine mammography in this age group.\nOption B (Incorrect): While closer, 25% does not represent the widely cited and accepted mortality reduction figure.\nOption D (Incorrect): A 45% reduction overstates the current evidence regarding the mortality benefit of screening mammography.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Age Group | Screening Recommendation | Mortality Reduction | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| ≥50 years | Annual mammography | ~33% | Established benefit, low controversy |\n| 40-49 years | Annual mammography (controversial) | Benefits outweigh risks (population basis) | Higher breast density, more false positives, more unnecessary biopsies |\n| <40 years | Baseline at 35, then annual from 40 | Less benefit, higher false positives | Lower incidence, higher breast density, less likely to benefit |\n| General | Baseline mammography at age 35 | N/A | To establish individual breast architecture for future comparisons |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mammography for >50s cuts breast cancer mortality by 33%.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, suspicious findings include spiculated masses, architectural distortion, and pleomorphic microcalcifications. These findings often necessitate further imaging (e.g., ultrasound, MRI) or biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Cancer Society (ACS) 2015 Guidelines: Recommends annual mammograms for women aged 40-44 (optional), 45-54 (annual), and then every 1-2 years for women 55 and older, as long as they are in good health and have a life expectancy of at least 10 years.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 25% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 33% | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 45% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Routine use of screening mammography in women ≥50 years of age reduces mortality from breast cancer ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
