  "question": "Lymphatic drainage fromthe supraglottic larynx is primarily to",
  "options": {
    "A": "The prelaryngeal (Delphian) node",
    "B": "Paratracheal nodes",
    "C": "Deep cervical nodes",
    "D": "Superior jugular nodes"
  },
  "answer": "D) Lymphatic drainage of the larynx is distinct for each subsite. Two major groups of laryngeal lymphatic pathways exist: those that drain areas superior to the ventricle, and those that drain areas inferior to it. Supraglottic drainage routes pierce the thyrohyoid membrane with the superior laryngeal artery, vein, and nerve, and drain mainly to the subdigastric and superior jugular nodes. Those from the glottic and subglottic areas exit via the cricothyroid ligament and end in the prelaryngeal node (the Delphian node), the paratracheal nodes, and the deep cervical nodes along the inferior thyroid artery. Limited glottic cancers typically do not spread to regional lymphatics (1 to 4%). However, there is a high incidence of lymphatic spread fromsupraglottic (30 to 50%) and subglottic cancers (40%). (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 498, and Fig. 18-2.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Supraglottic drainage goes high, glottic/subglottic goes low.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D, Superior jugular nodes, is the correct answer. The lymphatic drainage of the supraglottic larynx is distinct and primarily follows pathways superior to the ventricle, leading to these specific nodes.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lymphatic drainage of the larynx is highly compartmentalized, with separate pathways for supraglottic, glottic, and subglottic regions. Supraglottic lymphatic vessels pierce the thyrohyoid membrane, often accompanying the superior laryngeal artery, vein, and nerve, to drain predominantly into the subdigastric and superior jugular nodes. This distinct anatomical arrangement explains the higher incidence of lymphatic spread observed in supraglottic cancers (30-50%) compared to glottic cancers, necessitating careful nodal evaluation in these patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The prelaryngeal (Delphian) node is primarily involved in the drainage of the glottic and subglottic regions, not the supraglottic larynx.\nOption B (Incorrect): Paratracheal nodes receive lymphatic drainage from the glottic and subglottic areas, exiting via the cricothyroid ligament.\nOption C (Incorrect): While superior jugular nodes are a type of deep cervical node, 'Deep cervical nodes' is too general. More specifically, deep cervical nodes along the inferior thyroid artery drain glottic and subglottic areas, making this option less precise for primary supraglottic drainage.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Laryngeal Subsite | Primary Lymphatic Drainage |\n|--------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Supraglottic       | Subdigastric, Superior Jugular nodes              |\n| Glottic            | Prelaryngeal (Delphian), Paratracheal, Deep cervical (along inferior thyroid artery) |\n| Subglottic         | Prelaryngeal (Delphian), Paratracheal, Deep cervical (along inferior thyroid artery) |\n| Limited Glottic    | Low incidence of lymphatic spread (1-4%)          |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Supraglottic cancer spreads to superior jugular nodes; glottic/subglottic to Delphian/paratracheal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), enlarged or suspicious lymph nodes in levels II and III (superior jugular chain) would be a key finding for supraglottic laryngeal carcinoma. Intraoperatively, careful palpation and targeted neck dissection of these levels are crucial.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (2024): Recommends comprehensive neck dissection or radiation to the neck for clinically positive nodes, and often elective neck treatment for T-stages where the risk of occult nodal metastasis is significant, such as in supraglottic larynx cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The prelaryngeal (Delphian) node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Paratracheal nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Deep cervical nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Superior jugular nodes | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Lymphatic drainage of the larynx is distinct for each subsite. Two major groups of laryngeal lymphat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
