  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When you see NPC, think EBV!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Epstein Barr virus (EBV), which has a well-established and strong correlation with nasopharyngeal carcinoma (NPC). This association is clinically significant, extending to its use in monitoring treatment response.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe strong epidemiological link between EBV infection and NPC is a cornerstone of understanding this malignancy. High EBV titers are not only diagnostic but also serve as a valuable biomarker for disease activity and response to therapy, particularly in endemic regions like Southern China. This viral etiology distinguishes NPC from many other head and neck cancers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Herpes simplex virus (HSV) is not significantly correlated with nasopharyngeal carcinoma. While it can cause oral lesions, it is not a primary oncogenic driver for NPC.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cytomegalovirus (CMV) is a common herpesvirus but has no established strong oncogenic link to nasopharyngeal carcinoma. It is more commonly associated with opportunistic infections in immunocompromised patients.\nOption D (Incorrect): Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) is associated with an increased risk of several cancers, including Kaposi sarcoma, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, and cervical cancer, but not directly with nasopharyngeal carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Virus | Associated Cancers |\n|---|---|\n| Epstein-Barr Virus (EBV) | Nasopharyngeal Carcinoma, Burkitt Lymphoma, Hodgkin Lymphoma |\n| Human Papillomavirus (HPV) | Cervical, Anal, Oropharyngeal Carcinomas |\n| Hepatitis B/C Virus (HBV/HCV) | Hepatocellular Carcinoma |\n| Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) | Kaposi Sarcoma, Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma, Cervical Carcinoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EBV is the viral signature of nasopharyngeal carcinoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI or CT, nasopharyngeal carcinoma often presents as a soft tissue mass in the nasopharynx, potentially invading adjacent structures like the skull base, parapharyngeal space, or orbit, and frequently associated with cervical lymphadenopathy. Endoscopically, it appears as an irregular, often ulcerated or fungating mass.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Head and Neck Cancers (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of nasopharyngeal carcinoma, including the role of EBV serology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Herpes simplex virus (HSV) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Epstein Barr virus (EBV) | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cytomegalovirus (CMV) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Risk factors for nasopharyngeal carcinoma include area of habitation, ethnicity, and tobacco use. Th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
