  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let recurrent tonsil infections be a pain in the neck!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because recurrent acute tonsillitis, specifically three or more infections per year despite adequate medical therapy, is a well-established indication for tonsillectomy in children. This intervention aims to reduce the frequency and severity of infections, improving the child's overall health and quality of life.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe tonsils, part of Waldeyer's ring, are lymphoid tissues that play a role in immune surveillance. However, in cases of recurrent acute tonsillitis, they can become chronic reservoirs for bacterial pathogens, leading to repeated infections. Surgical removal eliminates this nidus of infection, preventing further episodes and associated complications like peritonsillar abscess or rheumatic fever. The decision to operate balances the immune function of the tonsils against the morbidity caused by persistent infection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \">5 infections\" is generally too high; the established guideline is typically 3 or more infections per year for several years, or 7 in one year, 5 per year for two years, or 3 per year for three years.\nOption B (Incorrect): \">3 infections with strong family history\" is incorrect because family history is not a primary diagnostic criterion for tonsillectomy indication, although genetic predisposition to recurrent infections might exist.\nOption D (Incorrect): \">1 week missed from school in a year due to tonsillar infections\" is too low; the provided text suggests 2 or more weeks missed annually as a potential indication, but the primary criterion is infection frequency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication Type | Specific Criteria |\n|---|---|\n| Recurrent Infection | ≥7 episodes in 1 year, or ≥5 episodes/year for 2 years, or ≥3 episodes/year for 3 years |\n| Obstructive Hypertrophy | Obstructive sleep apnea, severe dysphagia, speech impairment, craniofacial growth abnormalities |\n| Other Indications | Peritonsillar abscess unresponsive to drainage, suspicion of malignancy, chronic tonsillitis leading to halitosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Three strikes, you're out for tonsil infections.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, hypertrophied tonsils appear enlarged, often meeting or kissing in the midline, potentially obstructing the oropharynx. Chronically infected tonsils may show cryptic changes, scarring, or purulent exudate upon manipulation, and can be friable or adherent to surrounding pillars.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery Clinical Indicators Compendium recommends tonsillectomy after three or more infections per year despite adequate medical therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | >5 infections | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | >3 infections with strong family history | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | >3 infections in one year | ✅ Correct |\n| D | >1 week missed fromschool in a year due to tonsillar infections | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Tonsillectomy and adenoidectomy are indicated for chronic or recurrent acute infection and for obstr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
