  "answer": "A) Temporal bone fractures are divided into two patterns (Fig. 18-7), longitudinal and transverse, based on the clinical picture and CT imaging. In practice, most fractures are oblique. By classical descriptions, longitudinal fractures constitute 80% and are associated with lateral skull trauma. Signs and symptoms include conductive hearing loss, ossicular injury, bloody otorrhea, and labyrinthine concussion. The facial nerve is injured in approximately 20% of cases. In contrast, the transverse pattern constitutes only 20% of temporal bone fractures and occurs secondary to fronto-occipital trauma. The facial nerve is injured in 50% of cases. These injuries frequently involve the otic capsule to cause sensorineural hearing loss and loss of vestibular function. Hemotympanummay be observed. A cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) leak must be suspected in temporal bone trauma. This resolves with conservative measures in most cases. The most significant consideration in the management of temporal bone injuries is the status of the facial nerve. Delayed or partial paralysis will almost always resolve with conservative management. However, immediate paralysis that does not recover within 1 week should be considered for nerve decompression. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 488.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's transverse, the facial nerve is in distress!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Transverse. Transverse temporal bone fractures are associated with a significantly higher incidence of facial nerve injury (50%) compared to longitudinal fractures (20%), making them the most likely pattern to cause this complication.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTemporal bone fractures are classified by their orientation relative to the petrous pyramid. Transverse fractures typically result from fronto-occipital trauma and run perpendicular to the long axis of the petrous bone, often involving the otic capsule. This trajectory places the facial nerve, particularly its labyrinthine and tympanic segments, at direct risk of transection or compression, leading to a high rate of immediate or delayed paralysis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Longitudinal fractures are more common (80%) and typically result from lateral skull trauma. While they can cause facial nerve injury, the incidence is lower, around 20%.\nOption C (Incorrect): Oblique fractures are common in practice, representing a combination of longitudinal and transverse features. However, they are not classically described as having the highest specific association with facial nerve injury compared to the distinct transverse pattern.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Open' refers to a fracture communicating with the external environment, not a specific pattern of temporal bone fracture relative to the petrous pyramid that dictates facial nerve injury likelihood. This classification is not used to compare facial nerve injury rates in the same way as transverse vs. longitudinal.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Longitudinal Fracture | Transverse Fracture |\n|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | 80% | 20% |\n| Trauma Type | Lateral skull trauma | Fronto-occipital trauma |\n| Facial Nerve Injury | ~20% | ~50% |\n| Hearing Loss | Conductive (ossicular injury) | Sensorineural (otic capsule) |\n| Other | Bloody otorrhea, labyrinthine concussion | Loss of vestibular function, hemotympanum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Transverse fractures = high facial nerve injury risk. Longitudinal fractures = high incidence, lower facial nerve risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, transverse fractures appear perpendicular to the petrous ridge, often extending through the otic capsule. Intraoperatively, direct visualization of the facial nerve for transection or compression is crucial, especially in cases of immediate paralysis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific society guideline is mentioned. Standard surgical texts like Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th ed., p 488) guide diagnosis and management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Transverse | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Longitudinal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Oblique | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Open | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Temporal bone fractures are divided into two patterns (Fig. 18-7), longitudinal and transverse, base** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
