  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think MFH – the king of adult soft tissue sarcomas.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Malignant Fibrous Histiocytoma (MFH) because, historically, it was considered the most common soft tissue sarcoma in adults, accounting for approximately 28% of cases. This prevalence makes it a critical entity to recognize for surgical board examinations.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMalignant Fibrous Histiocytoma (MFH) was once a broad diagnostic category for pleomorphic sarcomas lacking specific differentiation. While many cases are now reclassified into more specific entities like undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma (UPS), it remains a significant and aggressive sarcoma. Its high prevalence underscores the importance of understanding its clinical presentation, often as a rapidly growing, deep-seated mass, and its propensity for local recurrence and distant metastasis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Liposarcoma) (Incorrect): While liposarcoma is the second most common soft tissue sarcoma (around 15%), it does not surpass MFH in overall prevalence.\nOption B (Leiomyosarcoma) (Incorrect): Leiomyosarcoma is a common soft tissue sarcoma, particularly in retroperitoneal or uterine locations (around 12%), but it is less common than MFH.\nOption C (Synovial sarcoma) (Incorrect): Synovial sarcoma is a distinct entity, more common in adolescents and young adults, and accounts for a smaller percentage (around 10%) of adult soft tissue sarcomas compared to MFH.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Sarcoma Type | Approximate Adult Prevalence |\n|---|---|\n| Malignant Fibrous Histihistocytoma (MFH) / Undifferentiated Pleomorphic Sarcoma (UPS) | 28% |\n| Liposarcoma | 15% |\n| Leiomyosarcoma | 12% |\n| Synovial Sarcoma | 10% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MFH/UPS is the most common adult soft tissue sarcoma, remember its prevalence.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (MRI), MFH/UPS typically appears as a large, heterogeneous, ill-defined mass with areas of necrosis, hemorrhage, and variable contrast enhancement. Intraoperatively, it often presents as a firm, bulky tumor, sometimes with a pseudocapsule, but frequently invading surrounding tissues, making wide resection challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (Version 2.2024) recommend multidisciplinary evaluation and management, emphasizing complete surgical resection with negative margins as the cornerstone of treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Liposarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Leiomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Synovial sarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Malignant fibrous histiocytoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The most common histologic types of soft tissue sarcoma in adults (excluding Kaposi’s sarcoma) are m** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
