  "answer": "A) Core needle biopsy is a safe, accurate, and economical procedure for diagnosing sarcomas. The tissue sample obtained from a core needle biopsy is usually sufficient for several diagnostic tests such as electron microscopy, cytogenetic analysis, and flow cytometry. The reported complication rate for core needle biopsy is less than 1%. Fine-needle aspiration is an acceptable method of diagnosing most soft tissue sarcomas, particularly when the results correlate closely with clinical and imaging findings. However, fine-needle aspiration biopsy is indicated for primary diagnosis of soft tissue sarcomas only at centers where cytopathologists have experience with these types of tumors. Incisional biopsy and excisional biopsy may change the outcome for patients by complicating staging. They are not considered the best initial diagnostic method for sarcomas >3 cmin diameter. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1287.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
