  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sarcoma biopsy: Core first, stage later, save the limb!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nCore needle biopsy is the most appropriate initial method for biopsying a suspected 4-cm sarcoma of the lower leg. This approach is favored due to its safety, accuracy, and ability to provide sufficient tissue for comprehensive diagnostic testing while minimizing complications and avoiding compromise of future staging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCore needle biopsy (CNB) is the gold standard for diagnosing soft tissue sarcomas, especially those larger than 3 cm, because it yields adequate tissue for histopathology, immunohistochemistry, cytogenetics, and molecular studies, which are crucial for accurate subtyping and grading. Its low complication rate (<1%) and ability to be performed under imaging guidance ensure precise sampling. By providing a definitive diagnosis pre-operatively without disrupting tissue planes extensively, CNB preserves the integrity of the tumor and surrounding tissues, which is vital for accurate surgical planning and staging, ultimately improving patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Suction biopsy is generally used for mucosal lesions or aspiration of fluid, not for solid, deep-seated tumors like a 4-cm sarcoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Incisional biopsy, while providing tissue, is not the initial method of choice for sarcomas >3 cm as it can complicate subsequent staging and definitive surgical resection by contaminating surrounding tissue planes.\nOption D (Incorrect): Excisional biopsy is inappropriate for a suspected 4-cm sarcoma as it risks incomplete resection, tumor spillage, and compromise of limb-sparing surgery, thereby complicating definitive staging and treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Biopsy Method | Indication/Use | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Core Needle Biopsy (CNB)** | Suspected sarcoma >3cm, deep lesions | Safe, accurate, sufficient tissue for advanced tests, preserves staging | Requires expertise, potential for sampling error if not image-guided |\n| **Fine Needle Aspiration (FNA)** | Initial screening, highly experienced centers | Minimally invasive, rapid results | Limited tissue for ancillary studies, high false-negative rate if not expert |\n| **Incisional Biopsy** | When CNB is non-diagnostic, or for very large/complex tumors | Provides larger tissue sample | Risks tumor spillage, complicates staging/definitive surgery |\n| **Excisional Biopsy** | Small, superficial lesions where benign diagnosis is highly likely | Diagnostic and therapeutic in one step | Inappropriate for suspected sarcoma, risks inadequate margins/tumor spread |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For sarcomas >3cm, core needle biopsy is the initial diagnostic method of choice.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a sarcoma typically appears as a heterogeneous mass with variable signal intensity, often enhancing with contrast. Intraoperatively, a core needle biopsy is performed under ultrasound or CT guidance to ensure accurate sampling of the lesion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (2023) recommend core needle biopsy as the preferred method for initial diagnosis of soft tissue masses suspicious for sarcoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Core needle biopsy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Suction biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Incisional biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excisional biopsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Core needle biopsy is a safe, accurate, and economical procedure for diagnosing sarcomas. The tissue** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
