  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just cut it out; plan your sarcoma biopsy route!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A because an excisional biopsy is acceptable for superficial, easily accessible extremity or truncal lesions smaller than 3 cm. This approach minimizes the risk of inadequate margins and allows for definitive re-excision if the lesion proves malignant.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nExcisional biopsy for suspected sarcoma is a nuanced decision. While generally discouraged due to high recurrence rates (30-40%) with positive or uncertain margins, it can be considered for small, superficial lesions in non-critical areas. The primary goal of any biopsy for sarcoma is to obtain adequate tissue for diagnosis without compromising future definitive surgical resection, which often requires wide margins. Inappropriate biopsy can lead to tumor spillage, contamination of tissue planes, and necessitate more extensive re-excision, potentially impacting limb function or requiring amputation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A 1.5-cm lesion of the dorsum of the hand is in a critical anatomical location where an excisional biopsy could compromise function or make definitive re-excision with adequate margins extremely difficult, potentially leading to amputation or significant morbidity.\nOption C (Incorrect): A 2-cm lesion over the calcaneus is in a functionally critical area (foot) where an excisional biopsy could lead to significant morbidity, difficulty with definitive re-excision, and potential for tumor spillage in a complex anatomical region.\nOption D (Incorrect): A 4-cm superficial thigh mass is too large for an excisional biopsy. Lesions greater than 3 cm generally require an incisional or core needle biopsy to establish diagnosis before planning definitive wide local excision.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Biopsy Type | Indication | Contraindication/Consideration |\n| :---------- | :--------- | :----------------------------- |\n| Excisional  | Superficial, <3cm, easily accessible truncal/extremity lesions | Lesions >3cm, deep lesions, critical anatomical areas (hands, feet, head/neck, joints) |\n| Incisional  | Lesions >3cm, deep lesions, critical anatomical areas where excisional biopsy is not feasible | Risk of tumor spillage if not planned carefully; requires subsequent definitive wide excision |\n| Core Needle | Preferred for most suspected sarcomas, especially deep or large lesions | Small lesions where tissue yield might be insufficient; requires experienced radiologist/surgeon |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For sarcoma, excisional biopsy is for small, superficial, non-critical lesions only.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a suspected sarcoma often appears as a heterogeneous mass with variable signal intensity, sometimes with areas of necrosis or hemorrhage, and typically enhances after contrast. Intraoperatively, sarcomas can be firm, poorly circumscribed, and may have a pseudocapsule that should not be violated during biopsy or resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., Version 2.2023). These guidelines recommend core needle biopsy as the preferred method for diagnosis of most suspected soft tissue sarcomas, with incisional biopsy reserved for cases where core needle biopsy is non-diagnostic or not feasible. Excisional biopsy is generally discouraged except for very small, superficial lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2-cmsuperficial flank mass | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 1.5-cmlesion of the dorsumof the hand | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2-cmlesion over the calcaneus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 4-cmsuperficial thigh mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Excisional biopsy can be performed for easily accessible (superficial) extremity or truncal lesions ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
