  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DFSP: A local bully, not a global threat.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans (DFSP). This tumor is characterized by its locally aggressive nature but has a distinctly low risk of distant metastasis, as explicitly stated in the provided text.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDermatofibrosarcoma protuberans (DFSP) is a rare, slow-growing, locally aggressive tumor originating from dermal fibroblasts. While it has a high propensity for local recurrence due to its infiltrative growth pattern (often described as 'tentacles' extending into surrounding tissue), its metastatic potential is remarkably low, typically less than 5%. This biological behavior distinguishes it from most other sarcomas, which generally carry a much higher risk of distant spread.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Clear-cell sarcoma) (Incorrect): Clear-cell sarcoma is explicitly listed as having substantial metastatic potential.\nOption B (Leiomyosarcoma) (Incorrect): Leiomyosarcoma is also listed among highly aggressive tumors with substantial metastatic potential.\nOption D (Chondrosarcoma) (Incorrect): The text mentions extraskeletal chondrosarcoma as having an intermediate risk of metastatic spread, not a low risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Metastatic Potential | Key Feature/Treatment Note |\n|---|---|---|\n| Dermatofibrosarcoma Protuberans (DFSP) | Low (<5%) | Locally aggressive, high local recurrence, wide local excision or Mohs surgery |\n| Clear-cell Sarcoma | High | Often mistaken for melanoma, aggressive |\n| Leiomyosarcoma | High | Malignant smooth muscle tumor, common in retroperitoneum/uterus |\n| Extraskeletal Chondrosarcoma | Intermediate | Often myxoid component, can metastasize |\n| Desmoid Tumor | None (benign but locally aggressive) | Fibromatosis, high local recurrence, not a true sarcoma |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Locally aggressive but rarely metastatic? Think DFSP.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (MRI), DFSP typically appears as a superficial, ill-defined soft tissue mass with infiltrative margins. Intraoperatively, its 'tentacle-like' extensions make achieving clear margins challenging, often necessitating wide local excision or Mohs micrographic surgery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., Version 1.2024). Recommends wide local excision with 2-3 cm margins or Mohs micrographic surgery for DFSP due to its high local recurrence rate and infiltrative nature.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Clear-cell sarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Leiomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Dermatosarcoma protuberans | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Chondrosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Tumors with limited metastatic potential include desmoid, atypical lipomatous tumor (also called wel** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
