  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, radiate the sarcoma out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Radiation therapy is an appropriate adjuvant treatment following wide local excision of a 4-cm leiomyoma of the calf, even with negative margins. This approach is particularly relevant when anatomical constraints limit the extent of surgical margins, aiming to optimize local control and prevent recurrence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSoft tissue sarcomas, such as leiomyomas, have a significant risk of local recurrence despite negative surgical margins, especially in anatomically challenging locations like the calf. Adjuvant radiation therapy plays a crucial role by sterilizing microscopic residual disease that may not be detectable on routine pathology. This significantly reduces the risk of local recurrence, thereby improving long-term local control rates and patient outcomes, even in the setting of apparently negative margins if the initial surgical field was constrained.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Systemic chemotherapy is generally reserved for metastatic disease or high-grade, large, unresectable tumors, not for a localized, resected 4-cm leiomyoma with negative margins and no metastases.\nOption C (Incorrect): Isolated limb perfusion is a regional chemotherapy technique typically used for advanced, recurrent, or unresectable limb sarcomas, not as an initial adjuvant treatment for a small, resected primary tumor.\nOption D (Incorrect): While radiation therapy is appropriate, systemic chemotherapy is not indicated in this specific scenario for a localized, resected tumor without metastases, making the combination inappropriate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Small Localized STS (<5cm) | Large Localized STS (>5cm) | Metastatic STS |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Treatment | Wide local excision +/- Adjuvant RT | Neoadjuvant RT/Chemo, then wide excision +/- Adjuvant RT | Systemic chemotherapy, palliative RT/surgery |\n| Role of RT | Adjuvant for local control, especially with close/positive margins or anatomical constraints | Often neoadjuvant to shrink tumor and facilitate resection, or adjuvant | Palliative for symptom control |\n| Role of Chemo | Rarely indicated | Considered for high-grade tumors, often neoadjuvant | Primary treatment modality |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Localized STS: Surgery is king, RT is queen for local control.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a leiomyoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, often heterogeneous mass with variable signal intensity. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, often encapsulated mass, requiring meticulous dissection to achieve wide margins while preserving critical neurovascular structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., Version 2.2023). They recommend surgery as the primary treatment, with adjuvant radiation therapy considered for high-risk features, positive/close margins, or tumors in anatomically challenging locations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radiation therapy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Systemic chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Isolated limb perfusion of chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Radiation therapy and chemotherapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Small (5 cm) primary tumors with no evidence of distant metastatic disease are managed with local th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
