  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't ignore that growing abdominal lump; it might be a silent killer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The most common presenting symptom of a retroperitoneal sarcoma is a large abdominal mass because these tumors grow insidiously in the spacious retroperitoneal compartment, often reaching significant size before causing noticeable symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRetroperitoneal sarcomas originate in a large, unconfined anatomical space, allowing them to grow extensively without early symptoms. This silent growth pattern means patients typically present with a palpable, often non-tender, abdominal mass as the primary complaint. This late presentation is critical, as these large tumors frequently abut or involve vital structures, making margin-negative (R0) resection challenging and contributing to high locoregional recurrence rates and a poorer prognosis compared to extremity sarcomas.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Ureteral obstruction can occur due to mass effect from a large retroperitoneal sarcoma, but it is typically a secondary symptom, not the most common initial presentation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Rectal obstruction is a less common presentation, usually seen with very large or pelvic retroperitoneal sarcomas, and not the primary presenting symptom.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lower extremity swelling from venous congestion (e.g., IVC compression) is also a consequence of a large tumor mass, not the initial or most common presenting symptom.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Retroperitoneal Sarcoma | Extremity Sarcoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Common Presentation** | Large, often asymptomatic abdominal mass | Painless, growing mass |\n| **Growth Space** | Large, unconfined retroperitoneal space | Confined within muscle compartments |\n| **Resectability** | Often difficult R0 due to vital structure involvement | Generally more amenable to R0 resection |\n| **Prognosis** | Poorer (high locoregional recurrence) | Better (lower locoregional recurrence) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Retroperitoneal sarcomas grow silently, presenting as large masses.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, a retroperitoneal sarcoma typically appears as a large, heterogeneous, often lobulated mass displacing adjacent organs and vessels. Intraoperatively, these tumors are often poorly encapsulated, infiltrating surrounding tissues, making clear margin dissection challenging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., 2023). These guidelines emphasize complete surgical resection as the cornerstone of treatment for retroperitoneal sarcomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A large abdominal mass | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Ureteral obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Rectal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lower extremity swelling fromvenous congestion | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) In contrast to extremity sarcomas, many retroperitoneal sarcomas present as large tumor masses abutt** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
