  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sarcomas hate margins, not lymph nodes.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is local resection with a 3-cm margin. This approach is appropriate because gastrointestinal leiomyosarcomas primarily spread locally and hematogenously, not via the lymphatic system, making extensive gastrectomy or lymphadenectomy unnecessary.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLeiomyosarcomas are mesenchymal tumors, and their surgical management differs significantly from epithelial tumors like adenocarcinomas. The primary goal is to achieve a margin-negative (R0) resection with a wide local margin (typically 2-4 cm) to prevent local recurrence. Lymphatic spread is exceedingly rare, so lymphadenectomy does not improve oncologic outcomes and adds unnecessary morbidity. This targeted approach minimizes surgical invasiveness while maximizing local tumor control.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Subtotal gastrectomy): Incorrect. This is an unnecessarily extensive resection for a 2-cm leiomyosarcoma, as local resection with adequate margins is sufficient and less morbid.\nOption C (Total gastrectomy): Incorrect. This is an even more radical and morbid procedure than subtotal gastrectomy, which is excessive for a small, localized leiomyosarcoma.\nOption D (Total gastrectomy and lymphadenectomy): Incorrect. This is overtreatment. Total gastrectomy is too radical, and lymphadenectomy is not indicated for leiomyosarcomas due to their rare lymphatic spread.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gastric Leiomyosarcoma | Gastric Adenocarcinoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Primary Spread | Local, Hematogenous | Lymphatic, Local, Peritoneal |\n| Lymphadenectomy | Not indicated | Standard of care (D1/D2) |\n| Resection Goal | R0 with wide margins (2-4 cm) | R0 with adequate margins, regional lymphadenectomy |\n| Tumor Type | Mesenchymal | Epithelial |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For sarcomas, think wide local excision, not lymph nodes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a gastric leiomyosarcoma often appears as a well-circumscribed, enhancing, often exophytic mass originating from the muscularis propria. Intraoperatively, it would be a firm, often submucosal or extraluminal mass, requiring careful palpation to define its extent for margin assessment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (e.g., Version 1.2024) recommend wide en bloc resection with negative margins for localized gastrointestinal sarcomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Local resection with 3-cmmargin of normal tissue | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Subtotal gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Total gastrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Total gastrectomy and lymphadenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Lymphatic spread is not the primary route of metastasis for gastrointestinal sarcomas. Consequently,** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
