  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For GIST, Imatinib is the GIST of the matter!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Imatinib is the correct answer because it is the cornerstone of targeted therapy for gastrointestinal stromal tumors (GISTs), specifically inhibiting the c-Kit receptor tyrosine kinase which is commonly mutated in these tumors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGISTs are characterized by activating mutations in the KIT or PDGFRA receptor tyrosine kinase genes. Imatinib, a selective c-Kit inhibitor, revolutionized GIST treatment by directly targeting these aberrant signaling pathways. This targeted therapy leads to impressive clinical responses, often causing tumor regression or stabilization, and significantly improving progression-free and overall survival in patients with unresectable or metastatic GISTs. Its efficacy underscores the importance of molecular diagnostics in guiding cancer therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Doxorubicin) (Incorrect): Doxorubicin is a broad-spectrum anthracycline chemotherapy agent, not a targeted therapy, and has limited efficacy in GISTs compared to imatinib.\nOption C (Bleomycin) (Incorrect): Bleomycin is an antineoplastic antibiotic primarily used for germ cell tumors, lymphomas, and head and neck cancers, and is not indicated for GIST.\nOption D (Methotrexate) (Incorrect): Methotrexate is an antimetabolite used for various malignancies like leukemia, lymphoma, and breast cancer, but it is not a primary treatment for GIST.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drug Name | Mechanism of Action | Primary Indication | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Imatinib | c-Kit/PDGFRA inhibitor | First-line for GIST | Targeted therapy, revolutionized GIST treatment |\n| Sunitinib | Multi-kinase inhibitor | Second-line for GIST (after imatinib failure) | Inhibits KIT, PDGFRA, VEGFR, FLT3 |\n| Regorafenib | Multi-kinase inhibitor | Third-line for GIST (after imatinib/sunitinib failure) | Broad-spectrum kinase inhibitor |\n| Doxorubicin | DNA intercalation, topoisomerase II inhibition | Broad-spectrum chemotherapy | Limited role in GIST, non-targeted |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: GIST = Imatinib. Think targeted therapy for c-Kit mutations.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, GISTs often appear as well-circumscribed, exophytic masses arising from the GI tract wall, frequently showing heterogeneous enhancement. Intraoperatively, they are typically firm, often encapsulated, and may have areas of hemorrhage or necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Soft Tissue Sarcoma (2023): Recommends imatinib as the primary systemic therapy for unresectable, metastatic, or recurrent GIST.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Doxirubicin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Imatinib | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Bleomycin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Methotrexate | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Until recently, systemic treatment options for patient with unresectable or metastatic GIST were of ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
