  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to VSDs, 'peri' means primary, especially for surgeons!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Perimembranous. Perimembranous ventricular septal defects (VSDs) are indeed the most common type, accounting for approximately 80% of cases requiring surgical intervention, as they involve the membranous septum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPerimembranous VSDs are anatomically located in the membranous septum, a critical area of the ventricular septum. Their high prevalence is due to the complex embryological development of this region. These defects are significant because they often require surgical closure and can be associated with other complex malformations, such as those seen in Tetralogy of Fallot (TOF), where they are often malalignment defects.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Supracristal) (Incorrect): Supracristal VSDs are a type of outlet VSD, located in the infundibular septum, and are less common than perimembranous defects.\nOption B (Muscular) (Incorrect): Muscular VSDs are located in the muscular (trabecular) septum. While common, they are often small and may close spontaneously, making them less frequently the most common type requiring intervention compared to perimembranous.\nOption D (AVcanal) (Incorrect): AV canal type VSDs (also known as inlet VSDs) are located in the posterior septum, often associated with atrioventricular valve abnormalities, and are not the most common overall type.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| VSD Type | Location | Prevalence/Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Perimembranous | Membranous septum | Most common (approx. 80% of surgical cases), often associated with TOF |\n| Muscular | Muscular (trabecular) septum | Can be multiple, often close spontaneously |\n| Outlet (Supracristal) | Infundibular septum (below pulmonary valve) | Less common, risk of aortic valve prolapse |\n| Inlet (AV Canal type) | Posterior septum (inlet portion) | Associated with AV valve abnormalities, often part of complete AVSD |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perimembranous VSDs are the most common type, often linked to the membranous septum's embryology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, a perimembranous VSD appears as a defect adjacent to the tricuspid valve annulus and below the aortic valve. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would visualize the defect in the membranous septum, often near the septal leaflet of the tricuspid valve, requiring careful closure to avoid injury to the conduction system.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease: Recommends surgical or transcatheter closure for symptomatic VSDs or those with significant shunting.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Supracristal | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Muscular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Perimembranous | ✅ Correct |\n| D | AVcanal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) VSD refers to a hole between the [left and right ventricles]. These defects are common, comprising 2** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
