  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For tiny hearts with a tight squeeze, surgery is the ultimate fix!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Resection with primary anastomosis. For infants with hemodynamically significant coarctation of the aorta, surgical repair, specifically resection with end-to-end anastomosis, remains the gold standard due to superior long-term outcomes compared to catheter-based interventions in this age group.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSurgical aortoplasty via resection with end-to-end anastomosis directly addresses the anatomical narrowing by removing the coarcted segment and rejoining the healthy aortic ends. This technique allows for complete removal of residual ductal tissue and can be extended (extended end-to-end anastomosis) to correct associated transverse arch hypoplasia, which is common in infants. This comprehensive anatomical correction minimizes the risk of recoarctation and other complications often seen with less definitive interventions in young patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Catheterization with balloon dilation has shown poor results when used for native coarctation in neonates and infants, with higher rates of recoarctation and aneurysm formation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Catheterization with placement of an aortic stent is primarily used in older patients or for recoarctation following surgical repair, not as a primary treatment for infants due to growth considerations and stent-related complications.\nOption C (Incorrect): Surgical aortoplasty, such as the subclavian flap technique, is used less frequently in the modern era due to the risk of late aneurysm formation and potential underdevelopment or ischemia of the left upper extremity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Indication (Age/Condition) | Key Considerations |\n|---|---|---|\n| Surgical Resection with Primary Anastomosis | Infants (<6 months) with native COA | Gold standard, addresses transverse arch hypoplasia, removes ductal tissue |\n| Catheter-based Balloon Dilation | Older patients, recoarctation | Effective for recurrent COA, poor results in native neonates |\n| Catheter-based Stent Implantation | Older patients, recoarctation | Increasingly widespread, avoids open surgery |\n| Subclavian Flap Aortoplasty | Historically used, less common now | Risk of aneurysm, left upper extremity issues |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Infant COA = surgical resection and anastomosis, not cath lab.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiogram or CT angiogram, coarctation appears as a discrete narrowing of the aorta, often distal to the left subclavian artery, with potential associated transverse arch hypoplasia. Intraoperatively, the surgeon identifies the constricted segment, carefully dissects it, and performs a tension-free end-to-end anastomosis after resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease (which often references pediatric management principles) recommends surgical repair as the preferred initial treatment for native coarctation in infants and young children.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Catheterization with balloon dilation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Catheterization with placement of an aortic stent | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Surgical aortoplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Resection with primary anastomosis | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The routine management of hemodynamically significant COA [coarctation] in all age groups has tradit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
