  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get tri-cked, Cor triatriatum divides the left atrium!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Left atrium. Cor triatriatum is a rare congenital heart defect characterized by the presence of a fibromuscular diaphragm that abnormally divides the left atrium into two distinct chambers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThis anatomical division creates a superior chamber that receives drainage from the pulmonary veins and an inferior chamber that communicates with the mitral valve and the left ventricle. This partitioning obstructs pulmonary venous return, leading to increased pressure in the pulmonary circulation and symptoms of pulmonary hypertension and heart failure. Surgical resection of this membrane is typically required to restore normal blood flow.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Right atrium) (Incorrect): While a rare condition known as Cor triatriatum dexter involves the right atrium, the term 'Cor triatriatum' without further specification typically refers to the left atrial anomaly (Cor triatriatum sinister).\nOption C (Left ventricle) (Incorrect): The left ventricle is a pumping chamber and is not divided by a fibromuscular diaphragm in this specific congenital anomaly; such a division would severely impair systemic circulation.\nOption D (Right ventricle) (Incorrect): Similar to the left ventricle, the right ventricle is a pumping chamber and is not divided in this manner in Cor triatriatum; other congenital anomalies affect the right ventricle but not with this specific pathology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Chamber Affected | Key Feature | Clinical Impact |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cor Triatriatum Sinister | Left Atrium | Fibromuscular membrane divides LA | Pulmonary venous obstruction, pulmonary hypertension |\n| Cor Triatriatum Dexter | Right Atrium | Persistent Eustachian/Thebesian valve | Usually asymptomatic, can obstruct IVC/SVC flow |\n| Atrial Septal Defect (ASD) | Atrial Septum | Hole in the interatrial septum | Left-to-right shunt, right heart volume overload |\n| Mitral Stenosis | Mitral Valve | Narrowing of mitral valve orifice | Obstruction to LV inflow, LA enlargement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cor triatriatum sinister means a divided left atrium.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, a distinct fibromuscular membrane will be visualized within the left atrium, dividing it into two compartments. Intraoperatively, this membrane is clearly visible and can be resected to restore normal left atrial anatomy and relieve obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease recommends surgical or transcatheter intervention for symptomatic Cor triatriatum to relieve obstruction and prevent complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Left atrium | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Right atrium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Left ventricle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Right ventricle | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Cor triatriatum is a rare CHD characterized by the presence of a fibromuscular diaphragm that partit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
