  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ebstein's: The tricuspid valve's unfortunate journey into the right ventricle.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Tricuspid. Ebstein’s anomaly is a congenital heart defect characterized by the inferior displacement of the tr tricuspid valve leaflets into the right ventricle, leading to atrialization of a portion of the right ventricle.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEbstein's anomaly primarily affects the tricuspid valve, where the septal and posterior leaflets are displaced apically into the right ventricle. This displacement effectively 'atrializes' a portion of the right ventricle, leading to functional right ventricular hypoplasia and often severe tricuspid regurgitation. The malformation results in right atrial enlargement and can cause right-to-left shunting through an associated atrial septal defect, contributing to cyanosis. The underlying pathology is often considered a defect in right ventricular morphology rather than an isolated valve issue.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Aortic valve is not primarily affected in Ebstein's anomaly.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Mitral valve is not primarily affected in Ebstein's anomaly.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Pulmonary valve is not primarily affected in Ebstein's anomaly.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Valve Affected | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ebstein's Anomaly | Tricuspid | Apical displacement of leaflets, atrialized RV |\n| Rheumatic Heart Disease | Mitral, Aortic | Valvular stenosis/regurgitation post-strep infection |\n| Tetralogy of Fallot | Pulmonary | Pulmonary stenosis, RV outflow obstruction |\n| Bicuspid Aortic Valve | Aortic | Congenital malformation, increased risk of stenosis/regurgitation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ebstein's anomaly is the tricuspid valve's tragic displacement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, one would observe the apical displacement of the septal and posterior tricuspid valve leaflets, often with severe tricuspid regurgitation. The right atrium is typically markedly enlarged, and the functional right ventricle is small. Intraoperatively, the malformed, displaced tricuspid valve leaflets would be evident, with varying degrees of leaflet tethering and dysplasia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease. This guideline provides recommendations for the diagnosis, surveillance, and management, including surgical repair, for Ebstein's anomaly.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Aortic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mitral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pulmonary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tricuspid | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Ebstein’s anomaly is a rare defect, occurring in less than 1% of CHD patients. The predominant malde** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
