  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Aortic valve: The silent congenital anomaly, waiting for its midlife crisis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Aortic. The spectrum of aortic valve abnormality, particularly bicuspid aortic valve, represents the most common form of congenital heart disease (CHD), often remaining asymptomatic until midlife.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCongenital aortic valve abnormalities, predominantly bicuspid aortic valve (BAV), are the most common congenital cardiac malformation, affecting 1-2% of the general population. This condition arises from abnormal fusion of aortic valve leaflets during embryogenesis, leading to a valve with two functional leaflets instead of the normal three. While often asymptomatic for decades, BAV is associated with progressive valvular dysfunction (stenosis or regurgitation), aortic root dilation, and an increased risk of infective endocarditis and aortic dissection, necessitating long-term surveillance and potential surgical intervention.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Mitral) (Incorrect): While mitral valve abnormalities like mitral valve prolapse or cleft mitral valve can be congenital, they are less common as a primary congenital anomaly compared to aortic valve defects.\nOption B (Tricuspid) (Incorrect): Congenital tricuspid valve abnormalities, such as Ebstein's anomaly, are relatively rare compared to aortic valve malformations.\nOption D (Pulmonary) (Incorrect): Congenital pulmonary valve stenosis is a known anomaly, but its overall incidence is significantly lower than that of congenital aortic valve abnormalities.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Valve | Common Congenital Anomaly | Prevalence | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Aortic | Bicuspid Aortic Valve (BAV) | 1-2% of population | Most common CHD, progressive stenosis/regurgitation, aortopathy |\n| Mitral | Cleft Mitral Valve, Mitral Prolapse | Less common than BAV | Can lead to regurgitation, often associated with other defects |\n| Tricuspid | Ebstein's Anomaly | Rare (1 in 20,000 live births) | Apical displacement of leaflets, tricuspid regurgitation, right heart failure |\n| Pulmonary | Pulmonary Stenosis | Less common than BAV | Obstruction to RV outflow, can be isolated or part of complex CHD |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 'A' for Aortic, 'A' for most common congenital valve anomaly.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, a bicuspid aortic valve appears as two leaflets opening eccentrically, often with a raphe (fused commissure). Intraoperatively, the surgeon will observe two distinct cusps, sometimes with a rudimentary third cusp or raphe, instead of the normal trileaflet configuration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2020 ACC/AHA Guideline for the Management of Patients With Valvular Heart Disease: Recommends lifelong surveillance for patients with bicuspid aortic valve due to the risk of progressive dysfunction and associated aortopathy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mitral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Tricuspid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Aortic | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Pulmonary | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The spectrum of aortic valve abnormality represents the most common form of CHD, with the great majo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
