  "question": "Which of the following can be seen in an infant with severe aortic stenosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Crying during feeding",
    "B": "Upper body cyanosis",
    "C": "Hyperactive precordium",
    "D": "Machinery murmur"
  },
  "answer": "A) Neonates and infants with severe valvular AS may have a relatively nonspecific history of irritability and failure to thrive. Angina, if present, is usually manifested by episodic, inconsolable crying that coincides with feeding. As discussed previously, evidence of poor peripheral perfusion, such as extreme pallor, indicates severe left ventricular outflow tract obstruction (LVOTO). Differential cyanosis is an uncommon finding, but is present when enough antegrade flow occurs only to maintain normal upper body perfusion, while a large PDA produces blue discoloration of the abdomen and legs. Hyperactive precordium and machinery murmur are typical findings in a patient with a patent ductus arteriosus. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 595.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Infant angina cries during feeding; severe AS is no joke!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, \"Crying during feeding.\" This symptom in an infant with severe aortic stenosis (AS) is a manifestation of angina, which occurs due to increased myocardial oxygen demand during feeding in the setting of severe left ventricular outflow tract obstruction (LVOTO).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSevere aortic stenosis in infants leads to significant obstruction of blood flow from the left ventricle, increasing afterload and myocardial oxygen demand. During feeding, the infant's metabolic rate and cardiac output increase, exacerbating this demand. When the coronary blood supply cannot meet the increased demand, myocardial ischemia (angina) occurs. In infants, angina is not expressed as chest pain but rather as irritability, inconsolable crying, or fussiness, particularly during periods of stress like feeding. This is a critical indicator of severe disease and potential for decompensation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Upper body cyanosis) (Incorrect): While differential cyanosis can occur in some complex congenital heart diseases, it is not a typical or primary finding in isolated severe aortic stenosis. It is more commonly associated with conditions like a large patent ductus arteriosus (PDA) with right-to-left shunting, where the lower body is cyanotic.\nOption C (Hyperactive precordium) (Incorrect): A hyperactive precordium is typically associated with conditions causing volume overload or significant shunting, such as a large patent ductus arteriosus or ventricular septal defect, not primarily with isolated severe aortic stenosis.\nOption D (Machinery murmur) (Incorrect): A machinery murmur is pathognomonic for a patent ductus arteriosus (PDA) and is not heard in aortic stenosis, which typically presents with a systolic ejection murmur.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Severe Aortic Stenosis (Infant) | Patent Ductus Arteriosus (PDA) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Clinical Manifestation** | Irritability, inconsolable crying (especially during feeding), poor feeding, failure to thrive, pallor | Bounding pulses, wide pulse pressure, signs of heart failure (if large shunt) |\n| **Murmur** | Systolic ejection murmur, often harsh, best heard at upper right sternal border, radiating to neck | Continuous 'machinery' murmur, best heard at left infraclavicular area |\n| **Precordium** | May be quiet or mildly hyperdynamic, signs of LV strain | Hyperactive precordium |\n| **Cyanosis** | Usually acyanotic; severe cases may show poor perfusion/pallor | Acyanotic (left-to-right shunt); differential cyanosis (right-to-left shunt) |\n| **Pathophysiology** | Left ventricular outflow tract obstruction (LVOTO) leading to myocardial ischemia | Shunting of blood from aorta to pulmonary artery |\n| **Treatment** | Balloon valvuloplasty, surgical valvotomy | Indomethacin (preterm), surgical ligation, catheter closure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Infant crying during feeding + pallor = severe LVOTO until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEchocardiography would reveal a thickened, often bicuspid, aortic valve with restricted opening, significant pressure gradient across the valve, and left ventricular hypertrophy with potential for dysfunction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2018 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Management of Adults With Congenital Heart Disease (though focused on adults, principles of AS severity apply to pediatric assessment and management strategies are often derived from similar understanding of pathophysiology).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Crying during feeding | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Upper body cyanosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hyperactive precordium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Machinery murmur | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Neonates and infants with severe valvular AS may have a relatively nonspecific history of irritabili** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
