  "question": "The arterioventricular (AV) node is supplied by the right coronary artery in what percentage of patients?",
  "options": {
    "A": "5%",
    "B": "20%",
    "C": "45%",
    "D": "80%"
  },
  "answer": "D) The left coronary system supplies the major portion of the left ventricular (LV) myocardium through the left main, left anterior descending, and circumflex coronary arteries. The right coronary artery supplies the right ventricle, and the posterior descending artery supplies the inferior wall of the left ventricle. The AV nodal artery arises from the right coronary artery in 80 to 85% of patients, termed right dominant circulation. In 15 to 20% of cases, the circumflex branch of the left coronary system supplies the posterior descending branch and the AV nodal artery, termed left dominant, while 5% are codominant. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 631.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The AV node's beat often dances to the RCA's tune, 80% of the time!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, 80%, because the right coronary artery (RCA) is the primary blood supply to the AV node in the vast majority of patients. This anatomical arrangement is known as right dominant circulation and is a fundamental concept in cardiac anatomy and physiology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCoronary artery dominance is determined by which artery supplies the posterior descending artery (PDA) and, critically for this question, the AV nodal artery. In 80-85% of individuals, the RCA gives rise to the AV nodal artery, establishing right dominance. This anatomical fact means that occlusion of the RCA can significantly impair AV nodal function, leading to bradyarrhythmias or heart block. Understanding this vascular supply is paramount for surgeons performing cardiac procedures or managing patients with coronary artery disease, as it directly impacts conduction system integrity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (5%) (Incorrect): This percentage refers to codominant circulation, where both the RCA and LCx contribute to the PDA, but it is not the primary supply percentage for the AV node from the RCA.\nOption B (20%) (Incorrect): This percentage (15-20%) represents left dominant circulation, where the circumflex artery (LCx) supplies the AV nodal artery, not the RCA.\nOption C (45%) (Incorrect): This percentage is not associated with the AV nodal artery supply from the RCA in standard anatomical descriptions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right Dominant | Left Dominant | Codominant |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Incidence | 80-85% | 15-20% | 5% |\n| AV Nodal Artery Origin | RCA | LCx | RCA and/or LCx |\n| Posterior Descending Artery Origin | RCA | LCx | RCA & LCx |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The RCA supplies the AV node in 80% of patients, defining right dominance.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn coronary angiography, the origin of the AV nodal artery can be visualized, typically arising from the distal RCA in right dominant systems, or from the circumflex artery in left dominant systems. During cardiac surgery, careful dissection near the crux of the heart must account for the variable origin of this critical vessel to avoid iatrogenic injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association (AHA) / American College of Cardiology (ACC) Guidelines for the Management of Patients with Stable Ischemic Heart Disease (2012, updated). These guidelines emphasize understanding coronary anatomy for revascularization strategies and managing complications like AV block, though specific percentages are foundational knowledge rather than guideline recommendations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 5% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 20% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 45% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 80% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The left coronary system supplies the major portion of the left ventricular (LV) myocardium through ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
