  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Three-quarters of CAD patients present with classic angina – don't miss it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 75%. This percentage accurately reflects the proportion of patients with coronary artery disease (CAD) who present with classic angina, as directly stated in the provided clinical information. Understanding this prevalence is crucial for diagnostic assessment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nClassic angina is a distinct clinical entity characterized by precordial pain described as squeezing, heavy, or burning, typically lasting 2 to 10 minutes. It is usually substernal, often radiating to the left shoulder and arm, but can also manifest in the midepigastrium, jaw, right arm, or midscapular region. This pain is predictably provoked by exertion, emotional stress, sexual activity, or eating, and is reliably relieved by rest or nitroglycerin. This consistent presentation allows for a high index of suspicion in 75% of CAD patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (40%) (Incorrect): This percentage is significantly lower than the established prevalence of classic angina in patients with coronary artery disease.\nOption B (56%) (Incorrect): This percentage does not align with the known epidemiological data for classic angina presentation in CAD.\nOption D (90%) (Incorrect): While a high percentage, 90% overestimates the prevalence of classic angina, as approximately 25% of CAD patients present with atypical symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Classic Angina | Atypical Angina |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Prevalence in CAD** | 75% | 25% (more common in women) |\n| **Pain Quality** | Squeezing, heavy, burning | Vague, sharp, pleuritic, positional |\n| **Location/Radiation** | Substernal, radiates to left arm/shoulder, jaw, midepigastric | Less typical locations, often isolated |\n| **Triggers** | Exercise, emotion, sexual activity, eating | Less predictable, often not exertion-related |\n| **Relief** | Rest, nitroglycerin | Variable, less consistent with rest/NTG |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember that classic angina is the predominant presentation in CAD, affecting three out of four patients.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCoronary angiography would reveal stenoses or occlusions in the coronary arteries, which are the anatomical basis for angina. Stress testing (ECG, echocardiography, or nuclear) would demonstrate inducible myocardial ischemia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 AHA/ACC/ASE/CHEST/SAEM/SCCT/SCMR Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain. This guideline recommends a structured approach to chest pain evaluation, including risk stratification and appropriate diagnostic testing for suspected coronary artery disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 40% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 56% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 75% | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 90% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Classic angina is precordial pain described as squeezing, heavy, or burning in nature, lasting from ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
