  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 One block, big shock: Class III angina's knock!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Canadian Cardiovascular Society (CCS) Class III angina is characterized by marked limitation of ordinary physical activity, with symptoms occurring after walking one or two blocks on level ground or climbing one flight of stairs. This classification helps standardize the assessment of angina severity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe CCS classification system provides a standardized, reproducible method for assessing the severity of stable angina pectoris, which is crucial for guiding treatment decisions and evaluating prognosis. Angina results from an imbalance between myocardial oxygen supply and demand, typically due to coronary artery disease. The CCS classes correlate the level of physical activity required to induce symptoms with the degree of myocardial ischemia, reflecting the functional impact of the underlying coronary stenosis. This system is widely used in clinical practice and research to stratify patients and monitor their response to therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): CCS Class I angina is characterized by angina only with strenuous, rapid, or prolonged exertion.\nOption B (Incorrect): CCS Class II angina involves slight limitation of ordinary activity, with angina occurring with walking or climbing stairs rapidly, walking uphill, or after meals/stress, or in cold/wind, but typically allows walking more than two blocks.\nOption D (Incorrect): CCS Class IV angina signifies an inability to carry on any physical activity without discomfort, with anginal symptoms often present at rest.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| CCS Class | Activity Level Causing Angina | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| I | Strenuous, rapid, or prolonged exertion | No limitation of ordinary physical activity |\n| II | Slight limitation of ordinary activity | Angina with walking or climbing stairs rapidly, walking uphill, or after meals/stress; walking >2 blocks |\n| III | Marked limitation of ordinary activity | Angina after walking 1-2 blocks on level ground or climbing 1 flight of stairs |\n| IV | Inability to carry on any physical activity | Anginal symptoms may be present at rest |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: One block, big shock: Class III angina's knock!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn coronary angiography, significant stenosis (>70% luminal narrowing) in one or more major epicardial coronary arteries would be expected. During a stress test (e.g., exercise ECG, stress echocardiography, or nuclear stress test), evidence of myocardial ischemia (e.g., ST-segment depression, wall motion abnormalities, or perfusion defects) would be observed at a low workload.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2021 AHA/ACC/ASE/CHEST/SAEM/SCCT/SCMR Guideline for the Evaluation and Diagnosis of Chest Pain: Recommends using symptom-based classifications like CCS to assess angina severity and guide subsequent diagnostic and therapeutic strategies for stable ischemic heart disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Canadian Cardiovascular Society Class I angina | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Canadian Cardiovascular Society Class II angina | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Canadian Cardiovascular Society Class III angina | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Canadian Cardiovascular Society Class IVangina | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 629, and Table 21-1.)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
