  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Myxoma: The heart's most common, usually benign, unwelcome guest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Myxoma. This is the most common primary cardiac tumor, accounting for a significant percentage of all primary cardiac neoplasms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary cardiac tumors are rare, with myxomas being the most frequent type, comprising 30-50% of all primary cardiac neoplasms. Myxomas are typically benign and most commonly originate in the left atrium, often presenting with symptoms related to obstruction or embolization. Their prevalence significantly outweighs other benign and all malignant primary cardiac tumors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Angiosarcoma is the most common malignant primary cardiac tumor, but overall, malignant tumors are less common than benign ones like myxoma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Fibroma is a benign primary cardiac tumor, but it is much less common than myxoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Fibrosarcoma is a malignant primary cardiac tumor and is significantly less common than myxoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Nature | Relative Frequency | Common Location | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Myxoma | Benign | Most common primary (30-50%) | Left Atrium | Can cause obstruction/embolism |\n| Angiosarcoma | Malignant | Most common malignant | Right Atrium | Aggressive, poor prognosis |\n| Fibroma | Benign | Less common benign | Ventricles | Can cause arrhythmias |\n| Rhabdomyoma | Benign | Most common in children | Ventricles | Often associated with tuberous sclerosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Myxoma is the most common primary cardiac tumor, usually benign and in the left atrium.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, myxomas typically appear as a mobile, heterogeneous mass, often pedunculated, attached to the interatrial septum in the left atrium. Intraoperatively, they are gelatinous, friable, and often have a villous surface.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nDue to the rarity of primary cardiac tumors, specific dedicated guidelines are less common. However, major cardiology societies like the American Heart Association (AHA) and European Society of Cardiology (ESC) provide recommendations for cardiac imaging (e.g., echocardiography, MRI) which are crucial for diagnosis and management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Myxoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Angiosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fibroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fibrosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Primary cardiac neoplasms are rare, reported to occur with incidences ranging from0.001 to 0.3% in a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
