  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When pain tears through, think dissection, or you'll be torn apart.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Pain. This question correctly identifies that severe pain is the cardinal and most common symptom in patients presenting with acute aortic dissection, making its recognition crucial for timely diagnosis and intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute aortic dissection is characterized by sudden, severe pain, which is experienced by 80-90% of patients. This pain typically has a sharp or tearing quality and often migrates distally as the dissection propagates along the aorta. The onset of this pain is clinically significant as it generally marks the beginning of the dissection process, which is critical for classification (acute vs. sub-acute vs. chronic) and management decisions. Its high prevalence and distinct characteristics make it the most reliable initial indicator.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Shortness of breath) (Incorrect): While shortness of breath can occur in aortic dissection, often due to heart failure, pleural effusion, or pericardial tamponade, it is a secondary manifestation and not the most common initial symptom.\nOption C (Palpitations) (Incorrect): Palpitations are a non-specific symptom that can be associated with anxiety or arrhythmias, but they are not a primary or common presenting symptom of acute aortic dissection.\nOption D (Syncope) (Incorrect): Syncope can occur in acute aortic dissection due to severe hypotension, cardiac tamponade, or cerebral malperfusion, indicating a more advanced or complicated presentation. However, it is less common than severe pain as the initial symptom.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Symptom | Prevalence in Acute Aortic Dissection | Characteristics |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Pain** | 80-90% | Sudden onset, severe, sharp/tearing, often migrating (chest, back, abdomen) |\n| Syncope | ~10-20% | Loss of consciousness due to hypoperfusion (cardiac tamponade, severe hypotension, cerebral ischemia) |\n| Shortness of Breath | Variable (secondary) | Due to heart failure, pleural effusion, pericardial tamponade, or lung ischemia |\n| Palpitations | Less common | Non-specific, may indicate arrhythmia or anxiety |\n| Neurologic Deficits | ~10-20% | Stroke, paraplegia, due to branch vessel occlusion |\n| Pulse Deficits | ~15-30% | Absent or diminished pulses due to branch vessel involvement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 'pain, sudden, tearing' for aortic dissection until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, an intimal flap separating the true and false lumens is the pathognomonic sign of aortic dissection. You may also see evidence of thrombus in the false lumen, branch vessel involvement, or pericardial effusion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2014 ESC Guidelines on the Diagnosis and Treatment of Aortic Diseases emphasize the critical role of early suspicion and diagnosis, highlighting severe pain as the most common presenting symptom.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Shortness of breath | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pain | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Palpitations | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Syncope | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The European Society of Cardiology Task Force onAortic Dissection stated, ‘The main challenge in man** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
