  "question": "Which of the following is NOT a typical complication of an acute ascending aortic dissection?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Myocardial infarction",
    "B": "Pleural effusion",
    "C": "Aortic valve regurgitation",
    "D": "Pericardial effusion"
  },
  "answer": "B) Ascending aortic dissection can directly injure the aortic valve, causing regurgitation. The severity of the regurgitation varies with the degree of commissural disruption, which ranges from partial separation of only one commissure, producing mild valvular regurgitation, to full separation of all three commissures and complete prolapse of the valve into the left ventricle, producing severe acute heart failure. Ascending dissections also can extend into the coronary arteries or shear the coronary ostia off of the true lumen, causing acute coronary occlusion; when this occurs, it most often involves the right coronary artery. The sudden disruption of coronary blood flow can cause a myocardial infarction. The thin and inflamed outer wall of a dissected ascending aorta often produces a serosanguineous pericardial effusion that can accumulate and cause tamponade. Suggestive signs include jugular venous distention, muffled heart tones, pulsus paradoxus, and low voltage electrocardiogram (ECG) tracings. Free rupture into the pericardial space produces rapid tamponade and is generally fatal. As the dissection progresses, any branch vessel from the aorta can become involved, which results in compromised blood flow and ischemic complications (i.e., malperfusion). Therefore, depending on which arteries are involved, the dissection can produce acute stroke, paraplegia, hepatic failure, bowel infarction, renal failure, or a threatened ischemic limb. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 688, and Table 22-3.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ascending dissection: Think heart, not just chest fluid!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Pleural effusion. While possible in severe cases or with rupture, pleural effusion is NOT considered a typical direct complication of an acute ascending aortic dissection compared to myocardial infarction, aortic regurgitation, or pericardial effusion, which result from direct extension or compression.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute ascending aortic dissection frequently leads to acute aortic regurgitation due to direct injury and disruption of the aortic valve commissures. Myocardial infarction is a common and critical complication resulting from the dissection extending into or shearing off the coronary artery ostia, most often the right coronary artery. Furthermore, the thin, inflamed outer wall of the dissected ascending aorta commonly leaks serosanguineous fluid, leading to a pericardial effusion, which can rapidly progress to life-threatening cardiac tamponade.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Myocardial infarction is a typical complication. The dissection can extend into coronary arteries or shear off coronary ostia, most often the right coronary artery, causing acute coronary occlusion and MI.\nOption C (Incorrect): Aortic valve regurgitation is a typical complication. The dissection can injure the aortic valve, causing regurgitation due to commissural disruption, ranging from mild to severe.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pericardial effusion is a typical complication. The thin, inflamed outer wall of the dissected aorta often produces a serosanguineous pericardial effusion, which can lead to tamponade.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism in Ascending Aortic Dissection | Typicality |\n|---|---|---|\n| Myocardial Infarction | Coronary artery involvement (e.g., RCA ostia shearing) | High |\n| Aortic Regurgitation | Aortic valve commissural disruption/prolapse | High |\n| Pericardial Effusion | Serosanguineous leakage from dissected wall or rupture | High |\n| Pleural Effusion | Indirectly from heart failure or rupture into pleural space (less direct) | Lower / Atypical |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ascending dissection = heart, coronary, and pericardial issues.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, a double-lumen aorta with an intimal flap is the hallmark. Pericardial effusion and coronary artery involvement can also be visualized. Intraoperatively, a dilated, friable ascending aorta with an intimal tear is typically found, often with associated aortic valve pathology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2022 AHA/ACC Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Aortic Disease. Recommends prompt diagnosis and emergent surgical repair for acute Type A aortic dissection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Myocardial infarction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pleural effusion | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Aortic valve regurgitation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pericardial effusion | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Ascending aortic dissection can directly injure the aortic valve, causing regurgitation. The severit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
