  "options": {
    "A": "Transesophageal echocardiography",
    "B": "CT scan",
    "C": "Chest x-ray",
    "D": "Aortography"
  },
  "answer": "B) Contrast-enhanced CT has a sensitivity of 98% and a specificity of 87% for diagnosis of aortic dissection. Although MRA is now considered the gold standard, with both a sensitivity and a specificity of 98%, CT scanning is the preferred imaging modality in the emergency department, mainly because of its swift image acquisition. In appropriate hands, TEE has a demonstrated sensitivity and specificity as high as 98 and 95%, respectively. Furthermore, TEE offers important information about ventricular function and aortic valve competency. Finally, TEE is the diagnostic modality of choice for hemodynamically unstable patients in whom the diagnosis of ascending dissection is suspected; ideally, these patients should be taken to the operating room, where the TEE can be performed and, if the TEE is confirmatory, surgery can be started immediately. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 689.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the aorta tears, CT clears the air.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is CT scan. For a hemodynamically stable patient with suspected acute thoracic aortic dissection, contrast-enhanced CT is the imaging study of choice due to its rapid acquisition, wide availability, and high diagnostic accuracy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nContrast-enhanced CT offers an excellent balance of speed, sensitivity (98%), and specificity (87%) for diagnosing aortic dissection, making it ideal in the emergency setting. While MRA boasts slightly higher accuracy (98% sensitivity and specificity), its longer acquisition time makes CT the preferred initial modality. TEE is highly accurate and provides additional functional information, but its invasiveness and operator dependence make it less suitable as the primary diagnostic tool for stable patients compared to CT.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Transesophageal echocardiography) (Incorrect): TEE is highly accurate and useful for hemodynamically unstable patients or as an intraoperative tool, but it is more invasive and operator-dependent than CT, making it not the first choice for stable patients.\nOption C (Chest x-ray) (Incorrect): A chest x-ray may show suggestive findings like a widened mediastinum, but it is neither sensitive nor specific enough to diagnose aortic dissection and cannot rule it out.\nOption D (Aortography) (Incorrect): Aortography is an invasive procedure with associated risks, and it has largely been replaced by non-invasive modalities like CT and MRA due to its lower diagnostic yield and longer procedure time.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Sensitivity | Specificity | Speed | Invasiveness | Ideal Use |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| CT Angiography | 98% | 87% | Fast | Non-invasive | Stable patient, ED setting |\n| MRA | 98% | 98% | Slow | Non-invasive | Stable patient, follow-up, contraindication to CT contrast |\n| TEE | 98% | 95% | Fast (operator-dependent) | Invasive | Unstable patient, intraoperative, valve assessment |\n| Chest X-ray | Low | Low | Very Fast | Non-invasive | Screening, initial broad assessment (not diagnostic) |\n| Aortography | Variable | Variable | Slow | Invasive | Historical, complex cases (rarely primary) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For stable aortic dissection, CT is king due to speed and accuracy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a contrast-enhanced CT scan, an aortic dissection appears as an intimal flap separating the true lumen from the false lumen, often with differential enhancement and compression of the true lumen. Thrombus may be present in the false lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2010 ACCF/AHA/AATS Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Patients With Thoracic Aortic Disease recommend contrast-enhanced CT as the initial imaging modality for suspected acute aortic syndromes in hemodynamically stable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Transesophageal echocardiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CT scan | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Chest x-ray | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Aortography | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Contrast-enhanced CT has a sensitivity of 98% and a specificity of 87% for diagnosis of aortic disse** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
