  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, go medial for posterior relief!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Deep posterior compartment. This question tests your knowledge of the anatomical approach to a four-compartment fasciotomy, specifically which compartments are accessed via the medial incision. The medial incision is strategically placed to decompress the posterior compartments.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA four-compartment fasciotomy of the leg is a critical procedure for compartment syndrome, requiring precise anatomical knowledge. The medial incision is designed to access both the superficial and deep posterior compartments. This approach minimizes neurovascular injury while effectively decompressing the muscle groups. The lateral incision, conversely, is used to open the anterior and peroneal (lateral) compartments, ensuring complete decompression of all four major compartments of the lower leg. Understanding this division is crucial for effective surgical intervention and preventing permanent muscle and nerve damage.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Anterior compartment) (Incorrect): The anterior compartment is accessed through the lateral incision, not the medial incision.\nOption C (Peroneal compartment) (Incorrect): The peroneal (lateral) compartment is accessed through the lateral incision, not the medial incision.\nOption D (None of the above) (Incorrect): The deep posterior compartment is indeed opened through the medial incision, making this option incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Incision Type | Compartments Decompressed |\n|---|---|\n| Medial Incision | Superficial Posterior, Deep Posterior |\n| Lateral Incision | Anterior, Peroneal (Lateral) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medial incision for posterior compartments; lateral for anterior and peroneal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after making the skin incision, you would identify the fascia and make long, parallel incisions through it to expose the bulging muscle bellies of the superficial and deep posterior compartments through the medial approach. The muscle should visibly relax and expand once the fascia is released.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEastern Association for the Surgery of Trauma (EAST) Practice Management Guidelines for the Management of Compartment Syndrome (2019): Recommends fasciotomy for clinical diagnosis of compartment syndrome or elevated compartment pressures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anterior compartment | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Deep posterior compartment | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Peroneal compartment | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Compartment pressures are relieved in the leg by medial and lateral incisions. Through the medial in** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
