  "question": "What is the approximate 90-day risk of a stroke in a patient with a transient ischemic attack?",
  "options": {
    "A": "2%",
    "B": "10-15%",
    "C": "25-30%",
    "D": "40-50%"
  },
  "answer": "B) Conventionally, patients with carotid bifurcation occlusive disease are divided into two broad categories: patients without prior history of ipsilateral stroke or transient ischemic attack (TIA) (asymptomatic) and those with prior or current ipsilateral neurologic symptoms (symptomatic). It is estimated that 15% of all strokes are preceded by a TIA. The 90-day risk of a stroke in a patient presenting with a TIA is 3 to 17%. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 715.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A TIA is a stroke's dress rehearsal; don't miss the show!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 10-15%. This option accurately reflects the significant short-term risk of a subsequent stroke following a transient ischemic attack (TIA), emphasizing the urgency of evaluation and intervention.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA TIA is a critical warning sign, representing a temporary episode of neurological dysfunction caused by focal brain, spinal cord, or retinal ischemia, without acute infarction. While symptoms resolve, the underlying pathology (often carotid stenosis or cardiac emboli) remains, placing the patient at high risk for a full-blown stroke. The 90-day risk of stroke after a TIA is estimated to be between 3% and 17%, with many studies converging around the 10-15% mark. This high short-term risk underscores the need for immediate diagnostic workup and aggressive secondary prevention strategies to mitigate future cerebrovascular events.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 2% is too low and significantly underestimates the acute stroke risk following a TIA, which is a high-risk period for patients.\nOption C (Incorrect): 25-30% is too high and overestimates the 90-day stroke risk after a TIA, although the lifetime risk is substantial.\nOption D (Incorrect): 40-50% is drastically too high and does not reflect the actual 90-day stroke risk following a TIA.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Definition | Duration | 90-day Stroke Risk (approx.) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA) | Temporary neurological dysfunction due to ischemia, no acute infarction | Typically <24 hours, often <1 hour | 3-17% (often cited as 10-15%) |\n| Minor Stroke | Acute infarction with mild, non-disabling symptoms | Persistent | Higher than TIA, but variable |\n| Major Stroke | Acute infarction with significant, disabling neurological deficits | Persistent | High, depending on severity and location |\n| Asymptomatic Carotid Stenosis | Carotid stenosis without prior ipsilateral neurological symptoms | N/A | ~1-2% per year for severe stenosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: TIA is a stroke warning; act fast, risk is high.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., MRI brain), a TIA is characterized by the absence of acute infarction. Carotid duplex ultrasound or CTA neck would often reveal significant carotid stenosis, which is a common etiology requiring surgical consideration.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAHA/ASA Guidelines for the Prevention of Stroke in Patients with Stroke and Transient Ischemic Attack (2021) recommend urgent evaluation and management of TIA patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 10-15% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 25-30% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 40-50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Conventionally, patients with carotid bifurcation occlusive disease are divided into two broad categ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
