  "answer": "A) Lifelong follow-up is essential to the long-term success after endovascular AAA repair. Indeed, one may go so far as to say that absence of appropriate follow-up is tantamount to not having had a repair at all. A triple-phase (noncontrast, contrast, delayed) spiral CT scan and a four-view (anteroposterior, lateral, and two obliques) abdominal x-ray should be obtained within the first month. Subsequent imaging can be obtained at 6-month intervals in the first 1 to 2 years and yearly thereafter. The primary success rate after endovascular repair of AAA has been reported to be as high as 95%. The less invasive nature of this procedure is appealing to many physicians and patients. In addition, virtually all reports indicate decreased blood loss, transfusion requirements, and length of ICU and hospital stay for endovascular repair of AAAs when compared to the standard surgical approach. With the advent of bifurcated grafts and improved delivery systems in the future, the only real limitation will be cost. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 728.) The in-hospital costs for both endovascular and open repair include graft cost, OR fees, radiology, pharmacy, ancillary care, ICU charges, and floor charges. Despite the improved morbidity and mortality rates, several early studies have reported no cost benefit with the application of endovascular repair. The limiting factor appears to be the cost of the device. Despite commercialization of endovascular repair, the device costs are still in the range of $5000 to $6000 with no signs of abating. A recent report by Angle and associates further corroborates previous studies. In their review, despite decreased hospital and ICU stays and use of pharmacy and respiratory services, cost of endovascular repair was 1.74 times greater than the standard surgical approach. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 729.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 EVAR: Less cut, more scan, forever the plan!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Endovascular repair (EVAR) of an abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) necessitates lifelong follow-up imaging because, despite being less invasive, it carries a risk of late complications such as endoleaks, device migration, and aneurysm sac expansion, which can lead to rupture if not detected and managed proactively.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLifelong follow-up imaging, typically involving triple-phase CT scans and abdominal X-rays, is paramount after EVAR to ensure the continued integrity and function of the endograft. This surveillance aims to detect endoleaks, which are persistent blood flows into the aneurysm sac that can lead to its repressurization and rupture. It also monitors for changes in aneurysm sac size, graft migration, or structural integrity issues. This continuous monitoring is a critical component of EVAR's long-term success, distinguishing it from open repair where the aneurysm is directly excluded and less intensive follow-up is generally required.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Endovascular repair typically results in decreased blood loss and, consequently, reduced transfusion requirements compared to open repair due to its minimally invasive nature.\nOption C (Incorrect): Endovascular repair generally costs more than open repair, primarily driven by the high cost of the endograft device itself, despite shorter hospital and ICU stays.\nOption D (Incorrect): Endovascular repair is associated with shorter ICU and overall hospital stays compared to open repair, reflecting its less invasive profile and quicker patient recovery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Endovascular Repair (EVAR) | Open Repair |\n|---|---|---|\n| Invasiveness | Less invasive | More invasive |\n| Blood Loss | Decreased | Increased |\n| ICU/Hospital Stay | Shorter | Longer |\n| Transfusion Req. | Decreased | Increased |\n| Cost | Higher (device cost) | Lower |\n| Follow-up | Lifelong imaging | Less intensive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: EVAR is less invasive but demands lifelong imaging surveillance for safety.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPost-EVAR imaging typically involves a triple-phase spiral CT scan (noncontrast, contrast, delayed) to detect endoleaks (contrast within the sac outside the graft) and monitor aneurysm sac size. Four-view abdominal X-rays are used to assess graft integrity, position, and potential fractures of the stent components.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms (e.g., 2018). These guidelines strongly recommend lifelong surveillance with imaging after EVAR to detect and manage potential complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Requires lifelong follow-up imaging | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Results in an increased transfusion requirement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Costs about the same | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Results in longer ICUstays | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Lifelong follow-up is essential to the long-term success after endovascular AAA repair. Indeed, one ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
