  "id": 120491,
  "question": "The 10-year patency rate for aortobifemoral bypass grafts is approximately",
  "options": {
    "A": "30%",
    "B": "50%",
    "C": "70%",
    "D": "90%"
  },
  "answer": "C) Surgical options for treatment of aortoiliac occlusive diseases consist of various configurations of aortobifemoral bypass (ABF) grafting, various types of extra-anatomic bypass grafts, and aortoiliac endarterectomy. The procedure performed is determined by several factors, including anatomic distribution of the disease, clinical condition of the patient, and personal preference of the surgeon. In most cases, ABF is performed because patients usually have disease in both iliac systems. Although one side may be more severely affected than the other, progression does occur, and bilateral bypass does not complicate the procedure or add to the physiologic stress of the operation. ABF reliably relieves symptoms, has excellent long-term patency (approximately 70 to 75% at 10 years), and can be completed with a tolerable perioperative mortality (2 to 3%). (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 745.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For aortoiliac disease, ABF is the bypass king with a 70% 10-year reign!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, 70%, because aortobifemoral bypass (ABF) grafts demonstrate excellent long-term patency, reliably achieving approximately 70-75% at 10 years. This makes ABF a highly effective surgical option for aortoiliac occlusive disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAortobifemoral bypass is the gold standard for extensive aortoiliac occlusive disease, particularly when bilateral involvement is present, as it addresses disease progression effectively. The procedure involves bypassing the diseased aortoiliac segment with a prosthetic graft, typically from the infrarenal aorta to both common femoral arteries. This anatomical configuration ensures robust inflow to both lower extremities, leading to reliable symptom relief and the observed high long-term patency rates, coupled with a low perioperative mortality of 2-3%.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 30% is significantly lower than the established 10-year patency rate for aortobifemoral bypass grafts, which is known to be excellent.\nOption B (Incorrect): 50% underestimates the robust long-term patency achieved by aortobifemoral bypass, which is a highly effective revascularization strategy.\nOption D (Incorrect): 90% is an overestimation of the 10-year patency rate for aortobifemoral bypass grafts, although patency is indeed very good, it typically falls in the 70-75% range.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Procedure | 10-year Patency | Indication/Note |\n|---|---|---|\n| Aortobifemoral Bypass (ABF) | 70-75% | Gold standard for extensive bilateral aortoiliac occlusive disease |\n| Extra-anatomic Bypass (e.g., axillofemoral) | 30-50% | Reserved for high-risk patients unable to tolerate ABF; generally lower patency |\n| Aortoiliac Endarterectomy | Variable (often lower than ABF) | Localized disease, good for common iliac artery lesions; less durable for extensive disease |\n| Femoropopliteal Bypass | 50-60% (vein graft) | Infrainguinal disease; patency varies significantly with conduit and outflow |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: ABF is the gold standard for aortoiliac disease, boasting excellent 10-year patency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, an aortobifemoral bypass involves anastomosing a bifurcated prosthetic graft (Dacron or PTFE) to the infrarenal aorta proximally and to both common femoral arteries distally, lying retroperitoneally and then subcutaneously in the groin. On CT angiography, the patent graft would appear as a brightly enhanced, well-perfused conduit bypassing the occluded native aortoiliac segments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 ACC/AHA/SCAI Guideline for the Management of Patients With Peripheral Artery Disease. It recommends aortobifemoral bypass as a Class I indication for symptomatic aortoiliac occlusive disease, especially for extensive disease, due to its excellent long-term patency and durability.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 30% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 50% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 70% | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 90% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Surgical options for treatment of aortoiliac occlusive diseases consist of various configurations of** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
