  "id": 120510,
  "question": "Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) occurs most commonly",
  "options": {
    "A": "Within 24 hours of starting therapy",
    "B": "3 days after starting therapy",
    "C": "7 days after starting therapy",
    "D": "14 days after starting therapy"
  },
  "answer": "C) Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) results from heparin-associated antiplatelet antibodies (HAAbs) directed against platelet factor 4 complexed with heparin. HIT occurs in 1 to 5% of patients being treated with heparin. In patients with repeat heparin exposure (such as vascular surgery patients), the incidence of HAAb may be as high as 21%. HIT occurs most frequently in the second week of therapy and may lead to disastrous venous or arterial thrombotic complications. Therefore, platelet counts should be monitored periodically in patients receiving continuous heparin therapy. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 785.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When platelets drop on heparin, think HIT, especially after a week!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, as Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) most commonly manifests in the second week of therapy, with day 7 being a representative time point. This immune-mediated complication is critical to recognize due to its thrombotic potential.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHIT is an immune-mediated adverse drug reaction caused by antibodies against platelet factor 4 (PF4) complexed with heparin. These antibodies activate platelets, leading to thrombocytopenia and paradoxically, a prothrombotic state. The typical onset is 5-10 days after heparin initiation, allowing time for antibody formation. Early recognition and monitoring of platelet counts are crucial to prevent disastrous venous or arterial thrombotic complications, which can be limb- or life-threatening.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Within 24 hours of starting therapy is too early for immune-mediated HIT (Type II). This timing is more consistent with non-immune heparin-associated thrombocytopenia (Type I), which is benign.\nOption B (Incorrect): 3 days after starting therapy is still too early for the typical immune response seen in HIT Type II, which generally requires 5-10 days for antibody development.\nOption D (Incorrect): 14 days after starting therapy is within the possible range, but the 'most common' onset is earlier in the second week, typically around day 7-10, making 7 days a more accurate representation of the peak incidence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | HIT Type I (Non-immune) | HIT Type II (Immune-mediated) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Onset | Within 2 days | 5-10 days (often around day 7) |\n| Platelet Count | Mild drop, usually >100,000 | Significant drop, <100,000 or >50% drop |\n| Mechanism | Direct effect of heparin on platelets | Antibody-mediated (PF4-heparin complex) |\n| Clinical Significance | Benign, no thrombosis | High risk of thrombosis (venous/arterial) |\n| Management | Continue heparin | Discontinue heparin, start alternative anticoagulant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HIT hits around day 7, not day 1.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/US), one might see evidence of new or worsening deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), or arterial thrombosis (e.g., limb ischemia, mesenteric ischemia) in a patient on heparin, prompting investigation for HIT.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Hematology (ASH) 2018 Guidelines for the Management of Heparin-Induced Thrombocytopenia. These guidelines recommend discontinuing all heparin products and initiating a non-heparin anticoagulant (e.g., argatroban, bivalirudin) if HIT is suspected.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Within 24 hours of starting therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3 days after starting therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 7 days after starting therapy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 14 days after starting therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Heparin-induced thrombocytopenia (HIT) results from heparin-associated antiplatelet antibodies (HAAb** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
