  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When anticoagulation fails or can't flow, the IVC filter is the way to go!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, \"All of the above.\" This is because all three options (recurrent DVT despite adequate anticoagulation, contraindication for anticoagulation in a patient with proximal DVT, and pulmonary hypertension with recurrent pulmonary embolism) represent established indications for inferior vena cava (IVC) filter placement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIVC filters are mechanical devices designed to prevent pulmonary embolism (PE) by trapping thrombi originating from the lower extremities or pelvic veins before they reach the pulmonary circulation. Their primary role is in situations where the patient is at high risk for PE and anticoagulation is either ineffective, contraindicated, or has failed. This includes patients with recurrent VTE despite therapeutic anticoagulation, those with acute proximal DVT who cannot receive anticoagulation due to bleeding risk, or patients with severe cardiopulmonary compromise (like pulmonary hypertension) where even a small PE could be fatal.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Recurrent deep vein thrombosis (DVT) despite adequate anticoagulation is a correct indication, but it is not the *only* indication, making 'All of the above' the better answer.\nOption B (Incorrect): Contraindication for anticoagulation in a patient with proximal DVT is a correct indication, but it is not the *only* indication, making 'All of the above' the better answer.\nOption C (Incorrect): Pulmonary hypertension with recurrent pulmonary embolism is a correct indication, but it is not the *only* indication, making 'All of the above' the better answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication Category | Specific Scenario |\n|:--------------------|:--------------------|\n| Absolute Contraindication to Anticoagulation | Active bleeding, recent intracranial hemorrhage, severe thrombocytopenia |\n| Failure of Anticoagulation | Recurrent DVT or PE despite therapeutic anticoagulation |\n| High Risk for PE with Contraindication | Acute proximal DVT with high bleeding risk |\n| High Risk for PE with Severe Cardiopulmonary Compromise | Recurrent PE in patients with severe pulmonary hypertension |\n| Prophylactic (Limited Use) | Select high-risk trauma patients, bariatric surgery with prior VTE (controversial) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: IVC filters are for failed or contraindicated anticoagulation in high-risk VTE.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn fluoroscopy during placement, the filter is deployed typically below the renal veins. On CT or X-ray, it appears as a metallic, often conical or umbrella-shaped device within the IVC, with struts extending to the vessel walls.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Chest Physicians (ACCP) Guidelines 2016: Recommend against routine use of IVC filters and reserve them for patients with acute VTE who have an absolute contraindication to anticoagulation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Recurrent deep vein thrombosis (DVT) despite adequate anticoagulation | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Contraindication for anticoagulation in a patient with proximal DVT | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pulmonary hypertension with recurrent pulmonary embolism | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Placement of an IVC filter is indicated for patients who develop recurrent DVT (significant propagat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
