  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut until you know which side is the culprit!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. With bilaterally enlarged adrenals and hyperaldosteronism, selective venous catheterization (SVC) is essential to differentiate between unilateral aldosterone-producing adenoma (APA) and bilateral adrenal hyperplasia (BAH) before deciding on surgical or medical management. CT alone cannot reliably distinguish these.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSelective venous catheterization with adrenal vein sampling (AVS) is the gold standard for lateralizing aldosterone production in patients with primary hyperaldosteronism, especially when imaging is equivocal or shows bilateral changes. It boasts high sensitivity (95%) and specificity (90%) for localizing an aldosteronoma. This differentiation is critical because unilateral disease (APA) is curable with adrenalectomy, while bilateral hyperplasia is typically managed medically, as only a small percentage (20-30%) benefit from surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Unilateral adrenalectomy) (Incorrect): This is premature. While unilateral adrenalectomy is curative for a unilateral adenoma, the CT shows bilateral enlargement without a mass, necessitating further localization with SVC before considering surgery.\nOption B (Bilateral adrenalectomy) (Incorrect): Bilateral adrenalectomy is rarely performed due to the lifelong need for corticosteroid replacement and is not indicated as a primary intervention for bilateral hyperplasia, which is usually managed medically.\nOption D (Medical management) (Incorrect): While many patients with bilateral hyperplasia will ultimately receive medical management, it is not the *most appropriate next intervention*. SVC is crucial to identify the subset of patients who might benefit from unilateral surgery if a lateralizing source is found, thereby offering a potential cure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Aldosterone-Producing Adenoma (APA) | Bilateral Adrenal Hyperplasia (BAH) |\n|---|---|---|\n| CT Scan | Often shows unilateral nodule/mass | Bilateral enlargement or normal |\n| AVS | Lateralizing aldosterone gradient | No significant lateralization |\n| Treatment | Unilateral adrenalectomy (curative) | Medical management (spironolactone, eplerenone) |\n| Surgical Benefit | High (cure hypertension) | Low (20-30% benefit from surgery if lateralizing) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilateral adrenals + hyperaldosteronism = AVS before surgery.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCT scan shows bilaterally enlarged adrenals without a distinct mass. Adrenal vein sampling (AVS) involves catheterizing both adrenal veins to measure aldosterone and cortisol levels, looking for a significant aldosterone-to-cortisol ratio gradient on one side, indicating lateralization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Primary Aldosteronism (2016) recommends adrenal vein sampling for all patients with primary aldosteronism who are candidates for adrenalectomy, especially when CT imaging is normal or shows bilateral abnormalities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Unilateral adrenalectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bilateral adrenalectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Selective venous catheterization | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Medical management | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) If adrenal hyperplasia is suspected, the algorithm depicted in Fig. 38-7 is useful. Selective venous** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
