  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When you see clear cells, think McCune-Albright's GNAS mutation!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies McCune-Albright syndrome (MAS) as an association with the clear cell variant of papillary thyroid cancer. MAS is a rare genetic disorder characterized by fibrous dysplasia of bone, café-au-lait spots, and various endocrine dysfunctions, including thyroid abnormalities.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMcCune-Albright syndrome is caused by somatic activating mutations in the GNAS gene, leading to constitutive activation of G-protein coupled receptors. This overactivity drives hyperfunction in various endocrine glands, including the thyroid. While MAS is associated with a spectrum of thyroid pathologies, including follicular adenomas and hyperthyroidism, the clear cell variant of papillary thyroid carcinoma has been specifically reported in patients with this syndrome. The GNAS mutation's role in cellular proliferation and differentiation likely contributes to the development of these specific thyroid neoplasms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cowden’s syndrome is associated with PTEN mutations and an increased risk of various cancers, including breast, endometrial, and follicular or papillary thyroid cancer, but not specifically the clear cell variant.\nOption B (Incorrect): Familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP), particularly its variant Gardner syndrome, is linked to APC gene mutations and an increased risk of papillary thyroid cancer, often of the cribriform-morular variant, not typically the clear cell variant.\nOption C (Incorrect): Werner’s syndrome (adult progeroid syndrome) is caused by WRN gene mutations and is associated with premature aging and an increased risk of various cancers, including thyroid cancer, but lacks a specific association with the clear cell variant of papillary thyroid cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Gene Mutation | Key Features | Thyroid Cancer Association |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| McCune-Albright | GNAS (somatic) | Fibrous dysplasia, café-au-lait, endocrine hyperfunction | Papillary thyroid carcinoma (clear cell variant) |\n| Cowden's | PTEN | Multiple hamartomas, breast/endometrial cancer | Follicular/Papillary thyroid carcinoma |\n| FAP (Gardner) | APC | Colonic polyps, osteomas, desmoids | Papillary thyroid carcinoma (cribriform-morular variant) |\n| Werner's | WRN | Premature aging, cataracts, diabetes | Various thyroid cancers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: McCune-Albright = GNAS + clear cell PTC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a clear cell variant PTC would appear as a hypoechoic, often irregular nodule, similar to other PTCs. Intraoperatively, the tumor might have a slightly different texture or appearance, but definitive diagnosis relies on histopathology.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe 2015 American Thyroid Association (ATA) Management Guidelines for Adult Patients with Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer recommend considering genetic testing for familial syndromes in patients with specific thyroid cancer presentations or family history.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cowden’s syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Familial adenomatous polyposis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Werner’s syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | McCune-Albright syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Nonmedullary thyroid cancers can occur in association with other known familial cancer syndromes suc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
