  "answer": "A) Pheochromocytomas occur in families with MEN2A and MEN2B, in approximately 50% of patients. Both syndromes are inherited in an autosomal dominant fashion and are caused by germline mutations in the RET proto-oncogene. Another syndrome with an increased risk of pheochromocytomas is von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease, which also is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. This syndrome also includes retinal angioma, hemangioblastomas of the central nervous system, renal cysts and carcinomas, pancreatic cysts, and epididymal cystadenomas. The incidence of pheochromocytomas in the syndrome is approximately 14%. The gene causing VHLhas been mapped to chromosome 3p and is a tumor-suppressor gene. Pheochromocytomas also are included within the tumor spectrumof neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1 gene) and other neuroectodermal disorders (Sturge-Weber syndrome and tuberous sclerosis), Carney’s syndrome (gastric epithelioid leiomyosarcoma, pulmonary chondroma, and extra-adrenal paraganglioma), MEN1 syndrome, and the familial paraganglioma and pheochromocytoma syndrome caused by mutations in the succinyl dehydrogenase family of genes (SDHB, SDHC, and SDHD). (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1399.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get caught in a pheo-nomenal genetic trap!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Familial adenomatous polyposis syndrome. This syndrome is not typically associated with an increased risk of pheochromocytoma, distinguishing it from the other listed conditions which are known to predispose individuals to this neuroendocrine tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPheochromocytomas are neuroendocrine tumors arising from chromaffin cells, primarily in the adrenal medulla, and their association with various genetic syndromes underscores the importance of genetic screening. Syndromes like Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2A/B), von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease, Neurofibromatosis type 1 (NF1), and Carney's syndrome involve specific gene mutations (e.g., RET, VHL, NF1, PRKAR1A, SDH genes). These mutations disrupt normal cellular growth and differentiation pathways, leading to the development of pheochromocytomas and other characteristic tumors within each syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Carney’s syndrome) (Incorrect): Carney's syndrome is explicitly associated with pheochromocytomas, alongside gastric epithelioid leiomyosarcoma, pulmonary chondroma, and extra-adrenal paraganglioma.\nOption C (von Hippel-Lindau syndrome) (Incorrect): Von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) disease is a well-established syndrome with an increased risk of pheochromocytomas (approximately 14% incidence), caused by mutations in a tumor-suppressor gene.\nOption D (Sturge-Weber syndrome) (Incorrect): Sturge-Weber syndrome is listed among other neuroectodermal disorders that include pheochromocytomas within their tumor spectrum.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Pheochromocytoma Risk | Key Associated Features | Genetic Basis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | No | Colorectal polyps, desmoid tumors, osteomas, CHRPE | APC gene mutation |\n| Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2) | Yes (50%) | Medullary thyroid carcinoma, hyperparathyroidism (MEN2A), mucosal neuromas (MEN2B) | RET proto-oncogene mutation |\n| Von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) | Yes (14%) | Retinal angiomas, CNS hemangioblastomas, renal cysts/carcinomas, pancreatic cysts | VHL tumor-suppressor gene mutation |\n| Carney's Syndrome | Yes | Gastric epithelioid leiomyosarcoma, pulmonary chondroma, extra-adrenal paraganglioma | PRKAR1A gene mutation |\n| Sturge-Weber Syndrome | Yes | Facial port-wine stain, leptomeningeal angioma, glaucoma | GNAQ gene mutation (somatic) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think \"10% rule\" for pheo, but remember genetic syndromes defy simple percentages.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, pheochromocytomas typically appear as well-defined, highly vascular adrenal masses, often with high signal intensity on T2-weighted MRI. Intraoperatively, they are usually reddish-brown, encapsulated, and can be highly vascular; careful manipulation is crucial to avoid catecholamine release and hypertensive crisis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline (2014): \"Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma: An Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline\" recommends biochemical testing for all patients with suspected pheochromocytoma/paraganglioma and genetic testing for all patients with confirmed tumors due to the high prevalence of germline mutations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Familial adenomatous polyposis syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Carney’s syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | von Hippel-Lindau syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Sturge-Weber syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Pheochromocytomas occur in families with MEN2A and MEN2B, in approximately 50% of patients. Both syn** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
