  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't bypass the duodenum, or your bones will rue it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. Option C is correct because the duodenum is the primary site for calcium absorption in the gastrointestinal tract. This anatomical fact is clinically significant, especially in surgical procedures like gastrojejunostomy which bypass this critical segment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCalcium absorption is a complex process, occurring via both active, vitamin D-dependent transport and passive, paracellular diffusion. The duodenum, with its specialized epithelial cells and high concentration of calcium channels (TRPV6), is uniquely adapted for efficient active calcium uptake, particularly when dietary calcium is low. Its acidic environment also helps keep calcium soluble. Bypassing the duodenum, as in Roux-en-Y gastric bypass, significantly impairs this primary absorption site, leading to potential calcium and vitamin D deficiencies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The body of the stomach is primarily involved in acid secretion and initial protein digestion, not significant calcium absorption.\nOption B (Incorrect): The antrum of the stomach is involved in grinding food and regulating gastric emptying, with negligible calcium absorption.\nOption D (Incorrect): While some passive calcium absorption can occur in the jejunum, the duodenum is the principal and most efficient site, especially for active transport, making it the primary answer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| GI Segment | Primary Absorption |\n|---|---|\n| Duodenum | Calcium, Iron, Folate |\n| Jejunum | Carbohydrates, Fats, Proteins, Water-soluble vitamins |\n| Ileum | Bile salts, Vitamin B12 |\n| Colon | Water, Electrolytes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Duodenum is the 'calcium catcher' of the gut.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring a gastrojejunostomy, the duodenum is typically excluded from the main food stream. On post-operative imaging (e.g., upper GI series), the contrast would bypass the duodenum, flowing directly from the gastric pouch into the jejunum, visually confirming the exclusion of the primary calcium absorption site.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) 2016 Integrated Health Guidelines for Bariatric Surgery. Recommends lifelong monitoring and supplementation of calcium and vitamin D for patients undergoing malabsorptive bariatric procedures like Roux-en-Y gastric bypass due to duodenal bypass.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The body of the stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The antrumof the stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The duodenum | ✅ Correct |\n| D | The proximal jejunum | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Gastric surgery sometimes disturbs calcium and vitamin D metabolism. Calcium absorption occurs prima** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
