  "question": "A patient with a vagotomy and pyloroplasty returns with a recurrent ulcer. The best method for determining if there was an inadequate vagotomy performed is",
  "options": {
    "A": "Direct vagal stimulation",
    "B": "Stimulated gastric analysis",
    "C": "Stimulated PPI (pancreatic polypeptide) levels",
    "D": "None of the above—there is no good test to determine inadequate vagotomy"
  },
  "answer": "C) Historically, gastric analysis was performed most commonly to test for the adequacy of vagotomy in postoperative patients with recurrent or persistent ulcer. Now this can be done by assessing peripheral pancreatic polypeptide levels in response to sham feeding. A 50% increase in pancreatic polypeptide within 30 minutes of shamfeeding suggests vagal integrity. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 906.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get stumped by a stump vagus!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Stimulated PPI (pancreatic polypeptide) levels. This method is now considered the best way to assess for inadequate vagotomy post-pyloroplasty, as a significant increase in pancreatic polypeptide after sham feeding indicates residual vagal innervation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic polypeptide (PP) is a hormone secreted by the pancreas, primarily from F cells in the islets of Langerhans. Its release is strongly stimulated by vagal activity, particularly during the cephalic phase of digestion (sham feeding). By measuring the increase in peripheral PP levels (e.g., a 50% rise within 30 minutes) after sham feeding, one can objectively determine if the vagal nerve supply to the gastrointestinal tract remains intact, thereby indicating an incomplete vagotomy. This provides a physiological and less invasive assessment compared to older methods.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Direct vagal stimulation is an invasive procedure, not practical or routinely used to assess for inadequate vagotomy in a patient presenting with a recurrent ulcer post-surgery. It would involve surgical exposure of the vagus nerve.\nOption B (Incorrect): Stimulated gastric analysis (e.g., Hollander test) was historically used to assess vagotomy adequacy. However, it is less specific, more cumbersome, and has largely been replaced by more modern and less invasive methods like pancreatic polypeptide level assessment.\nOption D (Incorrect): There are indeed good tests available to determine inadequate vagotomy, with stimulated pancreatic polypeptide levels being the current gold standard.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Method | Mechanism | Utility | Current Status |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Stimulated Gastric Analysis (Hollander Test) | Measures gastric acid output in response to insulin-induced hypoglycemia (vagal stimulation) | Historically used to assess vagotomy completeness | Largely superseded due to invasiveness, side effects, and better alternatives |\n| Stimulated Pancreatic Polypeptide (PP) Levels | Measures increase in peripheral PP after sham feeding (vagal stimulation) | Assesses vagal integrity; a significant rise indicates incomplete vagotomy | Current best method for assessing vagotomy adequacy |\n| Direct Vagal Stimulation | Direct electrical stimulation of vagus nerve | Primarily research or intraoperative; not a post-op diagnostic test | Not a practical post-operative diagnostic test |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sham feeding and PP levels unmask residual vagal innervation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring endoscopy for a recurrent ulcer after vagotomy/pyloroplasty, one might see an ulcer at the anastomotic site (marginal ulcer) or in the gastric remnant. Intraoperatively, during a re-exploration for recurrent ulcer, one might identify an incomplete vagotomy by observing intact vagal fibers or branches that were missed during the initial procedure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSchwartz's Principles of Surgery (11th ed.) emphasizes the role of stimulated pancreatic polypeptide levels in assessing vagal integrity post-vagotomy for recurrent ulcer disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Direct vagal stimulation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stimulated gastric analysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Stimulated PPI (pancreatic polypeptide) levels | ✅ Correct |\n| D | None of the above—there is no good test to determine inadequate vagotomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Historically, gastric analysis was performed most commonly to test for the adequacy of vagotomy in p** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
