  "question": "Which of the following locations of gastric ulcers is associated with increased acid production?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Cardia",
    "B": "Fundus",
    "C": "Angularis Iincisiura",
    "D": "Pylorus"
  },
  "answer": "D) In patients with gastric ulcer, acid secretion is variable. Currently, five types of gastric ulcer are described, although the original Johnson classification contained three types (Fig. 26-7). The most common, Johnson type I gastric ulcer, is typically located near the angularis incisura on the lesser curvature, close to the border between the antrum and the body of the stomach. Patients with type I gastric ulcer usually have normal or decreased acid secretion. Type II gastric ulcer is associated with active or quiescent duodenal ulcer disease, and type III gastric ulcer is prepyloric ulcer disease. Both type II and type III gastric ulcers are associated with normal or increased gastric acid secretion. Type IV gastric ulcers occur near the GE junction, and acid secretion is normal or below normal. Type V gastric ulcers are medication induced and may occur anywhere in the stomach. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 909.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric ulcers: where acid reigns supreme!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Pylorus. Gastric ulcers located in the pylorus (prepyloric ulcers, Johnson Type III) are associated with normal or increased gastric acid secretion, distinguishing them from other common gastric ulcer types.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe Johnson classification categorizes gastric ulcers based on their location and associated acid secretion. Type III gastric ulcers are prepyloric, meaning they occur in the pylorus, and are characterized by normal or increased gastric acid secretion, similar to Type II ulcers which are associated with duodenal ulcer disease. This increased acid production contributes to their pathogenesis, often requiring acid-suppressive therapy. In contrast, Type I ulcers (lesser curvature, angularis incisura) and Type IV ulcers (GE junction/cardia) are typically associated with normal or decreased acid secretion, often linked to mucosal barrier defects rather than hyperacidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cardia) (Incorrect): Ulcers near the GE junction (Type IV) are associated with normal or decreased acid secretion.\nOption B (Fundus) (Incorrect): While not a specific Johnson type, fundic ulcers are generally rare and not typically associated with increased acid production.\nOption C (Angularis Iincisiura) (Incorrect): Ulcers at the angularis incisura on the lesser curvature (Type I) are associated with normal or decreased acid secretion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Johnson Ulcer Type | Location                                | Acid Secretion     |\n|--------------------|-----------------------------------------|--------------------|\n| Type I             | Lesser curvature, angularis incisura    | Normal or Decreased|\n| Type II            | Gastric + Duodenal Ulcer                | Normal or Increased|\n| Type III           | Prepyloric (Pylorus)                    | Normal or Increased|\n| Type IV            | Near GE junction (Cardia)               | Normal or Decreased|\n| Type V             | Medication-induced (anywhere)           | Variable           |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloric ulcers often mean more acid; think Type III.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a pyloric ulcer would be visualized in the distal stomach, immediately proximal to the pyloric channel, often appearing as a well-demarcated mucosal defect with surrounding inflammation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) 2017 Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease. It recommends H. pylori eradication and acid suppression for ulcer healing and prevention of recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cardia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fundus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Angularis Iincisiura | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pylorus | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) In patients with gastric ulcer, acid secretion is variable. Currently, five types of gastric ulcer a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
