  "id": 120568,
  "question": "Which of the following is the procedure of choice in a low-risk patient with a perforated duodenal ulcer who is known to be Helicobacter pylori negative, and does not use NSAID’s?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Grahampatch only",
    "B": "Grahampatch with highly selective vagotomy",
    "C": "Truncal vagotomy and pyloroplasty",
    "D": "Truncal vagotomy and antrectomy"
  },
  "answer": "B) See Table 26-5. The options for surgical treatment of perforated duodenal ulcer are simple patch closure, patch closure and HSV, or patch closure and V+D. Simple patch closure alone should be done in patients with hemodynamic instability and/or exudative peritonitis signifying a perforation >24 hours old. In all other patients, the addition of HSVmay be considered because numerous studies have reported a negligible mortality with this approach. However, in the United States and Western Europe, there is clearly a trend away from definitive operation for perforated duodenal ulcer, probably because of the ready availability of PPI, and surgeon unfamiliarity with definitive operation in this setting. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 921.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Patch the hole, snip the nerves, save the patient.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Grahampatch with highly selective vagotomy. This procedure is the optimal choice for a low-risk patient with a perforated duodenal ulcer who is Helicobacter pylori negative and does not use NSAIDs, as it provides definitive treatment for acid reduction while minimizing surgical morbidity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHighly selective vagotomy (HSV) precisely denervates only the parietal cell mass, effectively reducing gastric acid secretion without disrupting the vagal innervation to the pylorus or other abdominal viscera. This preservation of pyloric function eliminates the need for a drainage procedure, thereby significantly reducing the incidence of post-vagotomy syndromes such as dumping or diarrhea. In a carefully selected, low-risk patient, combining a Graham patch for the perforation with HSV offers a durable solution by addressing both the acute defect and the underlying acid hypersecretion, preventing ulcer recurrence with minimal long-term side effects.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Grahampatch only): Incorrect. While it closes the perforation, it does not address the underlying cause of the ulcer in a patient without H. pylori or NSAID use, leading to a high risk of recurrence. It is typically reserved for high-risk patients or those with delayed presentation.\nOption C (Truncal vagotomy and pyloroplasty): Incorrect. Truncal vagotomy denervates the entire stomach, including the pylorus, necessitating a drainage procedure like pyloroplasty. This carries a higher risk of post-vagotomy syndromes compared to HSV.\nOption D (Truncal vagotomy and antrectomy): Incorrect. This is a more extensive and morbid procedure involving gastric resection. It is generally reserved for complicated ulcers (e.g., bleeding, obstruction, malignancy suspicion) or refractory cases, not a simple perforated ulcer in a low-risk patient.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Profile | Procedure | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| High-risk, unstable, >24h perf | Graham patch only | Minimizes operative time/stress; addresses immediate life threat. |\n| Low-risk, H. pylori neg/no NSAIDs | Graham patch + HSV | Definitive acid reduction with minimal side effects; prevents recurrence. |\n| H. pylori positive | Graham patch + PPI + H. pylori eradication | Medical management of underlying cause; surgery for perforation only. |\n| Complicated ulcer (bleeding, obstruction) | Truncal vagotomy + antrectomy/pyloroplasty | Addresses complication and definitive acid reduction. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Definitive ulcer surgery is rare, but HSV is the least morbid vagotomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a perforated duodenal ulcer typically presents as a small, anterior defect on the first part of the duodenum, often with surrounding fibrinous exudate and bile staining. A Graham patch involves suturing a pedicle of omentum over this perforation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Perforated Peptic Ulcer (2020) recommend simple closure for most cases, with definitive acid-reducing surgery considered in selected low-risk patients, though its role has diminished.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Grahampatch only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Grahampatch with highly selective vagotomy | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Truncal vagotomy and pyloroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Truncal vagotomy and antrectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) See Table 26-5. The options for surgical treatment of perforated duodenal ulcer are simple patch clo** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
