  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, go big: 5 cm for gastric cancer margins!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 5 cm. Achieving a minimum gross margin of 5 cm is critical for curative resection (R0) of gastric adenocarcinoma, primarily due to its often infiltrative nature, which can extend microscopically beyond the visible tumor mass.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCurative surgery for gastric adenocarcinoma aims for an R0 resection, meaning no residual microscopic or macroscopic tumor. Gastric cancer, particularly the diffuse type, is notorious for its infiltrative growth pattern, where tumor cells can spread widely within the gastric wall without forming a distinct mass. Therefore, a generous gross margin of at least 5 cm proximally and distally is sought to ensure negative microscopic margins. Intraoperative frozen section analysis of margins is a valuable tool to confirm tumor-free tissue, especially in cases where the gross margin appears close or the tumor type is highly infiltrative, thereby maximizing the chance of a true R0 resection and reducing local recurrence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 2 cm is generally insufficient for gastric adenocarcinoma due to the high risk of microscopic tumor extension beyond this distance, leading to positive margins and recurrence.\nOption B (Incorrect): 3 cm, while better than 2 cm, still carries a significant risk of leaving microscopic disease behind in many gastric adenocarcinoma cases, especially infiltrative types.\nOption C (Incorrect): 4 cm is often considered inadequate for gastric adenocarcinoma, as the infiltrative nature of the disease frequently necessitates a wider margin to achieve a true R0 resection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cancer Type | Recommended Gross Margin |\n|---|---|\n| Gastric Adenocarcinoma (general) | ≥ 5 cm |\n| Gastric Adenocarcinoma (diffuse type) | Often > 5 cm, guided by frozen section |\n| Esophageal Adenocarcinoma | ≥ 5 cm (proximal), ≥ 2 cm (distal) |\n| Colorectal Adenocarcinoma | ≥ 2 cm (distal), clear radial margin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For gastric cancer, think '5 cm or more' for a safe margin.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, the infiltrative nature of gastric cancer (e.g., linitis plastica) may make gross tumor margins difficult to define, necessitating careful intraoperative palpation and frozen section analysis to ensure adequate resection beyond the visible lesion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Gastric Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend achieving negative margins (R0 resection) and emphasize the importance of adequate proximal and distal margins, often exceeding 5 cm for infiltrative tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 3 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 4 cm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 5 cm | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The goal of curative surgical treatment is resection of all tumor (i.e., R0 resection). Thus, all ma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
