  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For gastric cancer, 15 nodes or bust for proper staging!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 15 lymph nodes. This number is crucial for accurate pathological staging of gastric adenocarcinoma, which directly impacts prognosis and guides subsequent adjuvant therapy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdequate lymphadenectomy is paramount in gastric cancer surgery. Resection of at least 15 lymph nodes ensures comprehensive staging, allowing for precise determination of nodal status (N stage) and better prognostic stratification. This extensive dissection also offers a therapeutic benefit, as many patients with positive nodes can be cured. It's important to note that grossly involved nodes may be benign, emphasizing the need for thorough pathological examination of a sufficient number of nodes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (10) (Incorrect): Resecting only 10 lymph nodes is considered insufficient for accurate staging of gastric adenocarcinoma, potentially leading to understaging and inadequate treatment planning.\nOption C (20) (Incorrect): While resecting more nodes can be beneficial, 20 is not the *minimal* number required for adequate staging; 15 is the established minimum.\nOption D (25) (Incorrect): Similar to option C, 25 lymph nodes exceeds the *minimal* requirement for adequate staging, which is 15.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cancer Type | Minimal Lymph Nodes for Staging | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Gastric Adenocarcinoma | 15 | Accurate N-staging, prognosis, adjuvant therapy guidance |\n| Colon Adenocarcinoma | 11-12 | Accurate N-staging, prognosis, adjuvant therapy guidance |\n| Esophageal Adenocarcinoma | 7-10 | Accurate N-staging, prognosis, adjuvant therapy guidance |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't skimp on nodes; 15 is the magic number for gastric cancer staging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, suspicious lymph nodes may appear enlarged, firm, or matted, particularly along the greater and lesser curvatures, perigastric, and celiac axis regions. On imaging (CT), enlarged or irregular lymph nodes (>8-10mm short axis) suggest metastatic involvement, though definitive staging requires pathological examination.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAJCC Cancer Staging Manual, 8th Edition (2017). Recommends examination of at least 15 regional lymph nodes for accurate N-staging of gastric adenocarcinoma.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 10 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 15 | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 20 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 25 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) It should be strongly emphasized that many patients with positive lymph nodes are cured by adequate ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
