  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Control the sugar, control the stomach; surgery is a last resort.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Enhanced Diabetes Control. This is the most appropriate initial treatment because diabetic gastroparesis is a direct complication of diabetes, and addressing the underlying metabolic derangement is paramount before considering invasive surgical interventions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDiabetic gastroparesis results from autonomic neuropathy affecting the vagus nerve, leading to impaired gastric motility. Enhanced diabetes control, including strict glycemic management, aims to halt or reverse this neuropathy, thereby improving gastric emptying and symptoms. In severe cases, a pancreas transplant can achieve definitive diabetes control and often substantially improves gastroparesis, making it a consideration before other abdominal procedures.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Implantation of a gastric pacemaker is a surgical intervention considered for refractory gastroparesis after medical management has failed, not an initial treatment.\nOption B (Incorrect): Gastrostomy and jejunostomy are palliative surgical procedures for decompression and feeding, respectively, used in severe cases when medical and less invasive surgical options are insufficient, not as initial therapy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gastric resection is a highly invasive surgical option that is generally discouraged and rarely performed for primary gastroparesis due to its significant morbidity and often limited efficacy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Modality | Primary Goal | Indication | Notes |\n| :----------------- | :----------- | :--------- | :---- |\n| **Enhanced Diabetes Control** | Address root cause (neuropathy) | Initial management for all diabetic gastroparesis | Essential first step, can improve or stabilize symptoms. |\n| **Pancreas Transplant** | Definitive diabetes control | Severe diabetic gastroparesis, often with renal failure | Can substantially improve gastroparesis by resolving diabetes. |\n| **Gastric Pacemaker** | Symptom control (nausea/vomiting) | Refractory gastroparesis after medical failure | Surgical, neuromodulation. |\n| **Gastrostomy/Jejunostomy** | Decompression/Nutritional support | Severe, refractory gastroparesis with intractable symptoms or malnutrition | Palliative, not curative. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always treat the underlying disease before resorting to symptomatic or invasive surgical interventions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nA gastric emptying scintigraphy (GES) would show delayed gastric emptying, confirming the diagnosis. Intraoperatively, the stomach may appear distended, but there are no specific gross findings directly indicative of gastroparesis itself.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) 2021 Clinical Practice Update on the Management of Gastroparesis recommends optimizing glycemic control as a foundational treatment for diabetic gastroparesis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Implantation of a gastric pacemaker | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gastrostomy and jejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gastric resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Enhanced Ddiabetes Ccontrol | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Surgeons need to understand the role of surgery in primary gastroparesis. If appropriate, the patien** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
