  "question": "Which of the following is the most common emergent complication of laparoscopic adjustable gastric bands?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Band slippage",
    "B": "Dysfunction or leak fromthe reservoir or tubing",
    "C": "Prolapse",
    "D": "Erosion"
  },
  "answer": "C) Prolapse is perhaps the most common emergent complication that requires reoperation after laparoscopic adjustable gastric banding (LAGB). The incidence is generally in the 3% range. Postoperative vomiting predisposes to this problem, because the lower stomach can be pushed upward and trapped within the lumen of the band. Typical patient symptoms include immediate dysphagia, vomiting, and inability to take oral food or liquid. Either anterior or posterior prolapse may occur. Reoperation laparoscopically to reduce the prolapse and resuture the band imbrication is indicated. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 961.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the band's too tight, the stomach takes flight!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Prolapse. Prolapse is indeed the most common emergent complication requiring reoperation after laparoscopic adjustable gastric banding (LAGB), often precipitated by postoperative vomiting which pushes the stomach upward into the band.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric prolapse, specifically, occurs when a portion of the stomach above the band (either anterior or posterior) herniates through the band lumen. This emergent condition typically presents with acute dysphagia, intractable vomiting, and an inability to tolerate oral intake. Its incidence is around 3% and necessitates prompt laparoscopic reoperation to reduce the prolapse and secure the band, preventing further complications like ischemia or necrosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Band slippage, while a common complication, is often a more gradual process leading to obstruction or pouch dilation, and not always the most emergent presentation compared to acute prolapse.\nOption B (Incorrect): Dysfunction or leak from the reservoir or tubing can cause loss of restriction or infection, but these are generally not considered the most common emergent complications requiring immediate reoperation for acute obstruction.\nOption D (Incorrect): Erosion is a serious, late complication where the band migrates into the gastric lumen. It is typically a chronic process, presenting with pain, infection, or bleeding, rather than an acute emergent obstruction.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Presentation | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Gastric Prolapse | Acute dysphagia, intractable vomiting, inability to eat | Emergent laparoscopic reduction, band repositioning/suturing |\n| Band Slippage | Gradual or acute obstruction, pouch dilation, reflux | Laparoscopic repositioning, band removal if severe |\n| Band Erosion | Chronic pain, infection, GI bleed, port infection | Endoscopic or surgical band removal |\n| Port/Tubing Issues | Loss of restriction, port site pain/infection | Port revision/replacement, tubing repair |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute dysphagia post-LAGB = think prolapse first!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn an upper GI series, prolapse appears as an abnormally dilated gastric pouch above the band with a 'beak' sign or a 'phi' sign, indicating stomach herniation through the band. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would visualize stomach tissue either anterior or posterior to the band, trapped within its lumen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) 2020 Guidelines for the Clinical Application of Bariatric Surgery: These guidelines discuss the management of LAGB complications, emphasizing prompt recognition and intervention for emergent issues like prolapse.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Band slippage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Dysfunction or leak fromthe reservoir or tubing | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Prolapse | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Erosion | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Prolapse is perhaps the most common emergent complication that requires reoperation after laparoscop** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
