  "answer": "D) We routinely perform screening ultrasound of the abdomen in patients planning to undergo LRYGB who have an intact gallbladder to rule out the presence of gallstones. Should gallstones be discovered, we currently recommend simultaneous laparoscopic cholecystectomy. Another approach is to defer cholecystectomy until after LRYGB if the patient is symptomatic. When a patient does not have gallstones as determined by preoperative ultrasound, we have followed the recommendations of a previous study which showed that prophylactic administration of ursodiol at a dosage of 300 mg bid will decrease the incidence of gallstone formation after RYGB to approximately 4%. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 955.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let rapid weight loss turn into a gallstone crisis; ursodiol is your bile's best friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Patients undergoing Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB) are at high risk for developing gallstones due to rapid weight loss. Prophylactic oral ursodiol is the recommended management for patients with a negative preoperative ultrasound to prevent gallstone formation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRapid weight loss following RYGB leads to increased cholesterol saturation in bile and decreased gallbladder motility, significantly elevating the risk of cholesterol gallstone formation. Ursodiol (ursodeoxycholic acid) works by reducing cholesterol secretion into bile and increasing bile acid synthesis, thereby decreasing bile lithogenicity. This prophylactic measure effectively lowers the incidence of gallstone formation from approximately 30% to around 4%, preventing potential complications like biliary colic, cholecystitis, or pancreatitis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Prophylactic cholecystectomy is not indicated for patients with a negative ultrasound as it is an unnecessary surgical intervention with associated risks when no gallstones are present. It is reserved for those with pre-existing stones or symptoms.\nOption B (Incorrect): Serial ultrasounds are a diagnostic tool, not a prophylactic strategy. While they can detect stones, the primary goal in high-risk patients is prevention, and waiting for detection means the stones have already formed.\nOption C (Incorrect): Waiting for symptoms means the patient has already developed gallstones and potentially complications. This approach is reactive rather than proactive and does not align with best practices for a high-risk population where prevention is feasible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | Pre-op Ultrasound | Recommended Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| High-risk RYGB patient | Positive for gallstones | Simultaneous laparoscopic cholecystectomy (or defer if asymptomatic) |\n| High-risk RYGB patient | Negative for gallstones | Prophylactic oral ursodiol (300 mg BID) |\n| Post-RYGB patient | Symptomatic (e.g., biliary colic) | Diagnostic workup (US) then cholecystectomy if stones present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ursodiol prevents gallstones post-RYGB; cholecystectomy treats existing ones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones appear as echogenic foci within the gallbladder lumen, typically with posterior acoustic shadowing. Intraoperatively, a normal gallbladder would appear healthy, while one with stones might show inflammation or palpable calculi.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) Guidelines (e.g., 2016 or later consensus statements) recommend consideration of ursodiol for gallstone prophylaxis in RYGB patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prophylactic cholecystectomy at the time of surgery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Serial ultrasounds every 3 months after surgery for 2 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ultrasounds after surgery only if the patient develops symptoms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Oral ursodiol to prevent gallstone formation after surgery | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) We routinely perform screening ultrasound of the abdomen in patients planning to undergo LRYGB who h** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
