  "id": 120593,
  "question": "A postoperative marginal ulcer in a patient who has undergone a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass is best treated by",
  "options": {
    "A": "Triple therapy for Helicobacter pylori",
    "B": "Proton pump inhibitors",
    "C": "Endoscopic dilation with post-dilation proton pump inhibitors",
    "D": "Resection of the ulcer with surgical revision of the gastrojejunostomy"
  },
  "answer": "B) Marginal ulcers are another complication relatively specific to Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB), either laparoscopic adjustable Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (LRYGB) or open RYGB. The patient presents with pain in the epigastric region that is not altered by eating. Diagnosis is by endoscopy. Treatment is medical with administration of proton pump inhibitors, which are effective in 90% of cases. Only those with a gastrogastric fistula to the distal stomach or severe stenosis of the lumen of the gastrojejunostomy or non-healing ulcers require surgical therapy. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 966.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the bypass burns, PPIs are the first-line turn.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Proton pump inhibitors (PPIs). Marginal ulcers are a common complication after Roux-en-Y gastric bypass, and medical management with PPIs is the highly effective first-line treatment, resolving symptoms in the vast majority of cases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMarginal ulcers, also known as anastomotic ulcers, typically occur at the gastrojejunal anastomosis following Roux-en-Y gastric bypass. The pathogenesis is multifactorial, involving acid exposure from the gastric pouch, ischemia, foreign body reaction to staples, and potentially H. pylori. PPIs work by irreversibly inhibiting the H+/K+-ATPase pump in gastric parietal cells, thereby reducing gastric acid secretion. This reduction in acid allows the ulcer to heal, and PPIs are effective in approximately 90% of cases, making them the cornerstone of initial therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Triple therapy for Helicobacter pylori is indicated if H. pylori infection is confirmed and contributing, but it is not the primary or sole treatment for a marginal ulcer itself, especially given that many marginal ulcers are not primarily H. pylori-driven.\nOption C (Incorrect): Endoscopic dilation is indicated for anastomotic strictures or stenosis, which can be a complication of marginal ulcers or occur independently. It is not the primary treatment for the ulceration itself, though it might be needed if a stricture develops.\nOption D (Incorrect): Resection of the ulcer with surgical revision is reserved for refractory cases that fail medical management, or for complications like perforation, bleeding, or severe stenosis, not as a first-line treatment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Marginal Ulcer (Initial) | Marginal Ulcer (Refractory) | Anastomotic Stricture |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Primary Treatment** | Proton Pump Inhibitors (PPIs) | Surgical revision/Resection | Endoscopic Dilation |\n| **Success Rate** | ~90% with PPIs | Variable, depends on cause | High with dilation |\n| **Underlying Cause** | Acid, ischemia, staples, H. pylori | Persistent acid, ischemia, fistula | Scarring, inflammation |\n| **Diagnosis** | Endoscopy | Endoscopy | Endoscopy, Barium swallow |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PPIs are the first-line treatment for marginal ulcers post-RYGB; surgery is for failures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, a marginal ulcer appears as a discrete mucosal defect, often with surrounding inflammation, located at or near the gastrojejunal anastomosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) Guidelines (various years) recommend medical management with PPIs as the initial treatment for marginal ulcers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Triple therapy for Helicobacter pylori | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Proton pump inhibitors | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Endoscopic dilation with post-dilation proton pump inhibitors | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Resection of the ulcer with surgical revision of the gastrojejunostomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Marginal ulcers are another complication relatively specific to Roux-en-Y gastric bypass (RYGB), eit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
