  "question": "Which of the following is a component of a biliopancreatic diversion?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Creation of a gastric pouch approximately 20 mLin volume",
    "B": "Oversewing of the distal duodenum",
    "C": "Creation of a Roux limb at least 150 cmin length",
    "D": "Prophylactic cholecystectomy"
  },
  "answer": "D) The operation, which is pictured in Fig. 27-1, involves resection of the distal half to two thirds of the stomach and creation of an alimentary tract of the most distal 200 cm of ileum, which is anastomosed to the stomach. The biliopancreatic limb is anastomosed to the alimentary tract either 75 or 100 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve, depending on the protein content of the patient’s diet. This operation met with limited international popularity, probably due to the technical difficulty of performing it combined with the significant percentage of nutritional complications that arise postoperatively. The biliopancratic diversion (BPD) operation begins with performance of a distal subtotal gastrectomy. A residual 200-mLgastric pouch is created for superobese patients and a slightly larger pouch for patients with a BMI of 50 kg/m . The terminal ileum is identified and divided 250 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve. The distal end of that divided ileum is then anastomosed to the stomach, creating a 2- to 3-cm stoma. The proximal end of the ileum is then anastomosed side to side to the terminal ileum approximately 100 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve. Some surgeons perform the anastomosis only 50 cm proximal to the valve, but in these patients the likelihood of good protein intake postoperatively should be high. Prophylactic cholecystectomy is performed due to the high incidence of gallstone formation with the malabsorption of bile salts. (See Schwartz 9th ed., pp 969, 968.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 BPD: Malabsorption means gallstones, so out comes the gallbladder!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D because prophylactic cholecystectomy is a standard component of biliopancreatic diversion (BPD) due to the significant risk of gallstone formation post-operatively. The provided text explicitly states this, linking it to bile salt malabsorption.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliopancreatic diversion (BPD) is a highly malabsorptive bariatric procedure that significantly alters the enterohepatic circulation of bile salts. This alteration leads to increased lithogenicity of bile, predisposing patients to a high incidence of gallstone formation. Performing a prophylactic cholecystectomy during the initial BPD procedure is a crucial step to mitigate this common and potentially morbid postoperative complication, ensuring better long-term outcomes for the patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Creation of a gastric pouch approximately 20 mL in volume. The text specifies a residual 200-mL gastric pouch for superobese patients, making 20 mL incorrect.\nOption B (Incorrect): Oversewing of the distal duodenum. BPD involves a distal subtotal gastrectomy and specific ileal anastomoses, not oversewing the distal duodenum.\nOption C (Incorrect): Creation of a Roux limb at least 150 cm in length. While BPD involves limb creation, the text describes an alimentary tract of 200-250 cm and a biliopancreatic limb of 75-100 cm, and it's not typically referred to as a 'Roux limb' in the same context as RYGB.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Biliopancreatic Diversion (BPD) | Roux-en-Y Gastric Bypass (RYGB) | Sleeve Gastrectomy (SG) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Gastric Pouch Size | ~200 mL (larger) | ~30 mL (small) | Resection of 75-80% of stomach |\n| Malabsorption | High (significant) | Moderate | Minimal |\n| Bile Diversion | Yes (long biliopancreatic limb) | Yes (biliopancreatic limb) | No |\n| Cholecystectomy | Often prophylactic | Considered, but less routine | Not routine |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: BPD = Big Malabsorption, Big Pouch, Prophylactic Cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, after the distal gastrectomy, one would identify the terminal ileum, divide it 250 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve, and perform the gastroileal anastomosis. The proximal ileal limb (biliopancreatic limb) is then anastomosed to the alimentary limb 75-100 cm proximal to the ileocecal valve. The cholecystectomy would be performed concurrently.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) Guidelines 2022. These guidelines provide recommendations for patient selection, surgical techniques, and postoperative management for various bariatric procedures, including BPD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Creation of a gastric pouch approximately 20 mLin volume | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Oversewing of the distal duodenum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Creation of a Roux limb at least 150 cmin length | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Prophylactic cholecystectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The operation, which is pictured in Fig. 27-1, involves resection of the distal half to two thirds o** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
