  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pylorus preservation is the DS distinction.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, \"The size of the remaining stomach.\" The fundamental difference between a Biliopancreatic Diversion (BPD) and a Duodenal Switch (DS) lies in the gastric resection and the subsequent gastric remnant, specifically the preservation of the pylorus in DS.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe core distinction is that the Duodenal Switch (DS) procedure involves a sleeve gastrectomy, creating a narrow gastric tube while preserving the pylorus and a short segment of the duodenum. This pyloric preservation is crucial as it maintains physiological gastric emptying, reducing the risk of dumping syndrome and marginal ulcers often associated with traditional BPD, which performs a distal gastrectomy, removing the antrum and pylorus. The calibrated gastric tube in DS optimizes weight loss while allowing adequate oral intake, making it a technically more complex but physiologically advantageous modification.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): The length of the alimentary limb is a critical component for malabsorption in both BPD and DS, typically long (e.g., 250 cm), and is not the primary differentiating factor between the two procedures.\nOption C (Incorrect): The length of the biliopancreatic limb is also a shared design principle in both BPD and DS, determining the extent of malabsorption, and does not distinguish them.\nOption D (Incorrect): This is incorrect because, as detailed, the gastric resection and pyloric preservation are significant differences that define DS as a distinct modification of BPD.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Biliopancreatic Diversion (BPD) | Duodenal Switch (DS) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Gastric Resection | Distal gastrectomy (antrum/pylorus removed) | Sleeve gastrectomy (pylorus preserved) |\n| Gastric Remnant | Proximal stomach pouch | Narrow gastric tube |\n| Pylorus | Removed | Preserved |\n| Anastomosis | Gastric remnant to ileum | Duodenum to ileum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DS preserves the pylorus; BPD removes it.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a surgeon performing a DS would use a bougie (e.g., 32F) to calibrate the gastric tube during the sleeve gastrectomy, ensuring the pylorus remains intact. On an upper GI series, a DS patient would demonstrate a narrow, tubular stomach emptying into the preserved duodenum, which then connects to the ileum, contrasting with a BPD patient's larger gastric pouch directly anastomosed to the ileum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (ASMBS) and International Federation for the Surgery of Obesity and Metabolic Disorders (IFSO) Guidelines for Metabolic and Bariatric Surgery (2022). These guidelines outline the indications and technical considerations for both BPD and DS.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The size of the remaining stomach | ✅ Correct |\n| B | The length of the alimentary limb | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The length of the biliopancreatic limb | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None of the above—it is the same operation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The deuodenal switch (DS) procedure differs from BPD only in the proximal gut portion of the operati** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
