  "id": 120635,
  "question": "Appendectomy may decrease the risk of developing which of the following diseases?",
  "options": {
    "A": "HIV",
    "B": "Burkitt’s lymphoma",
    "C": "Ulcerative colitis",
    "D": "Colon cancer"
  },
  "answer": "C) Although there is no clear role for the appendix in the development of human disease, recent studies demonstrate a potential correlation between appendectomy and the development of inflammatory bowel disease. There appears to be a negative age-related association between prior appendectomy and subsequent development of ulcerative colitis. In addition, comparative analysis clearly shows that prior appendectomy is associated with a more benign phenotype in ulcerative colitis and a delay in onset of disease. The association between Crohn’s disease and appendectomy is less clear. Although earlier studies suggested that appendectomy increases the risk of developing Crohn’s disease, more recent studies that carefully assessed the timing of appendectomy in relation to the onset of Crohn’s disease demonstrated a negative correlation. These data suggest that appendectomy may protect against the subsequent development of inflammatory bowel disease; however, the mechanismis unclear. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1073.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 An appendix-ectomy might just be your gut's best friend against UC!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ulcerative Colitis. Recent studies suggest a potential protective effect of prior appendectomy against the development of ulcerative colitis, demonstrating a negative age-related association and a more benign disease phenotype.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWhile the exact mechanism remains unclear, a prior appendectomy has been shown to correlate with a decreased risk of developing ulcerative colitis. This association includes a negative age-related link between appendectomy and subsequent UC onset, as well as a more benign disease course and delayed onset in those who do develop UC. The relationship with Crohn's disease is less definitive, with earlier studies suggesting increased risk, but more recent, carefully timed analyses indicating a potential negative correlation, similar to UC. This suggests a broader protective role against inflammatory bowel disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (HIV) (Incorrect): There is no known correlation between appendectomy and the risk of developing HIV.\nOption B (Burkitt’s lymphoma) (Incorrect): Burkitt's lymphoma is a type of non-Hodgkin lymphoma, and its development is not influenced by appendectomy.\nOption D (Colon cancer) (Incorrect): Appendectomy does not decrease the risk of colon cancer. While appendicitis can sometimes mask colon cancer, the surgical removal of the appendix itself has no protective effect against colon cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Disease | Relationship with Appendectomy | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ulcerative Colitis | Decreased risk, more benign phenotype, delayed onset | Continuous inflammation, limited to colon, mucosal involvement |\n| Crohn's Disease | Less clear, possibly decreased risk (recent studies) | Skip lesions, transmural inflammation, can affect any part of GI tract |\n| Appendicitis | Acute inflammation of the appendix | Right lower quadrant pain, fever, leukocytosis |\n| Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD) | Appendectomy may offer protection | Chronic inflammation of the GI tract, autoimmune component |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Appendectomy protects against Ulcerative Colitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an inflamed appendix appears as a dilated, fluid-filled structure with surrounding fat stranding. In the OR, a normal appendix is typically removed during appendectomy, but in cases of IBD, the bowel may show signs of chronic inflammation, strictures, or fistulas, which are distinct from acute appendicitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guidelines for the Management of Ulcerative Colitis (2019): While not directly recommending appendectomy for prevention, these guidelines discuss risk factors and disease modifiers, acknowledging the observed association between appendectomy and UC outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | HIV | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Burkitt’s lymphoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ulcerative colitis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Colon cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Although there is no clear role for the appendix in the development of human disease, recent studies** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
