  "question": "Which of the following is important to consider in the differential diagnosis of an HIV+ patient with right lower quadrant abdominal pain?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Herpes type 1 enteritis",
    "B": "Cytomegalovirus infection",
    "C": "Cecal volvulus",
    "D": "Small bowel diverticulitis"
  },
  "answer": "B) The differential diagnosis of right lower quadrant pain is expanded in HIV-infected patients compared with the general population. In addition to the conditions discussed elsewhere in this chapter, opportunistic infections should be considered as a possible cause of right lower quadrant pain. Such opportunistic infections include cytomegalovirus (CMV) infection, Kaposi’s sarcoma, tuberculosis, lymphoma, and other causes of infectious colitis. CMV infection may be seen anywhere in the GI tract. CMV infection causes a vasculitis of blood vessels in the submucosa of the gut, which leads to thrombosis. Mucosal ischemia develops, leading to ulceration, gangrene of the bowel wall, and perforation. Spontaneous peritonitis may be caused by opportunistic pathogens, including CMV, Mycobacterium avium-intracellulare complex, Mycobacterium tuberculosis, Cryptococcus neoformans, and Strongyloides. Kaposi’s sarcoma and non-Hodgkin’s lymphoma may present with pain and a right lower quadrant mass. Viral and bacterial colitis occur with a higher frequency in HIV-infected patients than in the general population. Colitis should always be considered in HIV-infected patients presenting with right lower quadrant pain. Neutropenic enterocolitis (typhlitis) should also be considered in the differential diagnosis of right lower quadrant pain in HIV-infected patients. Herpes type 1 does not cause enteritis. Cecal volvulus and small bowel diverticulitis are very rare, and no more likely to occur in an HIV patient than in someone without HIV infection. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1083.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HIV + RLQ pain = Think opportunistic, especially CMV.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Cytomegalovirus infection. In HIV-infected patients, the differential diagnosis for right lower quadrant abdominal pain is significantly expanded due to their immunocompromised state, making opportunistic infections a primary consideration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCytomegalovirus (CMV) infection is a critical opportunistic pathogen in HIV patients and can cause enteritis throughout the GI tract, including the right lower quadrant. Its pathophysiology involves a vasculitis of submucosal blood vessels, leading to thrombosis, mucosal ischemia, ulceration, and potentially gangrene or perforation of the bowel wall. This ischemic process directly causes the abdominal pain. Other opportunistic infections like Kaposi's sarcoma, tuberculosis, lymphoma, and neutropenic enterocolitis (typhlitis) are also important considerations in this patient population, highlighting the need for a broad differential in immunocompromised individuals.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Herpes type 1 enteritis) (Incorrect): Herpes type 1 typically causes oral or genital lesions and does not commonly cause enteritis.\nOption C (Cecal volvulus) (Incorrect): Cecal volvulus is a rare condition and its incidence is not increased in HIV-infected patients compared to the general population.\nOption D (Small bowel diverticulitis) (Incorrect): Small bowel diverticulitis is also a rare condition and is not more likely to occur in an HIV patient than in someone without HIV infection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | HIV+ Patient Considerations | General Population Considerations |\n|---|---|---|\n| **RLQ Pain** | CMV enteritis, Typhlitis, Kaposi's sarcoma, Lymphoma, TB, Appendicitis | Appendicitis, Crohn's disease, Diverticulitis, Ovarian pathology |\n| **CMV Enteritis** | Common opportunistic infection, causes vasculitis, ischemia, ulceration | Rare, typically in severely immunocompromised (transplant) |\n| **Typhlitis** | Neutropenic enterocolitis, high mortality, common in chemotherapy/HIV | Extremely rare, associated with severe neutropenia |\n| **Appendicitis** | Still possible, but opportunistic infections must be ruled out first | Most common cause of acute RLQ pain |\n| **Diagnosis** | Endoscopy with biopsy, viral load, CT scan | CT scan, ultrasound, clinical exam |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always consider opportunistic infections in HIV patients with abdominal pain.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT scan, CMV enteritis may manifest as diffuse or segmental bowel wall thickening, mural stratification, or the 'target sign.' Endoscopy would reveal friable, erythematous mucosa with ulcerations, which can be confirmed by biopsy showing characteristic viral inclusions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nIDSA Guidelines for the Prevention and Treatment of Opportunistic Infections in HIV-Infected Adults and Adolescents (2023): Recommends considering CMV as a cause of gastrointestinal disease in HIV patients with CD4 counts <50 cells/µL and appropriate symptoms, often requiring endoscopic evaluation with biopsy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Herpes type 1 enteritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cytomegalovirus infection | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cecal volvulus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Small bowel diverticulitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The differential diagnosis of right lower quadrant pain is expanded in HIV-infected patients compare** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
