  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When they sleep more than they live, weeks are all they've got.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, \"Weeks.\" This patient's symptoms, including sleeping >50% of the day and requiring assistance with ADLs, are strong indicators of a very short prognosis, typically measured in weeks, according to established palliative care prognostic tools.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAccurate prognostication in terminal illness is crucial for effective palliative care planning and patient/family communication. Tools like the Palliative Performance Scale (PPS) or Karnofsky Performance Status (KPS) correlate functional decline with survival. A patient sleeping more than 50% of the day and needing assistance with ADLs falls into a category of significant functional impairment, indicating a rapid decline towards the end of life. This level of functional status is a well-recognized marker for a prognosis of weeks, allowing clinicians to guide discussions about end-of-life care, hospice enrollment, and symptom management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Unknown, it could be months to years\" - Incorrect. The described symptoms are specific indicators of advanced disease and a short prognosis, not an unknown or long one.\nOption B (Incorrect): \"Months\" - Incorrect. While a short prognosis, the degree of functional decline (sleeping >50% of the day, requiring ADL assistance) points to an even shorter timeframe, typically weeks, not months.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"Days\" - Incorrect. A prognosis of \"days\" is generally reserved for patients who are essentially bedfast and completely dependent for all ADLs, a more severe state than described in the question.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Functional Status | Palliative Performance Scale (PPS) | Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ambulatory, able to care for self, occasional assistance | 70-80% | Months to years |\n| Sleeping >50% of day, requires some ADL assistance | 40-50% | Weeks |\n| Essentially bedfast, dependent for all ADLs | 10-30% | Days to 1-2 weeks |\n| Comatose, total care | 0% | Hours to days |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Functional decline and increased somnolence predict weeks, not months or years.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., CT, MRI) in this context would likely show widespread metastatic disease, but it does not directly predict the imminent prognosis as precisely as functional status does. Intraoperatively, one might observe extensive tumor burden if surgery were attempted, but this scenario is typically for palliative care, not surgical intervention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Palliative Care (e.g., 2023). These guidelines recommend regular assessment of functional status and symptom burden to guide prognostic discussions and end-of-life care planning.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Unknown, it could be months to years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Weeks | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Days | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) For example, patients with advanced metastatic cancer who are resting/sleeping for 50% or more of no** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
