  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Variations are the spice of life, especially in Calot's triangle!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, as the question specifically asks for the second most common anatomic configuration of the cystic artery. While the most common origin is from the right hepatic artery, the second most common involves a single cystic artery arising from an aberrant or accessory right hepatic artery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUnderstanding the anatomical variations of the cystic artery is crucial for safe cholecystectomy, preventing hemorrhage or bile duct injury. The cystic artery typically arises from the right hepatic artery in 80-90% of cases, usually within the triangle of Calot. The second most common configuration, occurring in about 10% of individuals, involves a single cystic artery originating from an aberrant or accessory right hepatic artery. This variation means the artery may not be found in its usual location, requiring careful dissection to identify and ligate it safely. Awareness of these variations minimizes complications during surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While multiple cystic arteries can occur, two cystic arteries both arising from the right hepatic artery is not described as the *second most common* configuration. The question specifically asks for the second most common, which is a single artery from an aberrant RHA.\nOption B (Incorrect): Two cystic arteries, one from the right hepatic artery and one from the left hepatic artery, is a rare variation and not the second most common. This configuration would be highly unusual and not represent the 10% prevalence cited.\nOption D (Incorrect): A cystic artery arising from the gastroduodenal artery is an extremely rare anatomical variation and certainly not the second most common. Such an origin would place the artery far from the typical Calot's triangle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cystic Artery Configuration | Prevalence | Surgical Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Single, from Right Hepatic Artery | 80-90% | Most common, usually found in Calot's triangle. |\n| Single, from Aberrant/Accessory Right Hepatic Artery | ~10% | Second most common, artery may be outside Calot's triangle, requiring careful dissection. |\n| Multiple Cystic Arteries | Rare | Requires identification and ligation of all branches to prevent bleeding. |\n| Origin from Left Hepatic Artery or Gastroduodenal Artery | Very Rare | Highly anomalous, increases risk of injury if not identified. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always expect cystic artery variations; the second most common is from an aberrant RHA.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring laparoscopic cholecystectomy, meticulous dissection within Calot's triangle is paramount. If the cystic artery is not immediately identified in its usual position, suspect an aberrant origin. Look for it arising more proximally or distally along the common hepatic or right hepatic artery, or even from an accessory right hepatic artery. Intraoperative cholangiography or indocyanine green (ICG) fluorescence can help delineate biliary and vascular anatomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Surgical Treatment of Gallstone Disease (2010): Recommends critical view of safety (CVS) to prevent bile duct injury, which implicitly requires careful identification of cystic duct and artery anatomy, including variations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Two cystic arteries, both arising fromthe right hepatic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Two cystic arteries, one arising from the right hepatic artery and one aris | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | One cystic artery, arising froman aberrant right hepatic artery | ✅ Correct |\n| D | One cystic artery, arising fromthe gastroduodenal artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The second most common anatomic configuration is one cystic artery, arising from an accessory, or ab** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
