  "answer": "C) One of the main stimuli to gallbladder emptying is the hormone cholecystokinin (CCK). CCK is released endogenously from the duodenal mucosa in response to a meal. When stimulated by eating, the gallbladder empties 50 to 70% of its contents within 30 to 40 minutes. Over the following 60 to 90 minutes, the gallbladder gradually refills. This is correlated with a reduced CCK level. Vasoactive intestinal polypeptide inhibits contraction and causes gallbladder relaxation. Somatostatin and its analogues are potent inhibitors of gallbladder contraction. Patients treated with somatostatin analogues and those with somatostatinoma have a high incidence of gallstones, presumably due to the inhibition of gallbladder contraction and emptying. Other hormones such as substance P and enkephalin affect gallbladder motility, but the physiologic role is unclear. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1139.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CCK: The gallbladder's personal trainer for a good squeeze!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cholecystokinin (CCK) because it is the primary physiological stimulus for gallbladder contraction and emptying, released from the duodenum in response to a meal. This hormone orchestrates the release of bile into the small intestine for fat digestion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholecystokinin (CCK) is a crucial gastrointestinal hormone released from the duodenal mucosa when food, particularly fats and proteins, enters the small intestine. Its primary action on the gallbladder is to induce strong muscular contractions, leading to the expulsion of 50-70% of its stored bile within 30-40 minutes. This coordinated physiological response ensures that bile, essential for emulsifying dietary fats, is available precisely when needed for digestion. The subsequent decrease in CCK levels allows the gallbladder to gradually refill.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Vasoactive intestinal polypeptide) (Incorrect): VIP primarily inhibits gallbladder contraction and promotes relaxation, directly opposing the action of CCK.\nOption B (Somatostatin) (Incorrect): Somatostatin is a potent inhibitor of gallbladder contraction and emptying, and its prolonged action can lead to bile stasis and gallstone formation.\nOption D (Enkephalin) (Incorrect): While enkephalins can affect gallbladder motility, their physiological role as a primary mediator of contraction is not well-established or considered significant compared to CCK.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Primary Effect on Gallbladder | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cholecystokinin (CCK) | Contraction & Emptying | Primary physiological stimulus for bile release |\n| Vasoactive Intestinal Polypeptide (VIP) | Relaxation & Inhibition | Counteracts CCK, promotes filling |\n| Somatostatin | Inhibition of Contraction | Associated with increased gallstone risk due to stasis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think \"CCK for Contraction\" when considering gallbladder emptying.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a HIDA scan (cholescintigraphy), CCK can be exogenously administered to assess gallbladder ejection fraction, which is crucial in diagnosing biliary dyskinesia or chronic acalculous cholecystitis. A low ejection fraction (<35-40%) after CCK stimulation suggests gallbladder dysfunction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Gallstones and Cholecystitis (2019). This guideline discusses the role of CCK-stimulated cholescintigraphy in the diagnosis of chronic acalculous cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Vasoactive intestinal polypeptide | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Somatostatin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cholecystokinin | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Enkephalin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) One of the main stimuli to gallbladder emptying is the hormone cholecystokinin (CCK). CCK is release** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
