  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CCK: The sprint runner of GI hormones, quick in, quick out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 2-3 minutes. This short half-life is characteristic of peptide hormones like CCK, which are rapidly metabolized to ensure precise and transient physiological responses, such as gallbladder contraction and enzyme secretion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholecystokinin (CCK) is a crucial peptide hormone originating from the epithelial cells of the upper gastrointestinal tract, primarily the duodenum. Its release is triggered by the presence of acid, fat, and amino acids. CCK's primary physiological roles include stimulating gallbladder contraction and relaxing the sphincter of Oddi, facilitating bile release for fat digestion. It also mediates pancreatic enzyme secretion. This rapid action necessitates a short plasma half-life, which is achieved through metabolism by both the liver and kidneys. Vagal cholinergic neurons also mediate CCK's effects on the gallbladder and biliary tree.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 20-30 minutes is significantly longer than CCK's actual half-life and would lead to prolonged physiological effects not consistent with its role in acute digestive responses.\nOption C (Incorrect): 2-3 hours is an extremely long half-life for a peptide hormone involved in rapid digestive regulation, suggesting a chronic rather than acute signaling role.\nOption D (Incorrect): 20-30 hours is an implausibly long half-life for CCK, which would result in sustained and unregulated physiological responses, disrupting normal digestive processes.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Origin | Primary Action | Half-life |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| CCK | Duodenum | Gallbladder contraction, pancreatic enzyme secretion | 2-3 minutes |\n| Gastrin | G cells (antrum) | Gastric acid secretion, mucosal growth | 10-15 minutes |\n| Secretin | S cells (duodenum) | Bicarbonate secretion (pancreas, bile) | 3-5 minutes |\n| GIP | K cells (duodenum, jejunum) | Insulin release, gastric acid inhibition | 4-20 minutes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CCK acts fast and leaves fast – think minutes, not hours.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn HIDA scan or ultrasound, CCK infusion is used to assess gallbladder ejection fraction. A normal response would show significant gallbladder contraction and bile duct emptying. In the OR, during a cholecystectomy, the surgeon might observe a distended gallbladder if CCK release is impaired or its receptors are unresponsive.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Gallstone Disease (2019). Recommends CCK-stimulated cholescintigraphy (HIDA scan) as a diagnostic tool for suspected biliary dyskinesia when other causes of pain have been excluded.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2-3 minutes | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 20-30 minutes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2-3 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 20-30 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) CCK is a peptide that comes from epithelial cells of the upper GI tract and is found in the highest ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
