  "question": "1. The sensitivity of ultrasound in detecting gallstones is",
  "options": {
    "A": ">99%",
    "B": "90-95%",
    "C": "85-90%",
    "D": "80-85%"
  },
  "answer": "B) An ultrasound is the initial investigation of any patient suspected of disease of the biliary tree. It is noninvasive, painless, does not submit the patient to radiation, and can be performed on critically ill patients. It is dependent upon the skills and the experience of the operator, and it is dynamic (i.e., static images do not give the same information as those obtained during the ultrasound investigation itself). Ultrasound will show stones in the gallbladder with sensitivity and specificity of >90%. Stones are acoustically dense and reflect the ultrasound waves back to the ultrasonic transducer. Because stones block the passage of sound waves to the region behind them, they also produce an acoustic shadow (Fig. 32-2). Stones move with changes in position. Polyps may be calcified and reflect shadows, but do not move with change in posture. Some stones forma layer in the gallbladder; others a sediment or sludge. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1140.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to gallstones, ultrasound is your best friend!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, the correct answer is B, 90-95%. Ultrasound is the initial and highly effective imaging modality for detecting gallstones due to its non-invasive nature and excellent sensitivity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nUltrasound detects gallstones by identifying acoustically dense structures within the gallbladder lumen. These stones reflect sound waves, creating a characteristic hyperechoic appearance, and block sound transmission, resulting in a distinct acoustic shadow. A key diagnostic feature is the mobility of these structures with changes in patient position, differentiating them from polyps or other fixed lesions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (>99%) (Incorrect): While ultrasound is highly sensitive, it is not perfect, and >99% overstates its diagnostic accuracy for gallstones.\nOption C (85-90%) (Incorrect): This range is slightly lower than the generally accepted sensitivity of >90% for ultrasound in detecting gallstones.\nOption D (80-85%) (Incorrect): This range is significantly lower than the established sensitivity of ultrasound for gallstone detection, which is typically above 90%.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Primary Use | Sensitivity for Gallstones | Specificity for Gallstones |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Ultrasound | Initial diagnosis of biliary disease | >90% | >90% |\n| CT Scan | Complications (e.g., pancreatitis, perforation) | 70-80% | 80-90% |\n| MRCP | Biliary ductal anatomy, choledocholithiasis | 90-95% | 90-95% |\n| HIDA Scan | Acute cholecystitis (cystic duct obstruction) | N/A (functional) | N/A (functional) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ultrasound is the first-line, highly sensitive test for gallstones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones appear as mobile, hyperechoic (bright) foci within the gallbladder lumen, consistently casting an acoustic shadow posteriorly. This triad is pathognomonic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) 2019 Guidelines on the Management of Gallstones and Cholecystitis recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for suspected gallstone disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | >99% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 90-95% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 85-90% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 80-85% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) An ultrasound is the initial investigation of any patient suspected of disease of the biliary tree. ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
