  "question": "2. Which of the following is associated with an increased risk for cholelithiasis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Ulcerative colitis",
    "B": "Crohn’s disease",
    "C": "Jejunal resection",
    "D": "Carcinoma of the colon"
  },
  "answer": "B) Certain conditions predispose to the development of gallstones. Obesity, pregnancy, dietary factors, Crohn’s disease, terminal ileal resection, gastric surgery, hereditary spherocytosis, sickle cell disease, and thalassemia are all associated with an increased risk of developing gallstones. Women are three times more likely to develop gallstones than men, and first-degree relatives of patients with gallstones have a twofold greater prevalence. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1142.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Crohn's in the ileum? Think stones in the bile!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT, the correct answer is B, Crohn's disease. Crohn's disease, particularly when affecting the terminal ileum, impairs bile salt reabsorption, leading to an increased risk of cholesterol gallstone formation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe terminal ileum is the primary site for reabsorption of conjugated bile salts, which are crucial for maintaining cholesterol solubility in bile. In Crohn's disease, inflammation or surgical resection of the terminal ileum disrupts this enterohepatic circulation. Reduced bile salt return to the liver decreases the bile salt pool, leading to bile that is supersaturated with cholesterol, thus promoting cholesterol crystal precipitation and gallstone formation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Ulcerative colitis primarily affects the colon and does not typically involve the terminal ileum in a way that impairs bile salt reabsorption, thus it is not directly associated with an increased risk of cholelithiasis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Jejunal resection does not significantly impact the enterohepatic circulation of bile salts, as the terminal ileum is the main site of reabsorption. Therefore, it is not a direct risk factor for cholelithiasis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Carcinoma of the colon has no direct physiological link to the formation of gallstones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Risk Factor | Mechanism/Association |\n|---|---|\n| Crohn's Disease (terminal ileum) | Impaired bile salt reabsorption, cholesterol supersaturation |\n| Obesity/Rapid Weight Loss | Increased cholesterol synthesis/secretion |\n| Pregnancy/Female Sex | Estrogen increases cholesterol secretion, progesterone decreases gallbladder motility |\n| Hemolytic Anemias (e.g., Sickle Cell) | Increased bilirubin production, pigment stone formation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Think 'Crohn's = terminal ileum = bile salts = gallstones'.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones appear as echogenic foci within the gallbladder lumen, often casting an acoustic shadow, and are typically mobile with patient position changes. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder may feel firm or gritty due to the presence of stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAGA Institute Guideline on the Management of Gallstones and Cholecystitis (2019). This guideline discusses risk factors for gallstone formation, including inflammatory bowel disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulcerative colitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Crohn’s disease | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Jejunal resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Carcinoma of the colon | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Certain conditions predispose to the development of gallstones. Obesity, pregnancy, dietary factors,** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
