  "answer": "A) The most common presentation [of cholangitis] is fever, epigastric or right upper quadrant pain, and jaundice. These classic symptoms, well known as Charcot’s triad , are present in about two thirds of patients. The illness may progress rapidly with septicemia and disorientation, known as Reynolds’ pentad (e.g., fever, jaundice, right upper quadrant pain, septic shock, and mental status changes). However, the presentation may be atypical, with little if any fever, jaundice, or pain. This occurs most commonly in the elderly, who may have unremarkable symptoms until they collapse with septicemia. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1149.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
