  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, blame the bifurcation.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the most common location for cholangiocarcinoma, which is the hepatic duct bifurcation. This specific perihilar location, often referred to as a Klatskin tumor, accounts for about two-thirds of all cholangiocarcinomas.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholangiocarcinoma can occur anywhere along the biliary tree, but its predilection for the perihilar region, specifically the common hepatic duct at the bifurcation, is a critical anatomical and clinical point. These perihilar tumors, known as Klatskin tumors, are further classified by the Bismuth-Corlette system, with Type I involving the common hepatic duct and Type II involving the bifurcation without secondary intrahepatic duct extension. Understanding this common location is crucial for early diagnosis, surgical planning, and prognosis, as surgical resection offers the only chance for cure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While intrahepatic cholangiocarcinomas exist, they are less common than perihilar tumors, which account for about two-thirds of cases.\nOption C (Incorrect): This describes a location within the common hepatic duct, but the bifurcation itself is the most specific and common site, encompassing the \"junction\" but being more precise.\nOption D (Incorrect): Distal cholangiocarcinomas are less common than perihilar tumors and have different surgical approaches and prognoses.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cholangiocarcinoma Type | Location | Prevalence |\n|---|---|---|\n| Perihilar (Klatskin) | Hepatic duct bifurcation | ~60-70% |\n| Intrahepatic | Within liver parenchyma | ~10-15% |\n| Distal | Distal common bile duct | ~20-30% |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Klatskin tumors are perihilar cholangiocarcinomas at the hepatic duct bifurcation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), a Klatskin tumor typically appears as a focal stricture or mass at the hepatic duct confluence, often with upstream biliary dilation. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, infiltrative mass at the bifurcation, requiring careful dissection to assess resectability and often necessitating complex hepatectomy with bile duct resection and hepaticojejunostomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and management of cholangiocarcinoma, including surgical resection, neoadjuvant/adjuvant therapies, and palliative care strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In the intrahepatic ducts | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In the common hepatic duct, at the bifurcation | ✅ Correct |\n| C | At the junction of the hepatic and common bile ducts | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In the distal common bile duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Cholangiocarcinoma is a rare tumor arising from the biliary epithelium and may occur anywhere along ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
