  "question": "9. Pancreatic acinar cells secrete",
  "options": {
    "A": "Lipases",
    "B": "Amylase",
    "C": "Proteases",
    "D": "All of the above"
  },
  "answer": "D) The acinar cells secrete amylase, proteases, and lipases, enzymes responsible for the digestion of all three food types: carbohydrate, protein, and fat. The acinar cells are pyramid-shaped, with their apices facing the lumen of the acinus. Near the apex of each cell are numerous enzyme-containing zymogen granules that fuse with the apical cell membrane. Unlike the endocrine pancreas, where islet cells specialize in the secretion of one hormone type, individual acinar cells secrete all types of enzymes. However, the ratio of the different enzymes released is adjusted to the composition of digested food through nonparallel regulation of secretion. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1174, and Table 33-2.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic acinar cells: the ultimate digestive enzyme buffet!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the broad secretory function of pancreatic acinar cells. These cells are the primary exocrine component of the pancreas, responsible for producing the enzymes essential for digestion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic acinar cells are specialized epithelial cells that synthesize and secrete a comprehensive array of digestive enzymes. These include lipases for fat digestion, amylase for carbohydrate breakdown, and proteases for protein hydrolysis. A key physiological detail is that individual acinar cells are capable of secreting all these enzyme types, ensuring a complete digestive enzymatic cocktail is delivered to the duodenum, adaptable to varying dietary compositions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Lipases) (Incorrect): While acinar cells do secrete lipases, this option is incomplete as they also secrete amylase and proteases.\nOption B (Amylase) (Incorrect): Amylase is indeed secreted by acinar cells, but this option is not comprehensive as lipases and proteases are also produced.\nOption C (Proteases) (Incorrect): Proteases are a major secretion of acinar cells, but this option is incomplete as it omits amylase and lipases.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pancreatic Acinar Cells | Pancreatic Islet Cells |\n|---|---|---|\n| Function | Exocrine secretion (digestive enzymes) | Endocrine secretion (hormones) |\n| Secretions | Amylase, Lipase, Proteases | Insulin, Glucagon, Somatostatin |\n| Target | Duodenum (via ducts) | Bloodstream |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acinar cells are the 'all-in-one' digestive enzyme factory.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, acute pancreatitis (inflammation of acinar cells) presents with pancreatic edema, peripancreatic fat stranding, and fluid collections. Intraoperatively, an inflamed pancreas may appear edematous and firm.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACG Clinical Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). Recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration and pain management for acute pancreatitis, often stemming from acinar cell injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lipases | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Amylase | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Proteases | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The acinar cells secrete amylase, proteases, and lipases, enzymes responsible for the digestion of a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
