  "question": "11. Approximately what percentage of the population has a replaced right hepatic artery?",
  "options": {
    "A": "2%",
    "B": "5%",
    "C": "10%",
    "D": "15%"
  },
  "answer": "D) Variations in the arterial anatomy occur in one out of five patients. The right hepatic artery, common hepatic artery, or gastroduodenal arteries can arise from the superior mesenteric artery. In 15 to 20% of patients, the right hepatic artery will arise from the superior mesenteric artery and travel upwards toward the liver along the posterior aspect of the head of the pancreas (referred to as a replaced right hepatic artery). It is important to look for this variation on preoperative computed tomographic (CT) scans and in the operating room so the replaced hepatic artery is recognized and injury is avoided. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1171.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't cut the SMA's hepatic gift!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, 15%. This question tests knowledge of common anatomical variations of the hepatic arterial supply, specifically the prevalence of a replaced right hepatic artery originating from the superior mesenteric artery (SMA).\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA replaced right hepatic artery, arising from the superior mesenteric artery, is a significant anatomical variant found in 15-20% of the population. This artery typically travels along the posterior aspect of the head of the pancreas towards the liver. Its identification is crucial during hepatobiliary and pancreatic surgeries, as inadvertent injury can lead to severe complications such as hepatic ischemia or biliary stricture. Preoperative imaging, particularly CT angiography, is essential for surgical planning to map out these variations and prevent iatrogenic harm.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 2% is significantly lower than the reported prevalence of a replaced right hepatic artery.\nOption B (Incorrect): 5% is an underestimation of the true incidence of this anatomical variation.\nOption C (Incorrect): 10% is below the established range for a replaced right hepatic artery originating from the SMA.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Arterial Variation | Prevalence | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Overall arterial variations in hepatic supply | 20% (1 in 5 patients) | Requires careful preoperative imaging and intraoperative identification |\n| Replaced Right Hepatic Artery (from SMA) | 15-20% | High risk of injury during pancreaticoduodenectomy or liver surgery |\n| Common Hepatic Artery from SMA | Less common, but significant | Can alter blood supply to liver and gastroduodenal region |\n| Gastroduodenal Artery from SMA | Rare | Important for pancreatic head resection planning |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Always look for a replaced right hepatic artery from the SMA; it's more common than you think!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn preoperative CT scans, trace the hepatic arteries from their origin. A replaced right hepatic artery will be seen arising from the SMA and coursing superiorly, often posterior to the portal vein or pancreatic head. Intraoperatively, it appears as an anomalous vessel in the hepatoduodenal ligament or posterior to the pancreas, requiring careful dissection and preservation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A. This information is foundational anatomical knowledge typically found in surgical textbooks like Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th ed., p 1171), rather than specific society guidelines.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 5% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 10% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 15% | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Variations in the arterial anatomy occur in one out of five patients. The right hepatic artery, comm** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
