  "id": 120704,
  "question": "13. The most common gene mutation found in pancreatic cancer is",
  "options": {
    "A": "HER2/neu",
    "B": "K-ras",
    "C": "p53",
    "D": "Smad 4"
  },
  "answer": "B) Pancreatic carcinogenesis probably involves multiple mutations that are inherited and acquired throughout aging. The K-ras on-cogene is currently thought to be the most commonly mutated gene in pancreatic cancer, with approximately 90% of tumors having a mutation. This prevalent mutation is present in precursor lesions and is therefore thought to occur early and be essential to pancreatic cancer development. K-ras mutations can be detected in DNA from serum, stool, pancreatic juice, and tissue aspirates of patients with pancreatic cancer, suggesting that the presence of this mutation may provide the basis for diagnostic testing in select individuals. The HER2/neu oncogene, homologous to the epidermal growth factor receptor (EGFr), is overex-pressed in pancreatic cancers. This receptor is involved in signal transduction pathways that lead to cellular proliferation. Multiple tumor-suppressor genes are deleted and/or mutated in pancreatic cancer, and include p53, p16, and DPC4 (Smad 4), and in a minority of cases, BRCA2. Most pancreatic cancers have three or more of the above mutations. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1220.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it comes to pancreatic cancer, K-ras is the undisputed genetic MVP.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe answer is correct. K-ras is the most common gene mutation found in pancreatic cancer, occurring in approximately 90% of tumors and playing a critical early role in carcinogenesis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nK-ras is an oncogene that is mutated in about 90% of pancreatic tumors, making it the most prevalent genetic alteration. Its presence in precursor lesions suggests it's an early and essential driver of pancreatic cancer development. This high prevalence and early occurrence also make K-ras mutations a potential target for diagnostic testing in various bodily fluids, offering a basis for early detection in select individuals.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): HER2/neu is an oncogene that is overexpressed in pancreatic cancers, involved in cellular proliferation, but it is not the most common *mutation*.\nOption C (Incorrect): p53 is a tumor-suppressor gene frequently mutated or deleted in pancreatic cancer, but it is not as common as K-ras.\nOption D (Incorrect): Smad 4 (DPC4) is a tumor-suppressor gene that is deleted or mutated in pancreatic cancer, but it is not the most common mutation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gene/Protein | Type | Role in Pancreatic Cancer | Prevalence/Significance |\n| :----------- | :--- | :------------------------ | :---------------------- |\n| K-ras        | Oncogene | Early driver of carcinogenesis | ~90% mutated, most common |\n| p53          | Tumor Suppressor | Cell cycle regulation, apoptosis | Frequently mutated/deleted |\n| Smad 4 (DPC4) | Tumor Suppressor | TGF-β signaling pathway | Frequently mutated/deleted |\n| HER2/neu     | Oncogene | Cell proliferation, signal transduction | Overexpressed, not most common mutation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: K-ras is king in pancreatic cancer mutations.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, pancreatic cancer often appears as a hypodense mass. Intraoperatively, the tumor may be firm and infiltrative, and the presence of K-ras mutations can guide future targeted therapies or confirm diagnosis from biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023). These guidelines recommend molecular profiling for advanced pancreatic cancer to identify actionable mutations, though K-ras is not typically a direct therapeutic target yet.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | HER2/neu | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | K-ras | ✅ Correct |\n| C | p53 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Smad 4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Pancreatic carcinogenesis probably involves multiple mutations that are inherited and acquired throu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
