  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CCK: Quick to act, quicker to vanish!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, 2-3 minutes. This question tests knowledge of basic gastrointestinal hormone physiology, specifically the plasma half-life of Cholecystokinin (CCK). Understanding the rapid metabolism of CCK is crucial for appreciating its transient yet potent effects on digestion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCCK is a vital peptide hormone secreted by the epithelial cells of the upper GI tract, primarily the duodenum, in response to luminal acid, fat, and amino acids. Its rapid plasma half-life of 2 to 3 minutes ensures a precise and transient regulatory role in digestion. This short duration of action is facilitated by its metabolism in both the liver and kidneys. CCK's primary actions include stimulating gallbladder contraction, relaxing the sphincter of Oddi and terminal bile duct, and influencing pancreatic enzyme secretion, often mediated by cholinergic vagal neurons. The brevity of its half-life allows for fine-tuned control over postprandial digestive processes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): A half-life of 20-30 minutes is significantly longer than the actual half-life of CCK, which is rapidly metabolized.\nOption C (Incorrect): A half-life of 2-3 hours is far too long for a hormone like CCK, which exerts acute, postprandial effects.\nOption D (Incorrect): A half-life of 20-30 hours is characteristic of hormones with prolonged systemic effects, not the rapid, localized action of CCK.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Half-life | Primary Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| CCK | 2-3 minutes | Gallbladder contraction, Sphincter of Oddi relaxation, Pancreatic enzyme secretion |\n| Gastrin | ~5-10 minutes | Gastric acid secretion, Mucosal growth |\n| Secretin | ~3-5 minutes | Pancreatic bicarbonate secretion, Bile secretion |\n| VIP | ~1-2 minutes | Intestinal secretion, Smooth muscle relaxation, Vasodilation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CCK's short half-life means its digestive effects are swift and transient.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a HIDA scan, administration of exogenous CCK (e.g., Kinevac) is used to assess gallbladder ejection fraction, which helps diagnose functional gallbladder disorders or chronic acalculous cholecystitis. A low ejection fraction (<35-40%) after CCK stimulation suggests gallbladder dysfunction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Technical Review on Functional Gallbladder and Sphincter of Oddi Disorders (2006): Recommends CCK-stimulated cholescintigraphy (HIDA scan) as a diagnostic tool for suspected functional gallbladder disorder, with an ejection fraction <35-40% considered abnormal.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 2-3 minutes | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 20-30 minutes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2-3 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 20-30 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) CCK is a peptide that comes from epithelial cells of the upper GI tract and is found in the highest ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
