  "question": "Which of the following is one of the components of gallstones?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Biliverdin",
    "B": "Hemoglobin",
    "C": "Lecithin",
    "D": "Short chain fatty acids"
  },
  "answer": "C) Lecithin is a phospholipid that is one of the three major components of gallstones (see Fig. 32-3). Gallstones form as a result of solids settling out of solution. The major organic solutes in bile are bilirubin, bile salts, phospholipids, and cholesterol. Gallstones are classified by their cholesterol content as either cholesterol stones or pigment stones. Pigment stones can be further classified as either black or brown. In Western countries about 80% of gallstones are cholesterol stones and about 15 to 20% are black pigment stones. Brown pigment stones account for only a small percentage. Both types of pigment stones are more common in Asia. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1143.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstones: a delicate balance of bile components gone awry.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Lecithin. Lecithin is a phospholipid and one of the three major organic components of bile, alongside cholesterol and bile salts, whose imbalance leads to gallstone formation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstones form when the delicate balance of solutes in bile is disrupted, leading to precipitation. Bile is composed primarily of water, bile salts, phospholipids (like lecithin), cholesterol, and bilirubin. Lecithin, a phospholipid, plays a crucial role in solubilizing cholesterol in bile by forming mixed micelles. When the concentration of cholesterol exceeds the solubilizing capacity of bile salts and phospholipids, cholesterol crystals precipitate, forming cholesterol gallstones. Pigment stones, on the other hand, are primarily composed of calcium bilirubinate.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Biliverdin is a green pigment formed from the breakdown of heme, which is then reduced to bilirubin. While bilirubin is a component of pigment gallstones, biliverdin itself is not a direct component of gallstones.\nOption B (Incorrect): Hemoglobin is the oxygen-carrying protein in red blood cells and is not a component of gallstones. Its breakdown product, bilirubin, can be.\nOption D (Incorrect): Short chain fatty acids are typically produced by bacterial fermentation in the gut and are not primary structural components of gallstones.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Component | Role in Bile/Gallstones | Type of Gallstone |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cholesterol | Major lipid, supersaturation leads to stone formation | Cholesterol stones |\n| Bile Salts | Solubilize cholesterol, aid fat digestion | Essential for preventing stone formation |\n| Lecithin (Phospholipid) | Solubilizes cholesterol by forming mixed micelles | Essential for preventing stone formation |\n| Bilirubin | Pigment from heme breakdown | Pigment stones (black/brown) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the \"3 Cs\" of bile: Cholesterol, Cholic acid (bile salts), and Choline (lecithin).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, gallstones typically appear as echogenic (bright) foci within the gallbladder lumen, often casting an acoustic shadow posteriorly, and are mobile with changes in patient position. Intraoperatively, they are palpable within the gallbladder and can range from small gravel to large, faceted stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Gallstones (2019). These guidelines recommend cholecystectomy for symptomatic gallstone disease and discuss the indications and techniques for surgical management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Biliverdin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hemoglobin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lecithin | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Short chain fatty acids | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Lecithin is a phospholipid that is one of the three major components of gallstones (see Fig. 32-3). ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
