  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gallstones often start with an epigastric groan.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe most common location for pain during an attack of biliary colic is the epigastrium. This is due to the visceral nature of the pain originating from the gallbladder, which is initially perceived centrally before potentially localizing.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBiliary colic pain arises from the visceral afferent fibers innervating the gallbladder, primarily T5-T9/T10 sympathetic segments. These visceral afferents enter the spinal cord at the same levels as somatic afferents from the epigastric region, leading to referred pain perceived in the epigastrium. The pain is typically visceral, dull, and poorly localized initially, often presenting centrally before localizing to the right upper quadrant. The explanation states epigastric pain occurs in 64% of patients, making it the most common initial site.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Left periumbilical pain is not characteristic of biliary colic, which originates from the right upper quadrant.\nOption B (Incorrect): Right shoulder pain is a classic referred pain pattern for biliary disease, often mediated by phrenic nerve irritation, but it is less common than epigastric pain as the primary presenting symptom.\nOption D (Incorrect): Scapular pain, specifically to the right scapula (Boas' sign), is a form of referred pain in biliary colic, but epigastric pain is the most frequently reported initial location.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Most Common Pain Location | Referred Pain |\n|---|---|---|\n| Biliary Colic | Epigastrium, RUQ | Right shoulder, Scapula |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | RUQ | Right shoulder, Scapula |\n| Acute Pancreatitis | Epigastrium (radiating to back) | Left shoulder, Flank |\n| Peptic Ulcer Disease | Epigastrium | Back (penetrating ulcer) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Epigastric pain is the initial and most common presentation of biliary colic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, biliary colic typically presents with gallstones in the gallbladder lumen without evidence of gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, or sonographic Murphy's sign, differentiating it from acute cholecystitis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Gallstone Disease (2016) recommends that biliary colic pain is typically located in the epigastrium or right upper quadrant.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Left periumbilical | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Right shoulder | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Epigastrium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Scapula | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The most common location for pain during an episode of biliary colic is the epigastrium (64%) follow** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
