  "question": "Which of the following is the appropriate treatment for adenomyomatosis of the gallbladder?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Observation only",
    "B": "INH",
    "C": "Serial exams with EGD and ultrasound every 12 months",
    "D": "Cholecystectomy"
  },
  "answer": "D) Adenomyomatosis or cholecystitis glandularis proliferans is characterized on microscopy by hypertrophic smooth muscle bundles and by the ingrowths of mucosal glands into the muscle layer (epithelial sinus formation). Granulomatous polyps develop in the lumen at the fundus, and the gallbladder wall is thickened and septae or strictures may be seen in the gallbladder. In symptomatic patients, cholecystectomy is the treatment of choice. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1146.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just observe a symptomatic adenomyomatosis; excise it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cholecystectomy. Adenomyomatosis, when symptomatic, is a benign but progressive condition of the gallbladder wall that causes pain and other biliary symptoms, making surgical removal the definitive treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAdenomyomatosis is characterized by hypertrophic smooth muscle bundles and invaginations of the mucosal epithelium into the muscular layer, forming Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses. These sinuses can trap bile and cholesterol crystals, leading to inflammation, pain, and sometimes stone formation. While benign, symptomatic adenomyomatosis warrants cholecystectomy to alleviate symptoms and prevent complications, as medical management is ineffective against the structural changes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Observation only is appropriate for asymptomatic adenomyomatosis, but the question implies a need for treatment, suggesting symptomatic disease.\nOption B (Incorrect): INH (Isoniazid) is an antitubercular drug and has no role in the treatment of gallbladder adenomyomatosis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Serial exams with EGD and ultrasound every 12 months are diagnostic and monitoring tools, not a definitive treatment for symptomatic adenomyomatosis. EGD is generally not indicated for primary gallbladder pathology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Feature | Presentation | Treatment |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Adenomyomatosis | Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses, thickened wall | Often asymptomatic; if symptomatic, biliary colic | Cholecystectomy (symptomatic) |\n| Cholesterolosis | \"Strawberry gallbladder,\" cholesterol deposits | Usually asymptomatic; can cause biliary colic | Cholecystectomy (symptomatic) |\n| Cholelithiasis | Gallstones in lumen | Biliary colic, cholecystitis, pancreatitis | Cholecystectomy |\n| Gallbladder Polyp | Mucosal protrusion | Usually asymptomatic; can be malignant | Surveillance or Cholecystectomy (size/risk dependent) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Symptomatic adenomyomatosis = cholecystectomy. Asymptomatic = observe.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, adenomyomatosis appears as gallbladder wall thickening with intramural diverticula (Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses) that may show 'comet-tail' artifacts. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder wall may appear focally or diffusely thickened, sometimes with a fundal cap.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES Clinical Practice Guideline for the Surgical Treatment of Gallbladder Disease (2019) recommends cholecystectomy for symptomatic gallbladder adenomyomatosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Observation only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | INH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Serial exams with EGD and ultrasound every 12 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cholecystectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Adenomyomatosis or cholecystitis glandularis proliferans is characterized on microscopy by hypertrop** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
