  "id": 120723,
  "question": "A 53-year-old man is admitted with 24 hours of pain from acute cholecystitis. He is made npo, IV antibiotics are started, and analgesia is given. He should undergo cholecystectomy",
  "options": {
    "A": "Urgently",
    "B": "In 1-3 days",
    "C": "In 7-10 days",
    "D": "In 6-8 weeks"
  },
  "answer": "B) Patients who present with acute cholecystitis will need IV fluids, antibiotics, and analgesia. The antibiotics should cover gram-negative aerobes as well as anaerobes. A third-generation cephalosporin with good anaerobic coverage or a second-generation cephalosporin combined with metronidazole is a typical regimen. For patients with allergies to cephalosporins, an aminoglycoside with metronidazole is appropriate. Although the inflammation in acute cholecystitis may be sterile in some patients, more than one half will have positive cultures from the gallbladder bile. It is difficult to know who is secondarily infected; therefore, antibiotics have become a part of the management in most medical centers. Cholecystectomy is the definitive treatment for acute cholecystitis. In the past, the timing of cholecystectomy has been a matter of debate. Early cholecystectomy performed within 2 to 3 days of the illness is preferred over interval or delayed cholecystectomy that is performed 6 to 10 weeks after initial medical treatment and recuperation. Several studies have shown that unless the patient is unfit for surgery, early cholecystectomy should be recommended, as it offers the patient a definitive solution in one hospital admission, quicker recovery times, and an earlier return to work. Laparoscopic cholecystectomy is the procedure of choice. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1148.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't delay the cholecystectomy, or the inflammation will make you pay!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"In 1-3 days.\" For acute cholecystitis, after initial stabilization with NPO, IV antibiotics, and analgesia, early cholecystectomy within 2-3 days is the preferred management strategy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEarly cholecystectomy, performed within 2 to 3 days of symptom onset, offers significant advantages over delayed approaches. It provides a definitive solution in a single hospital admission, leading to quicker recovery times and an earlier return to normal activities. This strategy minimizes the risk of recurrent attacks or complications that can arise during a prolonged waiting period, and is generally associated with less difficult dissection than later stages of inflammation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): \"Urgently\" implies immediate surgery, which is typically reserved for severe, complicated cases (e.g., perforation, gangrene, empyema) or when initial medical management fails. Uncomplicated acute cholecystitis usually allows for a brief period of stabilization.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"In 7-10 days\" is too late for early cholecystectomy, missing the optimal window where inflammation is still manageable and before fibrosis makes dissection more difficult.\nOption D (Incorrect): \"In 6-8 weeks\" represents an interval or delayed cholecystectomy, which is associated with higher rates of readmission for recurrent symptoms or complications while awaiting surgery, and does not offer the benefits of early intervention.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Timing of Cholecystectomy | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Acute Cholecystitis (uncomplicated) | Within 1-3 days (early) | Definitive treatment, single admission, quicker recovery, less complicated dissection than delayed. |\n| Acute Cholecystitis (severe/complicated) | Emergent/Urgent (within 24h) | To prevent/treat perforation, gangrene, empyema, or sepsis. |\n| Biliary Colic | Elective (outpatient) | Symptomatic gallstones without acute inflammation; can be scheduled. |\n| Interval Cholecystectomy | 6-8 weeks after initial medical treatment | Historically done to allow inflammation to subside, but now largely superseded by early cholecystectomy due to risks of recurrence. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For acute cholecystitis, stabilize then operate within 72 hours.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, findings include gallbladder wall thickening (>3mm), pericholecystic fluid, and a positive sonographic Murphy's sign. Intraoperatively, the gallbladder appears edematous, hyperemic, and distended, often with adhesions to surrounding structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nTokyo Guidelines 2018 for the management of acute cholecystitis recommend early laparoscopic cholecystectomy within 72 hours for Grade I and Grade II acute cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Urgently | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In 1-3 days | ✅ Correct |\n| C | In 7-10 days | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In 6-8 weeks | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Patients who present with acute cholecystitis will need IV fluids, antibiotics, and analgesia. The a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
