  "id": 120724,
  "question": "Primary choledochal stones are usually",
  "options": {
    "A": "Cholesterol stones",
    "B": "Black pigment stones",
    "C": "Brown pigment stones",
    "D": "Mulberry stones"
  },
  "answer": "C) The vast majority of ductal stones in Western countries are formed within the gallbladder and migrate down the cystic duct to the common bile duct. These are classified as secondary common bile duct stones, in contrast to the primary stones that form in the bile ducts. The secondary stones are usually cholesterol stones, whereas the primary stones are usually of the brown pigment type. The primary stones are associated with biliary stasis and infection and are more commonly seen in Asian populations. The causes of biliary stasis that lead to the development of primary stones include biliary stricture, papillary stenosis, tumors, or other (secondary) stones. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1148.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Brown pigment stones: the primary problem in the duct.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, brown pigment stones. Primary choledochal stones are those that form de novo within the bile ducts, distinguishing them from secondary stones which migrate from the gallbladder.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary choledochal stones are predominantly brown pigment stones, characterized by their formation within the bile ducts due to biliary stasis and infection. These stones are more prevalent in Asian populations and are often associated with underlying conditions causing stasis, such as strictures, papillary stenosis, or tumors. Their composition is primarily calcium bilirubinate, reflecting their infectious and stasis-related etiology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cholesterol stones) (Incorrect): These are typically secondary common bile duct stones, forming in the gallbladder and migrating into the CBD. They are the most common type of gallstone in Western countries.\nOption B (Black pigment stones) (Incorrect): Black pigment stones are usually found in the gallbladder, often associated with chronic hemolysis or cirrhosis, and are not typically primary choledochal stones.\nOption D (Mulberry stones) (Incorrect): \"Mulberry stones\" is a morphological description, often referring to cholesterol stones due to their nodular, irregular surface, rather than a distinct compositional type of primary choledochal stone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stone Type | Location of Formation | Composition | Associated Factors | Epidemiology |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Choledochal | Bile Ducts | Brown Pigment (Calcium Bilirubinate) | Biliary stasis, infection, strictures, papillary stenosis | More common in Asian populations |\n| Secondary Choledochal | Gallbladder | Cholesterol (most common), mixed | Gallbladder disease, migration from GB | Most common in Western populations |\n| Black Pigment | Gallbladder | Calcium bilirubinate, calcium phosphate | Chronic hemolysis, cirrhosis | Less common than cholesterol stones |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Primary ductal stones are brown, stasis-induced, and Asian.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ERCP or intraoperative cholangiography, primary brown pigment stones often appear as multiple, soft, friable, and irregularly shaped filling defects within dilated bile ducts, sometimes associated with sludge or strictures. They can be difficult to extract due to their consistency.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) Guideline 2019: The Role of Endoscopy in the Management of Choledocholithiasis. It recommends ERCP for definitive diagnosis and treatment of choledocholithiasis, especially in high-risk patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholesterol stones | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Black pigment stones | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Brown pigment stones | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Mulberry stones | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The vast majority of ductal stones in Western countries are formed within the gallbladder and migrat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
