  "id": 120725,
  "question": "A patient presents with biliary colic. On ultrasound there are multiple small gallstones in the gallbladder and the common bile duct measures 9 mm in diameter. No stone is visualized in the common bile duct. Which of the following is the most reasonable next step?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Repeat ultrasound in 24-48 hours",
    "B": "MRCP with contrast",
    "C": "Percutaneous cholangiography",
    "D": "Laparosopic Ccholecystectomy and intraopetrative cholangiography"
  },
  "answer": "D) For patients with symptomatic gallstones and suspected common bile duct stones, either preoperative endoscopic cholangiography or an intraoperative cholangiogramwill document the bile duct stones. If an endoscopic cholangiogram reveals stones, sphincterotomy and ductal clearance of the stones is appropriate, followed by a laparoscopic cholecystectomy. An intraoperative cholangiogram at the time of cholecystectomy will also document the presence or absence of bile duct stones (Fig. 32-5). Laparoscopic common bile duct exploration via the cystic duct or with formal choledochotomy allows the stones to be retrieved in the same setting. If the expertise and/or the instrumentation for laparoscopic common bile duct exploration are not available, a drain should be left adjacent to the cystic duct and the patient scheduled for endoscopic sphincterotomy the following day. An open common bile duct exploration is an option if the endoscopic method has already been tried or is, for some reason, not feasible. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1148.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Dilated duct, symptomatic stones? Look for CBD stones!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. This patient presents with symptomatic cholelithiasis and a dilated common bile duct (9 mm), which strongly suggests concomitant choledocholithiasis, even without a stone visualized on ultrasound. The most reasonable next step is to proceed with laparoscopic cholecystectomy and simultaneously evaluate the common bile duct for stones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLaparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative cholangiography (IOC) is the gold standard for managing symptomatic gallstones when common bile duct (CBD) stones are suspected. IOC allows for definitive diagnosis of CBD stones during the same operative setting. If stones are found, they can often be extracted via laparoscopic common bile duct exploration (LCBDE) through the cystic duct or a formal choledochotomy, thus completing the treatment in a single procedure. This approach avoids the need for a separate, potentially invasive, preoperative endoscopic procedure unless LCBDE is not feasible or expertise is lacking.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Repeat ultrasound in 24-48 hours) (Incorrect): This would delay definitive diagnosis and treatment. Ultrasound has limited sensitivity for CBD stones, and repeating it is unlikely to change the management plan given the dilated duct.\nOption B (MRCP with contrast) (Incorrect): MRCP is an excellent diagnostic tool for CBD stones, but it is diagnostic only and does not offer therapeutic intervention. Furthermore, MRCP typically does not use intravenous contrast for stone detection; it relies on T2-weighted sequences to visualize fluid-filled structures. While it could confirm CBD stones, it would still necessitate a subsequent therapeutic procedure (ERCP or surgical exploration).\nOption C (Percutaneous cholangiography) (Incorrect): Percutaneous transhepatic cholangiography (PTC) is an invasive procedure typically reserved for cases of obstructive jaundice where ERCP has failed or is contraindicated, or for complex biliary strictures. It is not a first-line diagnostic or therapeutic option for suspected choledocholithiasis in this setting.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Modality | Type | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Ultrasound** | Diagnostic | Non-invasive, readily available, good for gallbladder stones | Poor sensitivity for CBD stones |\n| **MRCP** | Diagnostic | Non-invasive, no radiation, good for CBD stones | No therapeutic capability, can overestimate stone size |\n| **ERCP** | Diagnostic & Therapeutic | Gold standard for CBD stone removal, can treat strictures | Invasive, risk of pancreatitis, perforation, bleeding |\n| **IOC** | Diagnostic & Therapeutic (with LCBDE) | Performed during cholecystectomy, confirms CBD patency/stones | Requires surgical expertise, radiation exposure |\n| **PTC** | Diagnostic & Therapeutic | Can decompress obstructed systems, access for difficult cases | Highly invasive, risk of bleeding, infection, bile leak |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Dilated CBD + gallstones = rule out CBD stones before or during cholecystectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn intraoperative cholangiography (IOC), you would see filling defects within the common bile duct, indicating the presence of stones. The contrast would flow into the duodenum, confirming patency, or be obstructed by stones.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSAGES (Society of American Gastrointestinal and Endoscopic Surgeons) 2017 Guidelines for the Management of Choledocholithiasis recommend that patients with a high probability of choledocholithiasis undergo preoperative ERCP or intraoperative CBD exploration/cholangiography.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Repeat ultrasound in 24-48 hours | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRCP with contrast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Percutaneous cholangiography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Laparosopic Ccholecystectomy and intraopetrative cholangiography | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) For patients with symptomatic gallstones and suspected common bile duct stones, either preoperative ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
