  "answer": "D) For types I, II, and IV [choledochal cysts], excision of the extrahepatic biliary tree, including cholecystectomy, with a Roux-en-Y hepaticojejunostomy, are ideal. In type IV, additional segmental resection of the liver may be appropriate, particularly if intrahepatic stones, strictures, or abscesses are present, or if the dilatations are confined to one lobe. The risk of cholangiocarcinoma developing in choledochal cysts is as high as 15% in adults, and supports complete excision when they are diagnosed. For type III, sphincterotomy is recommended. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1155; 1158, and Fig. 32-6.)",
