  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 PSC and UC: a gut-wrenching liver connection!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ulcerative Colitis, as Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) has a well-established and strong association with this inflammatory bowel disease, occurring in about two-thirds of PSC patients. This link is crucial for understanding the systemic nature of these conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrimary Sclerosing Cholangitis is characterized by chronic inflammation and fibrosis of the bile ducts, leading to cholestasis and liver failure. Its most significant comorbidity is Ulcerative Colitis, highlighting a shared underlying pathophysiology, likely involving immune dysregulation and genetic predisposition, such as specific HLA haplotypes (e.g., HLA-B8, -DR3, -DQ2, and -DRw52A). This strong association often necessitates screening for PSC in UC patients and vice versa, as the liver disease can progress silently. Other less common associations include Riedel’s thyroiditis and retroperitoneal fibrosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Crohn’s disease) (Incorrect): While Crohn's disease is also an inflammatory bowel disease, it is not typically associated with Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis. PSC is overwhelmingly linked to Ulcerative Colitis.\nOption C (Rheumatoid arthritis) (Incorrect): Rheumatoid arthritis is a systemic autoimmune disease affecting joints, but it does not have a direct or significant association with Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis.\nOption D (Celiac sprue) (Incorrect): Celiac sprue is an autoimmune enteropathy triggered by gluten, and while it can have various extra-intestinal manifestations, it is not a recognized comorbidity for Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | GI Association | Liver Association | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC) | Ulcerative Colitis (60-80%) | Cholestasis, cirrhosis, cholangiocarcinoma | \"Beading\" on cholangiography |\n| Ulcerative Colitis (UC) | Colon (continuous inflammation) | PSC | Bloody diarrhea, tenesmus |\n| Crohn's Disease (CD) | Any part of GI tract (skip lesions) | Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (rare) | Transmural inflammation, strictures, fistulas |\n| Autoimmune Hepatitis (AIH) | Other autoimmune diseases | Hepatitis, cirrhosis | Elevated transaminases, autoantibodies (ANA, SMA) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: PSC + UC = a classic pair. Always think of them together.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cholangiography (ERCP/MRCP), PSC classically presents as multifocal stricturing and dilatations of the intrahepatic and/or extrahepatic bile ducts, giving a characteristic \"beaded\" appearance. The gallbladder and cystic duct are usually spared.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) Practice Guidance 2023: Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis. This guideline provides comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, management, and surveillance of PSC, including its association with IBD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ulcerative Ccolitis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Crohn’s disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Rheumatoid arthritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Celiac sprue | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) [Primary sclerosing cholangitis] is associated with ulcerative colitis in about two thirds of patien** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
