  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 For T2 gallbladder cancer, go beyond simple; resect IVB/V and nodes!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, Cholecystectomy with resection of liver segments IVB and V, because T2 gallbladder carcinoma requires an extended cholecystectomy to achieve adequate oncologic margins, specifically targeting the liver segments most commonly involved by direct extension and lymphatic spread.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nT2 gallbladder cancer invades the perimuscular connective tissue but has not extended beyond the serosa or into the liver parenchyma. However, microscopic invasion into the adjacent liver bed (segments IVB and V) is common due to the direct anatomical relationship and lymphatic drainage. Resecting these specific segments, along with regional lymphadenectomy, ensures a complete R0 resection, which is paramount for improving survival outcomes in these patients. This approach addresses the high likelihood of microscopic disease spread not visible to the naked eye, preventing local recurrence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cholecystectomy only is insufficient for T2 lesions, as it leaves behind potential microscopic disease in the liver bed and regional lymph nodes, leading to high recurrence rates. This is appropriate only for T1 lesions.\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Cholecystectomy with limited right hepatectomy\" is too vague and does not specify the precise segments required for T2 disease. The standard for T2 is specific to segments IVB and V, not a general \"limited right hepatectomy.\"\nOption D (Incorrect): Cholecystectomy with extended right hepatectomy (segments IV, V, VI, VII, and VIII) is an overtreatment for T2 lesions and is typically reserved for more advanced T3 or T4 tumors with deeper liver invasion, when technically feasible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Stage | Invasion Depth | Surgical Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| T1 | Lamina propria or muscular layer | Simple Cholecystectomy |\n| T2 | Perimuscular connective tissue (not beyond serosa/liver) | Extended Cholecystectomy (IVB/V + Lymphadenectomy) |\n| T3/T4 | Beyond serosa/into liver/adjacent organs | Extended Right Hepatectomy (IV, V, VI, VII, VIII) + Lymphadenectomy (if resectable) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: T2 gallbladder cancer = extended cholecystectomy (IVB/V) + lymphadenectomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), a T2 tumor might appear as focal or diffuse gallbladder wall thickening with enhancement, without clear evidence of serosal invasion or direct liver parenchymal invasion beyond the immediate gallbladder bed. Intraoperatively, the tumor may feel firm, but there should be no gross evidence of tumor extending through the serosa or into the liver.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Hepatobiliary Cancers (e.g., Version 2.2023). It recommends extended cholecystectomy (resection of gallbladder bed, segments IVB/V) and regional lymphadenectomy for T2 gallbladder cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholecystectomy only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cholecystectomy with resection of liver segments IVB and V | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cholecystectomy with limited right hepatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cholecystectomy with extended right hepatectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Tumors limited to the muscular layer of the gallbladder (T1) are usually identified incidentally, af** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
