  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bifurcation is the 'hot spot' for cholangiocarcinoma.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is the correct answer. Cholangiocarcinoma most commonly occurs at the common hepatic duct, specifically at the bifurcation, accounting for approximately two-thirds of all cases. This location is often referred to as a perihilar or Klatskin tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe predilection for the hepatic duct bifurcation is a critical anatomical and clinical point in understanding cholangiocarcinoma. These perihilar tumors, also known as Klatskin tumors, are further classified by the Bismuth-Corlette system based on their extent of involvement of the hepatic ducts. This specific location often presents unique surgical challenges due to its proximity to major vascular structures and the need for complex biliary reconstruction, making early diagnosis and precise staging paramount for potential curative resection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While cholangiocarcinomas can occur in the intrahepatic ducts, this location is less common than the perihilar region, accounting for approximately 10% of cases.\nOption C (Incorrect): The junction of the hepatic and common bile ducts is anatomically close to the common hepatic duct bifurcation, but 'at the bifurcation' (Option B) is a more precise and common site for these tumors.\nOption D (Incorrect): Distal common bile duct tumors, while occurring, are less frequent than perihilar tumors, representing about 20-30% of cases.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type | Location | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type I | Common Hepatic Duct | Confined to the common hepatic duct, below the bifurcation. |\n| Type II | Hepatic Duct Bifurcation | Involves the bifurcation but does not extend into secondary intrahepatic ducts. |\n| Type IIIa | Bifurcation + Right Hepatic Duct | Involves the bifurcation and extends into the right secondary intrahepatic ducts. |\n| Type IIIb | Bifurcation + Left Hepatic Duct | Involves the bifurcation and extends into the left secondary intrahepatic ducts. |\n| Type IV | Bilateral Secondary Ducts | Involves both right and left secondary intrahepatic ducts, often multifocal. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Klatskin tumors = perihilar cholangiocarcinoma at the bifurcation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), a perihilar cholangiocarcinoma often appears as a focal stricture or mass at the hepatic duct confluence, with upstream biliary dilation. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, often infiltrative mass at the hilum, requiring careful dissection from the portal vein and hepatic artery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Guidelines for the Management of Cholangiocarcinoma (2020) recommend multidisciplinary evaluation and surgical resection for resectable disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In the intrahepatic ducts | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In the common hepatic duct, at the bifurcation | ✅ Correct |\n| C | At the junction of the hepatic and common bile ducts | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In the distal common bile duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Cholangiocarcinoma is a rare tumor arising from the biliary epithelium and may occur anywhere along ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
