  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer's most common foe? The ductal adenocarcinoma, a silent, aggressive killer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Ductal adenocarcinoma. This is indeed the most common type of pancreatic cancer, accounting for approximately 75% of non-endocrine pancreatic malignancies. Its overwhelming prevalence makes it the primary focus in diagnosis and treatment strategies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC) originates from the epithelial cells lining the pancreatic ducts. Its high incidence is attributed to various risk factors including smoking, chronic pancreatitis, obesity, and genetic predispositions. The aggressive nature of PDAC, characterized by early local invasion, perineural spread, and distant metastasis, contributes to its notoriously poor prognosis, often presenting at advanced stages due to its retroperitoneal location and non-specific symptoms.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Adenosquamous carcinoma is a rare variant of pancreatic cancer, characterized by both glandular and squamous differentiation, and is not the most common type.\nOption C (Incorrect): Acinar cell carcinoma is an uncommon type of pancreatic cancer, typically presenting as a large tumor, and while its prognosis might be better than ductal adenocarcinoma, it is far less frequent.\nOption D (Incorrect): Squamous cell carcinoma of the pancreas is exceedingly rare, often considered a variant or component of other types, and is certainly not the most common.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type of Pancreatic Cancer | Prevalence/Characteristics | Prognosis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Ductal Adenocarcinoma | Most common (~75% of non-endocrine) | Poor |\n| Adenosquamous Carcinoma | Rare variant (glandular + squamous) | Poor (similar to PDAC) |\n| Acinar Cell Carcinoma | Uncommon, often large tumors | Potentially better than PDAC |\n| Squamous Cell Carcinoma | Very rare | Generally poor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in doubt about pancreatic cancer type, think ductal adenocarcinoma first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma often appears as a hypodense mass with irregular borders, causing upstream pancreatic duct dilation and atrophy of the distal pancreas. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, often ill-defined mass within the pancreatic parenchyma, frequently involving surrounding vessels or structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2023): Recommends multidisciplinary evaluation and management, emphasizing surgical resection for resectable disease, often followed by adjuvant chemotherapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ductal adenocarcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Adenosquamous carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Acinar cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Squamous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) In addition to ductal adenocarcinoma, which makes up about 75% of nonendocrine cancers of the pancre** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
