  "question": "Which of the following is NOT a risk factor for pancreatic cancer?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Age >60",
    "B": "African American race",
    "C": "Smoking",
    "D": "Female gender"
  },
  "answer": "D) Pancreatic cancer is more common in the elderly with most patients being >60 years old. Pancreatic cancer is more common in African Americans and slightly more common in men than women. The risk of developing pancreatic cancer is two to three times higher if a parent or sibling had the disease. Another risk factor that is consistently linked to pancreatic cancer is cigarette smoking. Smoking increases the risk of developing pancreatic cancer by at least twofold due to the carcinogens in cigarette smoke. Coffee and alcohol consumption have been investigated as possible risk factors, but the data are inconsistent. As in other GI cancers, diets high in fat and low in fiber, fruits, and vegetables are thought to be associated with an increased risk of pancreatic cancer. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1220.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pancreatic cancer: Silent killer, loud risk factors.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Female gender, as it is NOT a risk factor for pancreatic cancer. In fact, pancreatic cancer is slightly more common in men than in women, making female gender a relative protective factor or at least not an increased risk.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreatic cancer is a highly aggressive malignancy with several well-established risk factors. These include non-modifiable factors such as increasing age (most patients >60 years old), African American race, and a family history of the disease (2-3 times higher risk if a parent or sibling was affected). Modifiable risk factors include cigarette smoking, which significantly increases the risk by at least twofold due to carcinogen exposure, and dietary factors like diets high in fat and low in fiber, fruits, and vegetables. Understanding these risk factors is crucial for patient counseling and identifying high-risk individuals.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Age >60) (Incorrect): Pancreatic cancer is more common in the elderly, with most patients being over 60 years old, making age a significant risk factor.\nOption B (African American race) (Incorrect): Pancreatic cancer is more common in African Americans compared to other racial groups, establishing it as a risk factor.\nOption C (Smoking) (Incorrect): Cigarette smoking is a well-documented and strong risk factor, increasing the risk of pancreatic cancer by at least two to three times due to the presence of carcinogens.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Risk Factor | Description |\n|---|---|\n| Age >60 | Most patients diagnosed are elderly |\n| African American Race | Higher incidence compared to other races |\n| Smoking | 2-3x increased risk due to carcinogens |\n| Family History | 2-3x increased risk if parent or sibling affected |\n| Diet | High fat, low fiber, low fruits/vegetables |\n| Female Gender | Not a risk factor; slightly less common than in men |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the key modifiable and non-modifiable risk factors for pancreatic cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, pancreatic cancer often presents as a hypodense mass, frequently in the head of the pancreas, which may cause dilation of the pancreatic duct and/or common bile duct (the 'double duct sign'). Intraoperatively, the tumor typically appears as a firm, often ill-defined mass within the pancreatic parenchyma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (2024). Recommends comprehensive staging with cross-sectional imaging (CT or MRI) and endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) for diagnosis and treatment planning.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Age >60 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | African American race | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Smoking | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Female gender | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Pancreatic cancer is more common in the elderly with most patients being >60 years old. Pancreatic c** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
