  "answer": "D) In 70 to 90% of patients, the primary gastrinoma is found in Passaro’s triangle, an area defined by a triangle with points located at the junction of the cystic duct and common bile duct, the second and third portion of the duodenum, and the neck and body of the pancreas. However, because gastrinomas can be found almost anywhere, whole-body imaging is required. The test of choice is SSTR (octreotide) scintigraphy in combination with CT. The octreotide scan is more sensitive than CT, locating about 85% of gastrinomas and detecting tumors 1 cm. With the octreotide scan, the need for tedious and technically demanding selective angiography and measurement of gastrin gradients has declined. EUS is another new modality that assists in the preoperative localization of gastrinomas. It is particularly helpful in localizing tumors in the pancreatic head or duodenal wall, where gastrinomas are usually 1 cm in size. A combination of octreotide scan and EUS detects >90% of gastrinomas. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1218.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When gastrinoma hides, octreotide lights the way!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Octreotide scintigraphy. This imaging modality is highly sensitive for gastrinomas because these neuroendocrine tumors typically overexpress somatostatin receptors, which the radiolabeled octreotide binds to, allowing for precise localization.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrinomas are often small and can be found throughout Passaro's triangle or even ectopically, necessitating a sensitive whole-body imaging approach. Octreotide scintigraphy (SSTR scintigraphy) utilizes radiolabeled somatostatin analogs that specifically bind to the somatostatin receptors (SSTRs) abundant on gastrinoma cells. This functional imaging technique allows for the detection of primary tumors as small as 1 cm with a sensitivity of 85%, making it superior to conventional anatomical imaging like CT for initial localization. Its ability to detect these receptor-positive tumors anywhere in the body is crucial for accurate staging and treatment planning.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CT scan) (Incorrect): While useful for anatomical localization and detecting larger tumors or metastases, CT is less sensitive than octreotide scintigraphy for identifying small primary gastrinomas.\nOption B (MRI) (Incorrect): Similar to CT, MRI provides excellent anatomical detail but lacks the functional sensitivity of octreotide scintigraphy for detecting small, receptor-expressing gastrinomas.\nOption C (PET scan) (Incorrect): A general 'PET scan' is not as specific or sensitive for well-differentiated neuroendocrine tumors like gastrinomas as SSTR-based imaging. While SSTR-PET (e.g., Ga-68 DOTATATE) is now considered even more sensitive than octreotide scintigraphy, the option simply states 'PET scan,' and the provided text specifically highlights octreotide scintigraphy as the test of choice.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Imaging Modality | Mechanism | Sensitivity for Gastrinoma | Key Use |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Octreotide Scintigraphy (SPECT) | Somatostatin receptor binding | ~85% | Primary localization, whole-body staging |\n| CT scan | Anatomical imaging | Lower than Octreotide Scintigraphy | Anatomical localization, metastasis detection |\n| EUS | High-resolution ultrasound | >90% (in combination) | Localizing small tumors in pancreas/duodenum |\n| SSTR-PET (e.g., Ga-68 DOTATATE) | Somatostatin receptor binding | >95% (superior to SPECT) | Most sensitive for primary and metastatic disease |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastrinomas express SSTRs; octreotide scintigraphy lights them up.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn octreotide scintigraphy, gastrinomas appear as focal areas of increased radiotracer uptake. Intraoperatively, they are typically small, firm, yellowish-white nodules, often found in the duodenal wall or pancreatic head within Passaro's triangle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Neuroendocrine Tumors (e.g., 2023/2024). These guidelines recommend SSTR-based imaging (including octreotide scintigraphy or SSTR-PET) for the localization and staging of gastrinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CT scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | PET scan | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Octreotide scintigraphy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) In 70 to 90% of patients, the primary gastrinoma is found in Passaro’s triangle, an area defined by ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
