  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hypoglycemia? Think insulinoma, the pancreas's sweet secret.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Insulinoma. Insulinomas are indeed the most common functional pancreatic endocrine tumor, typically presenting with symptoms of hypoglycemia, which are relieved by glucose administration, a classic presentation known as Whipple's triad.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulinomas are beta-cell tumors that autonomously secrete insulin, leading to profound hypoglycemia, especially during fasting. This excess insulin suppresses hepatic glucose production and increases peripheral glucose utilization. Whipple's triad (symptoms of hypoglycemia, blood glucose <50 mg/dL, and symptom relief with glucose) is the hallmark. Most insulinomas are small (<2 cm), solitary, and benign, making surgical enucleation or resection curative.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Gastrinoma) (Incorrect): Gastrinomas are the second most common functional pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor, causing Zollinger-Ellison syndrome due to excessive gastrin secretion, leading to severe peptic ulcer disease.\nOption B (Glucagonoma) (Incorrect): Glucagonomas are rare alpha-cell tumors, characterized by the \"4 D's\": Dermatitis (necrolytic migratory erythema), Diabetes, DVT, and Depression.\nOption D (Somatostatinoma) (Incorrect): Somatostatinomas are extremely rare delta-cell tumors, often associated with the classic triad of diabetes mellitus, cholelithiasis, and steatorrhea.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Incidence/Frequency | Key Clinical Features | Associated Syndrome |\n| :--------- | :------------------ | :-------------------- | :------------------ |\n| Insulinoma | Most Common | Fasting hypoglycemia, Whipple's triad | Hypoglycemic syndrome |\n| Gastrinoma | Second Most Common | Severe peptic ulcers, diarrhea | Zollinger-Ellison Syndrome |\n| Glucagonoma | Rare | Necrolytic migratory erythema, diabetes | Glucagonoma Syndrome |\n| Somatostatinoma | Very Rare | Diabetes, cholelithiasis, steatorrhea | Somatostatinoma Syndrome |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Insulinoma: Think Whipple's triad and hypoglycemia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT, MRI, EUS), insulinomas typically appear as small, well-circumscribed, hypervascular lesions. Intraoperatively, they are often small, firm, and can be difficult to palpate, sometimes requiring intraoperative ultrasound for localization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Neuroendocrine Tumors (e.g., Version 1.2023) recommend surgical resection as the primary treatment for localized functional pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors like insulinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastrinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Glucagonoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Insulinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Somatostatinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Insulinomas are the most common pancreatic endocrine neoplasms and present with a typical clinical s** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
