  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ranson's criteria: Early numbers predict later woes in pancreatitis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. Ranson's criteria are a set of prognostic indicators used to assess the severity of acute pancreatitis. Serum LDH >350 IU/dL is one of the five criteria determined at the time of admission.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRanson's criteria provide an objective scoring system to predict the morbidity and mortality of acute pancreatitis. Five criteria are assessed at admission: age >55 years, WBC >16,000/mm³, blood glucose >200 mg/dL, serum LDH >350 IU/dL, and serum AST >250 U/dL. An additional six criteria are assessed within 48 hours. The number of positive signs directly correlates with increased mortality, ranging from 0% for <2 signs to >50% for >7 signs, guiding early management and resource allocation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Serum calcium <8 mg/dL is a Ranson's criterion, but it indicates hypocalcemia, not hypercalcemia, and is assessed at 48 hours, not admission.\nOption C (Incorrect): Blood glucose >200 mg/dL is a Ranson's criterion at admission, but the threshold provided (120 mg/dL) is incorrect.\nOption D (Incorrect): Serum AST >250 U/dL is a Ranson's criterion at admission, but the threshold provided (150 U/dL) is incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ranson's Admission Criteria | Threshold |\n|-----------------------------|-----------|\n| Age                         | >55 years |\n| WBC                         | >16,000/mm³ |\n| Blood Glucose               | >200 mg/dL |\n| Serum LDH                   | >350 IU/dL |\n| Serum AST                   | >250 U/dL |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the 'GALAW' mnemonic for Ranson's admission criteria: Glucose, Age, LDH, AST, WBC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, severe pancreatitis may show peripancreatic fluid collections, necrosis, pseudocysts, or abscesses. Intraoperatively, the pancreas may appear edematous, hemorrhagic, or necrotic, with saponification of peripancreatic fat.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013) recommends using prognostic scoring systems like Ranson's or APACHE II to assess severity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Serumcalcium8 mg/dL | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | SerumLDH >350 IU/dL | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Blood glucose >120 mg/dL | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | SerumAST >150 U/dL | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) In 1974, Ranson identified a series of prognostic signs for early identification of patients with se** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
