  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Heavy drinking: 10-15% chance of pancreatic pain or liver strain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, indicating that 10-15% of patients consuming 100-150g of alcohol daily will develop pancreatitis. This highlights a specific dose-response relationship and the fact that not all heavy drinkers develop the condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAlcohol-induced pancreatitis is a significant cause of both acute and chronic pancreatitis. While the exact mechanisms are complex, involving direct toxic effects on acinar cells, sphincter of Oddi dysfunction, and oxidative stress, it's crucial to understand the dose-dependent risk. The provided text emphasizes that a daily intake of 100-150g of ethanol places individuals at a specific risk (10-15%) for pancreatitis, a similar proportion to those who develop alcoholic cirrhosis, underscoring the systemic impact of chronic heavy alcohol consumption.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 1-3% is too low for the specified heavy alcohol intake, significantly underestimating the risk.\nOption C (Incorrect): 20-30% is too high, overestimating the risk for this specific alcohol consumption level.\nOption D (Incorrect): 50-65% is significantly too high, representing an extreme overestimation of the risk.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Alcohol Intake (daily) | Associated Risk | Percentage |\n|---|---|---|\n| 100-150g ethanol | Pancreatitis | 10-15% |\n| 100-150g ethanol | Cirrhosis of the liver | 10-15% |\n| Any chronic heavy use | Acute pancreatitis | Varies, increases with dose |\n| Any chronic heavy use | Chronic pancreatitis | Varies, increases with dose |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: 100-150g alcohol daily = 10-15% risk of pancreatitis or cirrhosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, acute alcoholic pancreatitis often presents with diffuse pancreatic enlargement, peripancreatic fat stranding, and fluid collections. In chronic pancreatitis, calcifications, ductal dilation, and atrophy of the gland are common findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Guideline: Management of Acute Pancreatitis (2013, updated 2018). Recommends early aggressive intravenous hydration and pain management for acute pancreatitis, and emphasizes identifying and addressing the etiology, including alcohol cessation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 1-3% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 10-15% | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 20-30% | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 50-65% | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The nature of alcohol consumed (i.e., beer, wine, or hard liquor) is less significant than a daily i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
