  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Whipple buys time, not a guarantee; manage expectations.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, 2 years. This is accurate because the median survival following pancreaticoduodenectomy for pancreatic cancer is approximately 22 months, making 2 years the closest and most appropriate option. This procedure offers the best palliation and is the only modality providing meaningful survival improvement.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPancreaticoduodenectomy, or Whipple procedure, is a complex operation that, despite its morbidity, remains the only potentially curative treatment for pancreatic head adenocarcinoma. It significantly improves median survival compared to no surgery, extending it from months to approximately 22 months. Beyond survival, it offers superior palliation by addressing biliary and gastric outlet obstruction. However, even with successful resection, recurrence is common, highlighting the aggressive nature of the disease and the need for realistic patient expectations regarding long-term outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 9 months is significantly shorter than the established median survival of approximately 22 months post-Whipple.\nOption C (Incorrect): 4 years (48 months) is well beyond the median survival and represents a rare long-term outcome, not the typical median.\nOption D (Incorrect): 8 years (96 months) is an exceptionally rare survival duration for pancreatic cancer, even after a Whipple procedure, and is far from the median.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metric/Treatment | Approximate Survival |\n|---|---|\n| Median survival post-Whipple | ~22 months (2 years) |\n| 5-year survival post-Whipple | 15-25% |\n| Median survival (unresectable PC) | 6-12 months |\n| Median survival (no treatment) | 3-6 months |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Whipple offers 2 years, not a cure, but the best shot.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPreoperative CT angiography is crucial to assess resectability, looking for tumor involvement of the superior mesenteric artery/vein, portal vein, and celiac axis. Intraoperatively, careful palpation for distant metastases and assessment of vascular involvement are key to determining resectability and achieving R0 margins.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Pancreatic Adenocarcinoma (latest version, e.g., 2023/2024). These guidelines recommend pancreaticoduodenectomy for resectable pancreatic head tumors, emphasizing multidisciplinary evaluation and neoadjuvant therapy for borderline resectable cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 9 months | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 2 years | ✅ Correct |\n| C | 4 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 8 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Median survival after pancreaticoduodenectomy is about 22 months. Even long-term (5-year) survivors ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
