  "answer": "A) Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is a disorder of the primitive pluripotent stem cell in the bone marrow that results in a significant increase in erythroid, megakaryotic, and pluripotent progenitors in the peripheral blood smear. The genetic hallmark is a transposition between the bcr gene on chromosome 9 and the abl gene on chromosome 22. CML accounts for 7 to 15% of all leukemias, with an incidence of 1.5 in 100,000 in the United States. It is often asymptomatic, but CMLcan cause fatigue, anorexia, sweating, and left upper quadrant pain and early satiety secondary to splenomegaly. Enlargement of the spleen is found in roughly one half of patients with CML. Splenectomy is indicated to ease pain and early satiety. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1254.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Philadelphia chromosome: The CML signature.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML). The transposition between the bcr gene on chromosome 9 and the abl gene on chromosome 22, forming the bcr-abl fusion gene, is the pathognomonic genetic abnormality for CML, also known as the Philadelphia chromosome.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe bcr-abl fusion gene results from a reciprocal translocation, t(9;22)(q34;q11), creating the Philadelphia chromosome. This fusion gene encodes a constitutively active tyrosine kinase, which drives uncontrolled proliferation of myeloid cells, leading to the characteristic features of CML. This specific genetic alteration is not only diagnostic but also a critical therapeutic target for tyrosine kinase inhibitors, revolutionizing CML treatment.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Chronic myelomonocytic leukemia (CMML) is characterized by features of both myelodysplastic syndromes and myeloproliferative neoplasms, often associated with mutations in genes like TET2, SRSF2, ASXL1, or RAS pathway genes, but not the bcr-abl translocation.\nOption C (Incorrect): Acute myeloid leukemia (AML) is a heterogeneous group of disorders with various genetic abnormalities, including different translocations (e.g., t(8;21), inv(16), t(15;17)), but the bcr-abl translocation is not its hallmark.\nOption D (Incorrect): Polycythemia vera is a myeloproliferative neoplasm characterized by an increase in red blood cell mass, primarily driven by the JAK2 V617F mutation, not the bcr-abl fusion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Genetic Hallmark | Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML) | bcr-abl fusion (t(9;22) / Philadelphia chromosome) | Constitutively active tyrosine kinase |\n| Chronic Myelomonocytic Leukemia (CMML) | TET2, SRSF2, ASXL1, RAS pathway mutations | Myelodysplastic and myeloproliferative features |\n| Acute Myeloid Leukemia (AML) | Diverse translocations (e.g., t(8;21), inv(16)) | Rapid proliferation of immature myeloid blasts |\n| Polycythemia Vera (PV) | JAK2 V617F mutation | Increased red blood cell mass |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CML = Chromosome 9 + 22 = bcr-abl.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/US), significant splenomegaly is a common finding in CML. Intraoperatively, splenectomy may be performed for symptomatic relief of pain or early satiety due to massive splenomegaly.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (e.g., NCCN Guidelines Version 3.2023) recommend bcr-abl testing for diagnosis and monitoring, and tyrosine kinase inhibitors as first-line therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Chronic myeloid leukemia | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Chronic myelomonocytic leukemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Acute myeloid leukemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Polycythemia vera | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is a disorder of the primitive pluripotent stem cell in the bone marr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
