  "answer": "C) Although splenic artery aneurysmis rare, it is the most common visceral artery aneurysm. Women are four times more likely to be affected than men. The aneurysm usually arises in the middle to distal portion of the splenic artery. In one series, mortality was significantly higher in patients with underlying portal hypertension (>50%) than in those without it (17%). Indications for treatment include presence of symptoms, pregnancy, intention to become pregnant, and presence of pseudoaneurysms associated with inflammatory processes. Aneurysm resection or ligation alone is acceptable for amenable lesions in the midsplenic artery, but distal lesions in close proximity to the splenic hilum should be treated with concomitant splenectomy. An excellent prognosis follows elective treatment. Splenic artery embolization has been used to treat splenic artery aneurysm, but painful splenic infarction and abscess may follow. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1256.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let a splenic aneurysm burst your patient's bubble!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Ligation or resection of the aneurysm. For a 2-cm splenic artery aneurysm in the mid-portion of the splenic artery in an 18-year-old healthy woman, surgical resection or ligation is the treatment of choice due to the risk of rupture, especially in women of childbearing age.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic artery aneurysms, though rare, are the most common visceral artery aneurysms and carry a significant risk of rupture, particularly in young women and during pregnancy. Elective treatment, such as aneurysm resection or ligation, offers an excellent prognosis and prevents life-threatening hemorrhage. For lesions located in the mid-splenic artery, this approach is preferred as it preserves splenic function while addressing the aneurysm effectively. The goal is to eliminate the risk of rupture while minimizing morbidity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Observation only) (Incorrect): Observation is generally not recommended for splenic artery aneurysms 2 cm or larger, especially in young women who may become pregnant, due to the high risk of rupture and associated mortality.\nOption B (Embolization) (Incorrect): While embolization can be used, it is associated with significant complications such as painful splenic infarction and abscess formation, making surgical resection a more definitive and often safer option for amenable lesions.\nOption D (Splenectomy) (Incorrect): Splenectomy is an overtreatment for a mid-splenic artery aneurysm unless the lesion is very distal, involves the hilum, or is associated with significant splenic damage. Preserving the spleen is always preferred when possible to maintain immune function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Mid-Splenic Artery Aneurysm | Distal/Hilar Splenic Artery Aneurysm | Symptomatic/Pregnant Patient | Asymptomatic <2cm Aneurysm |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Treatment** | Resection/Ligation | Resection + Splenectomy | Urgent Resection/Ligation | Observation (with caution) |\n| **Rationale** | Preserves spleen, definitive | Aneurysm close to hilum, difficult to isolate | High rupture risk, maternal/fetal mortality | Lower rupture risk, but monitor closely |\n| **Complications** | Standard surgical risks | Immunosuppression, post-splenectomy sepsis | High morbidity/mortality if ruptured | Potential for growth/rupture |\n| **Prognosis** | Excellent with elective repair | Good with elective repair | Poor if ruptured, good if elective | Monitor for changes |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Splenic artery aneurysms >2cm in young women warrant surgical repair.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT angiography, a splenic artery aneurysm appears as a focal saccular or fusiform dilatation of the splenic artery, often with calcification in its wall. Intraoperatively, it presents as a pulsatile, often firm, mass along the course of the splenic artery.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSociety for Vascular Surgery (SVS) Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Visceral Artery Aneurysms (2020) recommend intervention for splenic artery aneurysms >2cm, symptomatic aneurysms, or in women of childbearing age.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Observation only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Embolization | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ligation or resection of the aneurysm | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Splenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Although splenic artery aneurysmis rare, it is the most common visceral artery aneurysm. Women are f** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
