  "question": "Which of the following is associated with an increased risk for pulmonary hypertension following splenectomy?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Sickle cell disease",
    "B": "Warmantibody auto-immune hemolytic anemia",
    "C": "Thalassemia",
    "D": "Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura"
  },
  "answer": "C) Treatment for thalassemia involves red blood cell transfusions to maintain a hemoglobin level of >9 mg/dL, along with intensive parenteral chelation therapy with deferoxamine. Splenectomy is indicated for patients with excessive transfusion requirements (>200 mL/kg per year), discomfort due to splenomegaly, or painful splenic infarction. Careful assessment of the risk:benefit ratio is essential. Thalassemia patients are at high risk for pulmonary hypertension after splenectomy; the precise etiology of this sequela is under investigation. The increase in infectious complications is likely to be due to a coexisting immune deficiency, in large part brought about by iron overload, which may be associated both with the thalassemia itself and with transfusions. The disproportionately high rate of overwhelming postsplenectomy infection in thalassemia patients has led some investigators to consider partial splenectomy in children; some4success in reducing mortality has been reported. However, splenectomy should be delayed until after the age of 4 years unless it is absolutely necessary. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1252.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let thalassemia's spleen removal leave you breathless!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Thalassemia. Patients with thalassemia, particularly those requiring splenectomy due to excessive transfusion requirements or symptomatic splenomegaly, are at a significantly increased risk for developing pulmonary hypertension following the procedure. The exact etiology is complex and multifactorial.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenectomy in thalassemia patients, while often necessary for managing anemia and splenomegaly, removes a key organ involved in red blood cell quality control and immune regulation. In thalassemia, chronic hemolysis and iron overload contribute to endothelial dysfunction and a pro-thrombotic state. The spleen's removal may exacerbate these issues by altering red blood cell dynamics, increasing circulating abnormal red cells, and potentially contributing to systemic inflammation and vascular remodeling, ultimately leading to pulmonary vascular disease and hypertension.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sickle cell disease can cause pulmonary hypertension, but this is primarily due to chronic hemolysis, nitric oxide depletion, and vasculopathy, not specifically an *increased risk for PH following splenectomy* in the same context as thalassemia. Many sickle cell patients are autosplenectomized or undergo early splenectomy, but the PH is a disease complication itself.\nOption B (Incorrect): Warm antibody auto-immune hemolytic anemia is treated with splenectomy in refractory cases, but there is no established association with an increased risk of pulmonary hypertension post-splenectomy. The primary post-splenectomy risk is overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI).\nOption D (Incorrect): Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) is a common indication for splenectomy, but it is not associated with an increased risk of pulmonary hypertension after the procedure. The main post-splenectomy risks are OPSI and thrombosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Indication for Splenectomy | Specific Post-Splenectomy Risk |\n|---|---|---|\n| Thalassemia | Excessive transfusion requirements, symptomatic splenomegaly | High risk of Pulmonary Hypertension |\n| Sickle Cell Disease | Sequestration crisis, hypersplenism (less common now) | OPSI, but PH is a disease complication, not specifically *increased* by splenectomy itself |\n| ITP | Refractory thrombocytopenia | OPSI, thrombosis |\n| AIHA | Refractory hemolysis | OPSI, thrombosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thalassemia + Splenectomy = Pulmonary Hypertension risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-operative echocardiogram is crucial in thalassemia patients undergoing splenectomy to assess for baseline pulmonary hypertension. Intraoperatively, a large, congested spleen may be encountered, often requiring careful dissection due to adhesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThalassaemia International Federation (TIF) Guidelines for the Management of Thalassemia (e.g., 2021 edition). These guidelines recommend careful assessment for pulmonary hypertension before and after splenectomy in thalassemia patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sickle cell disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Warmantibody auto-immune hemolytic anemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thalassemia | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Idiopathic thrombocytopenic purpura | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Treatment for thalassemia involves red blood cell transfusions to maintain a hemoglobin level of >9 ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
