  "answer": "D) Abscesses of the spleen are uncommon, with an incidence of 0.14 to 0.7% based on autopsy findings. They occur more frequently in tropical locations, where they are associated with thrombosed splenic vessels and infarction in patients with sickle cell anemia. Five distinct mechanisms of splenic abscess formation have been described: (a) hematogenous infection; (b) contiguous infection; (c) hemoglobinopathy; (d) immunosuppression, including HIV infection and chemotherapy; and (e) trauma. Presentation frequently is delayed, with most patients enduring symptoms for 16 to 22 days before diagnosis. Clinical manifestations include fever, left upper quadrant pain, leukocytosis, and splenomegaly in about one third of patients. The diagnosis is confirmed by ultrasound or CT scan, which has a 95% sensitivity and specificity. Upon discovery of a splenic abscess, broad-spectrum antibiotics should be started, with adjustment to more specific therapy based on culture results and continuation of treatment for 14 days. Splenectomy is the operation of choice, but percutaneous and open drainage are options for patients who cannot tolerate splenectomy. Percutaneous drainage is successful for patients with unilocular disease. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1255.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Septated spleen? Splenectomy's the scene!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Antibiotics + splenectomy. For a large, septated splenic abscess in an otherwise healthy patient, splenectomy combined with antibiotics is the definitive treatment of choice, as per surgical principles outlined in major textbooks.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSplenic abscesses, especially when large and septated, often require surgical removal of the spleen (splenectomy) due to the organ's friable nature, rich vascularity, and the difficulty in completely eradicating infection from complex, multiloculated collections within its parenchyma. Antibiotics are crucial to control systemic infection, but surgical source control is paramount. The spleen's role in immunity means its removal is not without consequence, but in cases of significant, contained infection, it is often the safest and most effective approach to prevent rupture, sepsis, and recurrence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Antibiotic therapy only) (Incorrect): Antibiotics alone are insufficient for a large, septated abscess, as source control is critical and unlikely to be achieved without intervention.\nOption B (Antibiotics + percutaneous drainage) (Incorrect): Percutaneous drainage is generally successful only for unilocular splenic abscesses. A 'septated' abscess indicates multiple compartments, making complete drainage via percutaneous methods highly unlikely.\nOption C (Antibiotics + partial splenectomy) (Incorrect): Partial splenectomy is not the standard treatment for splenic abscesses. The goal is complete eradication of the infection, which is best achieved by total splenectomy for a large, septated lesion.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Abscess Characteristics | Patient Condition | Recommended Treatment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Unilocular, small | Stable, good surgical candidate | Percutaneous drainage + Antibiotics |\n| Large, Septated | Stable, good surgical candidate | Splenectomy + Antibiotics |\n| Any | Unstable, poor surgical candidate | Open drainage (if percutaneous fails/not feasible) + Antibiotics |\n| Any | Immunocompromised, high risk | Often more aggressive surgical approach (splenectomy) + Antibiotics |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For large, septated splenic abscesses, splenectomy is the treatment of choice.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, a septated splenic abscess would appear as a hypodense, often multiloculated lesion within the spleen, with enhancing walls and internal septations. Intraoperatively, the spleen may be enlarged, inflamed, and adherent to surrounding structures, with a palpable or visible abscess cavity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific society guideline is universally cited for splenic abscess treatment. Standard surgical practice, as outlined in major textbooks like Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th ed., p 1255), recommends splenectomy for large or septated abscesses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Antibiotic therapy only | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Antibiotics + percutaneous drainage | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Antibiotics + partial splenectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Antibiotics + splenectomy | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Abscesses of the spleen are uncommon, with an incidence of 0.14 to 0.7% based on autopsy findings. T** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
