  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Adrenal blood supply: Three sources, know their courses!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Renal artery. The adrenal glands have a rich and complex blood supply, with each gland typically receiving arterial branches from three distinct sources, making precise anatomical knowledge crucial for surgical procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEach adrenal gland is supplied by three main groups of arteries: the superior adrenal arteries, which originate from the inferior phrenic artery; the middle adrenal arteries, which arise directly from the aorta; and the inferior adrenal arteries, which are branches of the renal artery. This extensive vascularization, involving approximately 50 arterioles forming a subcapsular plexus, necessitates meticulous dissection and ligation during adrenalectomy to prevent significant hemorrhage. Understanding these specific origins is fundamental for safe and effective adrenal surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Phrenic artery) (Incorrect): The inferior phrenic artery gives rise to the superior adrenal arteries, not the inferior ones.\nOption B (Splenic artery) (Incorrect): The splenic artery does not directly supply the adrenal glands; it primarily supplies the spleen, pancreas, and parts of the stomach.\nOption D (Aorta) (Incorrect): The aorta directly gives rise to the middle adrenal arteries, not the inferior adrenal arteries.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Artery Group | Originating Vessel |\n|----------------------|---------------------|\n| Superior Adrenal     | Inferior Phrenic Artery |\n| Middle Adrenal       | Aorta               |\n| Inferior Adrenal     | Renal Artery        |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adrenal arteries: Superior from phrenic, Middle from aorta, Inferior from renal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring adrenalectomy, the inferior adrenal artery is typically identified entering the inferior pole of the gland, often arising from the main renal artery or one of its early branches, requiring careful isolation and ligation before gland mobilization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Tumors (2019): These guidelines emphasize detailed preoperative imaging and anatomical understanding to plan surgical approaches and minimize complications, including hemorrhage from the rich adrenal blood supply.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Phrenic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Splenic artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Renal artery | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Aorta | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Each adrenal gland is supplied by three groups of vessels—the superior adrenal arteries derived from** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
