  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Steroids: They break down muscle and bone, but build up fat (in the wrong places)!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B is the correct answer because glucocorticoids primarily *increase* lipolysis, especially in peripheral adipose tissue, while simultaneously promoting fat redistribution to central areas. Therefore, 'decreased lipolysis' is not an effect of these hormones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGlucocorticoids are potent catabolic hormones with widespread metabolic effects. In adipose tissue, they stimulate hormone-sensitive lipase, leading to the breakdown of triglycerides into free fatty acids and glycerol, thus increasing lipolysis. This provides substrates for gluconeogenesis. While they can promote fat deposition in specific areas (e.g., truncal obesity, buffalo hump), their direct action on peripheral fat is often lipolytic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Decreased muscle protein synthesis is a well-known catabolic effect of glucocorticoids, leading to muscle wasting and weakness.\nOption C (Incorrect): Inhibition of bone formation is a significant effect, as glucocorticoids suppress osteoblast activity and promote osteoclast activity, contributing to osteoporosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Increased cardiac output is an effect, mediated by enhanced vascular responsiveness to catecholamines, increased blood volume, and direct myocardial effects.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| System/Metabolism | Glucocorticoid Effect |\n|---|---|\n| Protein | Decreased synthesis, increased catabolism |\n| Fat | Increased lipolysis (peripheral), increased lipogenesis (central) |\n| Bone | Decreased formation, increased resorption |\n| Cardiovascular | Increased cardiac output, increased vascular tone |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Glucocorticoids are catabolic for protein and bone, but complex for fat and glucose.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, chronic glucocorticoid use can manifest as osteopenia/osteoporosis on X-rays or DEXA scans. Intraoperatively, patients on chronic steroids may exhibit poor wound healing, thin skin, and increased susceptibility to infection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline: Glucocorticoid-Induced Osteoporosis (2017). It recommends screening for osteoporosis and prophylactic treatment in patients on long-term glucocorticoid therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Decreased muscle protein synthesis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Decreased lipolysis | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Inhibition of bone formation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Increased cardiac output | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Glucocorticoids have important functions in intermediary metabolism but also affect connective tissu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
