  "question": "Thyroxine (T4) is composed of",
  "options": {
    "A": "Two Diiodotyrosine (DIT) molecules",
    "B": "One Diiodotyrosine (DIT) molecules and two monoiodohyrosin (MIT) molecules",
    "C": "Four monoiodohyrosin (MIT) molecules",
    "D": "None of the above"
  },
  "answer": "A) The synthesis of thyroid hormone consists of several steps. The first, iodide trapping, involves active (ATP-dependent) transport of iodide across the basement membrane of the thyrocyte via an intrinsic membrane protein, the sodium/iodine (Na+/I–) symporter. Thyroglobulin (Tg) is a large (660 kDa) glycoprotein, which is present in thyroid follicles and has four tyrosyl residues. The second step in thyroid hormone synthesis involves oxidation of iodide to iodine and iodination of tyrosine residues on Tg, to form monoiodotyrosines (MIT) and diiodotyrosines (DIT). Both processes are catalyzed by thyroid peroxidase (TPO). A recently identified protein, pendrin, is thought to mediate iodine efflux at the apical membrane. The third step leads to coupling of two DIT molecules to form tetra-iodothyronine or thyroxine (T4), and one DIT molecule with one MIT molecule to form 3,5,3’-triiodothyronine (T3) or 3,3’,5’–triiodothyronine reverse (rT3). (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1348.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 T4: Double the DIT, double the power!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThyroxine (T4) is correctly identified as being composed of two Diiodotyrosine (DIT) molecules. This is a fundamental biochemical step in thyroid hormone synthesis, where two DIT molecules are coupled together on the thyroglobulin scaffold to form T4.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe synthesis of thyroid hormones, T3 and T4, occurs within the thyroid follicular cells on a large glycoprotein called thyroglobulin (Tg). After iodide is trapped and oxidized, tyrosine residues on Tg are iodinated by thyroid peroxidase (TPO) to form monoiodotyrosines (MIT) and diiodotyrosines (DIT). The crucial step for T4 formation involves the coupling of two DIT molecules. This coupling reaction, also catalyzed by TPO, results in the formation of tetra-iodothyronine (T4), which is then stored within the colloid until released into circulation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): One Diiodotyrosine (DIT) molecules and two monoiodohyrosin (MIT) molecules. This combination is incorrect for T4; Triiodothyronine (T3) is formed by the coupling of one DIT and one MIT molecule, not two MITs.\nOption C (Incorrect): Four monoiodohyrosin (MIT) molecules. MITs are precursors with only one iodine atom; coupling four MITs would not yield T4, which requires four iodine atoms derived from DITs.\nOption D (Incorrect): None of the above. Option A correctly describes the composition of T4.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone/Precursor | Composition | Iodine Atoms | Role |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Monoiodotyrosine (MIT) | Tyrosine + 1 Iodine | 1 | Precursor for T3/T4 |\n| Diiodotyrosine (DIT) | Tyrosine + 2 Iodine | 2 | Precursor for T3/T4 |\n| Triiodothyronine (T3) | 1 DIT + 1 MIT | 3 | Active thyroid hormone |\n| Thyroxine (T4) | 2 DIT | 4 | Prohormone, main thyroid secretion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: T4 is \"two DITs,\" T3 is \"DIT + MIT.\"\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the thyroid gland appears as a homogeneous, hyperechoic structure. Iodine uptake scans (e.g., I-123 or I-131) demonstrate the functional capacity of the thyroid to trap iodide, a prerequisite for DIT formation, but directly visualizing hormone synthesis components like DITs is not possible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations on the diagnosis and management of thyroid diseases, including aspects related to thyroid hormone physiology and replacement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Two Diiodotyrosine (DIT) molecules | ✅ Correct |\n| B | One Diiodotyrosine (DIT) molecules and two monoiodohyrosin (MIT) molecules | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Four monoiodohyrosin (MIT) molecules | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The synthesis of thyroid hormone consists of several steps. The first, iodide trapping, involves act** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
