  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't confuse your MENs, or your patients will be in a mess!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Pheochromocytoma. This is because pheochromocytomas are a hallmark feature of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2) syndrome, not MEN1. MEN1 syndrome is characterized by tumors of the parathyroid, pituitary, and pancreas/duodenum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMEN1 syndrome, also known as Wermer's syndrome, is an autosomal dominant disorder primarily affecting the parathyroid glands, pituitary gland, and pancreatic neuroendocrine cells. Primary hyperparathyroidism (PHPT) is the most common and earliest manifestation, occurring in 80-100% of patients. Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors (PNETs), such as gastrinomas (50%) and insulinomas (10-15%), are also frequent. Pituitary adenomas, particularly prolactinomas (10-50%), represent the most common pituitary lesion in MEN1 patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Gastrinomas are a common manifestation of MEN1, occurring in about 50% of patients, often multiple and metastatic.\nOption B (Incorrect): Insulinomas are seen in 10-15% of MEN1 cases, representing another type of pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor.\nOption C (Incorrect): Prolactinomas are the most common pituitary lesion in MEN1, affecting 10-50% of patients.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Key Features |\n|---|---|\n| MEN1 (Wermer's) | Parathyroid hyperplasia/adenoma, Pancreatic NETs (gastrinoma, insulinoma), Pituitary adenoma |\n| MEN2A (Sipple's) | Medullary thyroid carcinoma, Pheochromocytoma, Primary hyperparathyroidism |\n| MEN2B | Medullary thyroid carcinoma, Pheochromocytoma, Mucosal neuromas, Marfanoid habitus |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MEN1 is 3 P's: Parathyroid, Pituitary, Pancreas.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for MEN1 often includes neck ultrasound for parathyroid glands, abdominal CT/MRI for pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors, and pituitary MRI for adenomas. Intraoperatively, surgeons may find multiple enlarged parathyroid glands and often multiple small pancreatic lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline (2012): \"Diagnosis and Management of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 1 and Type 2 Syndromes.\" It provides comprehensive recommendations for screening, diagnosis, and management of MEN1-associated tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Gastrinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Insulinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Prolactinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pheochromocytoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Pheochromocytomas are seen in patients with MEN2 syndrome. PHPT is the earliest and most common mani** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
