  "answer": "A) Sialadenitis, nausea, and vomiting are symptoms reported to occur with as little as 50 mCi of 131I. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1367, and Table 38-4.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let 131I make your patients sour; treat their salivary glands with power!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nSialadenitis is a well-known and common complication of radioactive iodine (131I) therapy for thyroid cancer, occurring due to the active uptake of iodine by the salivary glands. This leads to inflammation and dysfunction of these glands, even at moderate doses like 100 mCi.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe salivary glands, particularly the parotid and submandibular glands, possess sodium-iodide symporters (NIS) similar to thyroid follicular cells, allowing them to actively concentrate iodine. When 131I is administered, these glands absorb the radioactive isotope, leading to local radiation damage. This damage manifests as inflammation, swelling, pain, and xerostomia (dry mouth), collectively known as sialadenitis. The severity is dose-dependent but can occur even with moderate doses like 100 mCi.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Cerebral edema is not a reported complication of 131I treatment. While severe hypothyroidism can rarely cause myxedema coma with cerebral edema, this is distinct from direct 131I toxicity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bone marrow suppression is a potential, but less common and typically later, complication of 131I, especially with higher cumulative doses. Sialadenitis is a more immediate and frequently reported side effect at the 100 mCi dose.\nOption D (Incorrect): Vocal cord paralysis is typically a complication of surgical injury to the recurrent laryngeal nerve during thyroidectomy, not a direct effect of radioactive iodine therapy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication | Mechanism | Management |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sialadenitis | 131I uptake by salivary glands via NIS, causing radiation damage | Hydration, sialogogues (lemon drops), massage, NSAIDs |\n| Nausea/Vomiting | Direct gastric irritation, central effects | Antiemetics (e.g., ondansetron) |\n| Xerostomia | Chronic radiation damage to salivary glands | Hydration, artificial saliva, pilocarpine |\n| Bone Marrow Suppression | Systemic radiation exposure, affecting hematopoietic stem cells | Monitoring CBC, rarely transfusions or growth factors for severe cases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Sialadenitis is the most common acute side effect of 131I due to salivary gland iodine uptake.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a post-treatment whole-body scan (WBS) after 131I administration, physiological uptake will be seen in the salivary glands, stomach, bladder, and bowel. In cases of sialadenitis, ultrasound might show enlarged, edematous salivary glands.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2024). These guidelines recommend considering 131I for remnant ablation or adjuvant therapy in intermediate to high-risk patients, and discuss potential side effects including sialadenitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sialadenitis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Cerebral edema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bone marrow suppression | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Vocal cord paralysis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Sialadenitis, nausea, and vomiting are symptoms reported to occur with as little as 50 mCi of 131I. ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
