  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pituitary's the boss, making Cushing's disease the most common cause!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Pituitary adenoma. This is because the most common cause of endogenous Cushing's syndrome is Cushing's disease, which is specifically caused by an ACTH-producing pituitary adenoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCushing's syndrome encompasses any cause of hypercortisolism, but when referring to endogenous causes, a pituitary adenoma is the predominant etiology. These adenomas secrete excessive ACTH, leading to bilateral adrenal hyperplasia and subsequent overproduction of cortisol. This specific pathway, known as Cushing's disease, accounts for approximately 70% of all endogenous Cushing's syndrome cases, making it the most frequent underlying mechanism. Understanding this distinction between Cushing's syndrome (the clinical state) and Cushing's disease (the pituitary-driven etiology) is crucial for diagnosis and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Adrenal adenoma) (Incorrect): While an adrenal adenoma can cause Cushing's syndrome (ACTH-independent), it accounts for only about 10% of endogenous cases, making it less common than a pituitary adenoma.\nOption B (Adrenal hyperplasia) (Incorrect): Adrenal hyperplasia is often a consequence of excessive ACTH stimulation (e.g., from a pituitary adenoma or ectopic ACTH). Primary adrenal hyperplasia is a less common cause of Cushing's syndrome than pituitary adenomas.\nOption C (Ectopic ACTH production) (Incorrect): Ectopic ACTH production, typically from neuroendocrine tumors, accounts for about 10% of endogenous Cushing's syndrome cases, making it significantly less common than pituitary adenomas.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cause of Endogenous Cushing's Syndrome | Etiology | Prevalence |\n|---------------------------------------|----------|------------|\n| Pituitary Adenoma (Cushing's Disease) | ACTH-dependent | ~70%       |\n| Adrenal Adenoma/Carcinoma             | ACTH-independent | ~10-20%    |\n| Ectopic ACTH Production               | ACTH-dependent | ~10%       |\n| Primary Adrenal Hyperplasia           | ACTH-independent | Rare       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cushing's disease (pituitary adenoma) is the most common cause of endogenous Cushing's syndrome.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a pituitary adenoma causing Cushing's disease may appear as a small (often microadenoma, <10mm) enhancing lesion within the sella turcica. Intraoperatively, during transsphenoidal surgery, the surgeon would identify and resect this adenoma, often observing a change in adrenal gland appearance (hyperplasia) post-operatively as ACTH levels normalize.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline (2008, updated 2015) for the Diagnosis of Cushing's Syndrome recommends initial screening tests for hypercortisolism, followed by tests to differentiate ACTH-dependent from ACTH-independent causes, with pituitary MRI being a key step in ACTH-dependent cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adrenal adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Adrenal hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ectopic ACTH production | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pituitary adenoma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Although a bit confusing, the most common cause of Cushing’s syndrome is Cushing’s disease. Cushing’** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
