  "question": "Which of the following is one of the most common locations for orbital fractures?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Superior",
    "B": "Laterosuperior",
    "C": "Lateral",
    "D": "Medial"
  },
  "answer": "D) Orbital fractures may involve the orbital roof, floor, or lateral or medial walls. The most common orbital fracture is the orbital floor blow-out fracture caused by direct pressure to the globe and sudden increase in intraorbital pressure. Because the medial floor and inferior medial wall are made of the thinnest bone, fractures occur most frequently at these locations. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1671.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the eye takes a hit, the medial wall's the first to split!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Medial. This is because the medial wall and orbital floor are anatomically the thinnest bony structures of the orbit, making them most susceptible to fracture from sudden increases in intraorbital pressure.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOrbital blow-out fractures typically result from blunt trauma to the globe, which rapidly increases intraorbital pressure. This pressure is then transmitted to the orbital walls. The medial wall, particularly the lamina papyracea, and the orbital floor are composed of the thinnest bone, making them the weakest points. Consequently, these areas are the most common sites for fractures, allowing orbital contents to herniate into adjacent sinuses (ethmoid for medial, maxillary for floor).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Superior) (Incorrect): The orbital roof is generally thicker and less prone to isolated blow-out fractures, though it can be involved in more extensive trauma.\nOption B (Laterosuperior) (Incorrect): This area is not recognized as a primary common site for isolated orbital blow-out fractures.\nOption C (Lateral) (Incorrect): The lateral orbital wall is robust, formed by the zygoma and greater wing of the sphenoid, making it less susceptible to isolated blow-out fractures.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Orbital Wall | Relative Thickness | Commonality of Isolated Fracture |\n|---|---|---|\n| Medial | Thinnest | Most Common (Lamina papyracea) |\n| Inferior (Floor) | Thin | Very Common |\n| Superior (Roof) | Thicker | Less Common |\n| Lateral | Thickest | Least Common |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thin bone breaks first; think medial wall and orbital floor for blow-out fractures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, an orbital floor blow-out fracture often presents with the 'teardrop sign,' indicating herniation of orbital fat and/or inferior rectus muscle into the maxillary sinus. Medial wall fractures may show herniation into the ethmoid air cells.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Preferred Practice Pattern: Orbital Fractures (2021). Recommends CT imaging for diagnosis and outlines indications for surgical repair based on symptoms and fracture size.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Superior | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Laterosuperior | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lateral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Medial | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Orbital fractures may involve the orbital roof, floor, or lateral or medial walls. The most common o** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
