  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A facial birthmark can be a window to the brain's vascular secrets.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Leptomeningeal vascular anomalies. The child described, likely presenting with a facial port-wine stain (capillary malformation), is at increased risk for Sturge-Weber syndrome, which characteristically involves vascular malformations of the leptomeninges.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSturge-Weber syndrome is a neurocutaneous disorder characterized by a facial capillary malformation (port-wine stain), typically in the trigeminal nerve distribution, ipsilateral leptomeningeal angiomatosis, and ocular involvement such as glaucoma. The leptomeningeal vascular anomalies, often referred to as angiomas, can lead to seizures, developmental delay, and hemiparesis due to chronic ischemia and calcification of the underlying cerebral cortex. The port-wine stain itself is a persistent capillary malformation that darkens and thickens over time, and its presence, especially in the V1 distribution, should prompt evaluation for intracranial involvement.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Brain aneurysm) (Incorrect): While Sturge-Weber involves intracranial vascular anomalies, the characteristic finding is leptomeningeal angiomatosis, not typically brain aneurysms. Aneurysms are distinct vascular lesions.\nOption B (Hepatic hemangioma) (Incorrect): Hepatic hemangiomas are common benign liver tumors, but they are not a characteristic association of Sturge-Weber syndrome. They are more commonly seen in syndromes like Kasabach-Merritt or PHACE syndrome.\nOption D (Visceral aneurysm) (Incorrect): Sturge-Weber syndrome primarily affects the face, brain, and eye. It is not typically associated with widespread visceral aneurysms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Key Features | Associated Anomalies |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Sturge-Weber Syndrome** | Facial port-wine stain (V1 distribution) | Leptomeningeal angiomatosis, glaucoma, seizures, developmental delay |\n| **Klippel-Trenaunay Syndrome** | Capillary malformation, venous malformation, limb hypertrophy | Lymphatic malformations, phlebectasia, bleeding |\n| **Osler-Weber-Rendu (HHT)** | Recurrent epistaxis, mucocutaneous telangiectasias | Arteriovenous malformations (AVMs) in lungs, brain, liver, GI tract |\n| **PHACE Syndrome** | Posterior fossa malformations, Hemangiomas (large facial), Arterial anomalies, Coarctation of aorta/Cardiac defects, Eye abnormalities | Large segmental hemangiomas, cerebrovascular anomalies, structural brain defects |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Port-wine stain on the face = think Sturge-Weber and look for brain/eye issues.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, leptomeningeal angiomatosis in Sturge-Weber syndrome appears as gyriform enhancement, often with associated cortical atrophy and calcifications (tram-track calcifications on CT) in the ipsilateral cerebral hemisphere.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) 2015 Guideline: Management of Sturge-Weber Syndrome. Recommends early screening for glaucoma and neurological complications, and consideration of prophylactic anti-epileptic drugs in some cases.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Brain aneurysm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Hepatic hemangioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Leptomeningeal vascular anomalies | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Visceral aneurysm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) This is a child with Sturge-Weber syndrome. Capillary malformations (CMs) are pink-red macular vascu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
