  "id": 120975,
  "question": "Which of the following tests of function in an elderly patient can be used to predict the time to recover after surgery?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Hand grip strength",
    "B": "Timed up and go test",
    "C": "Functional reach test",
    "D": "All of the above"
  },
  "answer": "D) It is important that a thorough preoperative evaluation include an accurate assessment of the functional status of surgical candidates as well as their cognitive level of functioning. This ensures that operative intervention will not significantly impair the quality of life of an elderly surgical candidate. The ability to withstand the stress of surgical interventions is dependent on functional reserve and ability to build an appropriate response to perioperative stress. The ability to perform activities of daily living (ADL) such as feeding, dressing, bathing, and toileting have been correlated with postoperative morbidity and mortality. Preoperative functional assessment can be measured by hand grip strength, timed up and go, and functional reach tests. All of these tests independently predicted better recovery and shorter time to recover ADLafter major surgery. In addition, these tests provide an accurate assessment of a patientís muscle mass, nutritional status, coordination, gait speed, balance, and mobility. Proper functional assessment will accurately predict rehabilitation needs, estimate biologic reserve, and even signal complications. (See Schwartz 9th ed., p 1714.)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Assess function pre-op; it's the crystal ball for recovery.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, \"All of the above.\" This is because hand grip strength, timed up and go test, and functional reach test are all validated tools used in preoperative assessment to predict an elderly patient's recovery time after surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThese functional tests are crucial for assessing an elderly patient's functional reserve, which directly correlates with their ability to withstand surgical stress and recover postoperatively. Hand grip strength reflects muscle mass and nutritional status, while the timed up and go test evaluates gait speed, balance, and mobility. The functional reach test assesses balance and fall risk. Collectively, these tests provide a comprehensive picture of a patient's physical capacity, predicting the time to recover activities of daily living (ADL) and signaling potential rehabilitation needs or complications, thereby guiding surgical planning and patient counseling.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hand grip strength is a valid and independent predictor of postoperative recovery, but it is not the only test mentioned that can do so.\nOption B (Incorrect): The timed up and go test is an effective measure of mobility and balance, independently predicting recovery, but it is not the sole test for this purpose.\nOption C (Incorrect): The functional reach test is a useful assessment of balance and fall risk, independently predicting recovery, but it is not the only test available.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Primary Focus | Predictive Value |\n|---|---|---|\n| Hand Grip Strength | Muscle mass, nutritional status | Postoperative recovery, ADL recovery time |\n| Timed Up and Go Test | Gait speed, balance, mobility | Postoperative recovery, ADL recovery time |\n| Functional Reach Test | Balance, fall risk | Postoperative recovery, ADL recovery time |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Preoperative functional assessment in the elderly predicts recovery, not just risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not imaging, these functional tests reveal a patient's 'physiologic age' and frailty status, which can guide intraoperative decisions regarding anesthetic depth, fluid management, and surgical approach to minimize stress on a patient with limited reserve.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons National Surgical Quality Improvement Program (ACS NSQIP) guidelines (ongoing updates) recommend comprehensive geriatric assessment, including functional status, for elderly surgical candidates to optimize outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hand grip strength | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Timed up and go test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Functional reach test | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | All of the above | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) It is important that a thorough preoperative evaluation include an accurate assessment of the functi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Schwartz's Principles of Surgery (9th Ed)**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
